<HEADLINE>All men relate back to `Adam'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224833</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVERY man on Earth today is related, linked by a Y chromosome to a common
ancestor who lived about 190,000 years ago, a new study suggests.
This so-called ancestral Adam was among many males who lived before
anatomically modern humans evolved but he's the only one purported in the study
to have a genetic legacy that persists today.
``We would all have a Y chromosome that existed in the same guy,'' said Mr
Michael Hammer, an assistant research scientist at the University of Arizona,
whose study appeared yesterday in the journal Nature.
The Y chromosome is one of the 24 kinds of microscopic threads that hold genes.
Unlike the other chromosomes, it is passed only from father to son.
Mr Hammer compared the detailed makeup of a tiny piece of the Y chromosome
sampled from eight Africans of various backgrounds, two Australians, three
Japanese, and two Europeans. The idea was to look for how varied that piece was
among the different ethnic groups and then calculate how long it would take for
evolution to produce the diversity he found.
The results suggest that all men alive today could trace their Y chromosomes
back for about 188,000 years to the same person.
Mr Hammer said his findings also suggest a single place of origin for modern
humans. The findings don't indicate where but Africa is a good bet, he said.
The study found evidence that modern-day humans resulted from a relatively
small breeding population over the past 200,000 or so years. The group was so
small that it is hard to believe its members could have been spread out over
more than one continent, Mr Hammer said.
</TEXT>
