<HEADLINE>Court told constable assaulted teenager</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224834</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YOUTH told a court yesterday how a policeman banged his head against the
inside of a police van.
It was alleged at Perth Sheriff Court that Constable Graham Howie, 31, also
grabbed Richard Hind, 17, by the neck and pulled him off his bicycle.
Richard Hind told the court Mr Howie came up to him in a street where there
were a group of youngsters ``mucking about''.
As he was pulled off the bike, he claimed said he pleaded with the constable:
``Get off me, you're choking me.''
He claimed Mr Howie banged his head off the side of the van.
Richard, of Ainslie Gardens, Perth, admitted that he struggled but said he
should not have been arrested.
Mr Howie denies assualting the youth in Gowans Terrace, Perth, on October 27
last year.
He also denies assaulting Mr Daniel Ferns, 19, on Octoer 23 last year.
Mr Ferns claimed he had been left with marks on his neck after the constable
grabbed him at his house.
Mr Ferns, of Strathtay Road, Perth, said Mr Howie and a policewoman came to his
door just after midnight and wanted to speak to him about an assault on a
police officer.
After he said would not talk to them at that time, he was told he was being
detained and that Mr Howie took a hold of his wrist.
Mr Ferns said he was then pinned to the wall.
Mr Howie had originally faced five charges of assault and four charges of
breach of the peace when his trial started on Wednesday.
During yesterday's proceedings, the constable, whose address was given as c/o
Tayside Police headquarters, Dundee, was cleared of three charges of breach of
the peace and two of assault.
Sheriff David Sutherland adjourned the trial until December 18.
</TEXT>
