<HEADLINE>Sister blamed for homosexual report.    MP sues over Goa bed story</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224835</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sister of Tory MP David Ashby, who is suing for libel over a newspaper
allegation that he was a homosexual, was out to destroy him, the High Court in
London heard yesterday.
Mrs Lynne Garling and her solicitor husband, Victor, made anonymous phone calls
to the Sunday Times in January 1994 which led to the newspaper's story that the
55-year-old MP had shared a bed with a male friend on a holiday in Goa the
previous November, said Mr Geoffrey Shaw, QC.
He referred Mr Justice Morland and a jury to the article in which Mr Ashby is
quoted as saying that Mrs Garling was a ``vicious, sick woman motivated solely
by malice and who despises me''.
Mr Shaw said Mrs Garling believed the MP for North West Leicestershire was
having an affair with a Dr.Ciaran Kilduff and had often spoken of exposing him
to the media.
When he was in Goa - alone - she had made call after call to try to track him
down and gather evidence against him.
The calls to the newspaper, alleging that Mr Ashby was having a homosexual
affair with Dr Kilduff and that he had left his wife for him, could only have
come from Mrs Garling and her husband, even though they denied it.
``It certainly seems she was out to destroy him,'' said Mr Shaw. He believed
her objective was to force her brother to resign as an MP.
Mr Ashby is claiming damages over the January 1994 article which, he says,
alleged he was a practising homosexual who had misled his wife, Silvana - from
whom he separated two months before it appeared - about the nature of his
sexuality.
It also meant he had lied to the public about having an affair with Dr Kilduff
during a trip to France early in 1994, and was a hypocrite in emphasising the
importance of the family in his last election address.
Times Newspapers Ltd, and former Sunday Times editor, Mr Andrew Neil, deny
libel, although they accept Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa.
Mr Shaw said their defence of justification included the assertion that Mr
Ashby was and is carrying on a homosexual relationship with Dr Kilduff.
Mr Shaw said it was clear that Mrs Garling had ``hated'' her brother since
early 1993 at the latest.
He dismissed a letter from the Sunday Times to Mr Ashby which denied that Mrs
Garling was the original source of the information.
``We say, of course she was.''
The hearing was adjourned until today, when Mr Shaw will continue his opening.
Mr Ashby is not likely to go into the witness box until Monday.
</TEXT>
