<HEADLINE>Car towed from collapsing bridge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224837</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN spoke yesterday of her shock at being stranded on a bridge when flood
waters immobilised her car, shortly before it collapsed and two teenagers
drowned when their car plunged into the River Kelvin.
Mrs Margaret Brownlie, 43, told a fatal accident inquiry at Glasgow Sheriff
Court, that she was going to pick up her husband from work on the afternoon of
Sunday, December ll last.
Because of severe flooding, she asked her son Stewart to go with her, and his
wife and baby came along, also in the car was her 85-year-old mother.
Mrs Brownlie, of Gartshore Crescent, Twechar, Strathclyde, told Mrs Margaret
Porter, leading the evidence, that as she approached Gavell Bridge there was
water across the road and in nearby fields.
She said: ``We decided to go on very, very slowly. when a deluge of water
washed over the car and the engine cut out.
My son jumped out of the car and the water came in. Stewart went to the back of
the car and tried to push it across the bridge but it would not move.''
She told the inquiry that the water was up to six-foot Stewart's waist and a
man standing at the bridge wall shouted: ``You had better get them off the
bridge, it's going to go.'' Her car was eventually towed off the bridge by a
man who attached a rope to his van.
Mrs Brownlie was giving evidence at the inquiry into the deaths of John Furay,
l7, of The Strone, St John's Way, and James McClement, l7, of Kelvin View, both
Kilsyth.
They drowned when the red VW Polo car being driven by John plunged from the
collapsed bridge.
A third youth, James Gibson, l7, of Differ Avenue, Twechar, kicked the car door
open, jumped into the river, and managed to reach safety.
Mrs Brownlie said she should never have been allowed to go on to the bridge
that afternoon and that it should have been closed.
The inquiry before Sheriff Bruce Kerr QC, continues.
</TEXT>
