<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tories seize on Labour criticism of Brown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224838</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CABINET Ministers yesterday delightedly leapt on evidence of discontent within
the Shadow Cabinet about the role of Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown which
forced Mr Tony Blair into a declaration that Mr Brown had his ``101% support''.
There had been murmurs that some Shadow Ministers were unhappy about the
intervention of Mr Brown into their departmental responsibilities.
A meeting of Labour back benchers was mostly critical of the complaints, and Mr
Blair let it be known that he was right behind Mr Brown, whose influence rivals
that of deputy leader John Prescott.
However, he also reassured Shadow Cabinet members that they will be involved
from the start in any tactical or policy decisions involving their areas of
responsibility taken by the team headed by Mr Brown, which deals with
day-to-day reactions to events.
The Prime Minister sought to cast doubts on the Blair-Brown solidarity in the
Commons. He said: ``The 1% I am sure is correct, the 100% I am not so sure of.''
Earlier, Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke said he was anxious to
protect Mr Brown against the Shadow Foreign Secretary, Mr Robin Cook, or anyone
else who wanted to take him on.
He said the Government wanted Mr Brown kept in his job and also the Shadow Home
Secretary, Mr Jack Straw.
Mr Brown's role goes beyond that of Treasury affairs and he has ruffled some
colleagues' feathers for not consulting them sufficiently, in their view.
A senior Labour official said: ``Gordon is in charge of a committee which meets
daily to discuss news management and that sometimes means decisions are taken
to promote one idea or another or respond to events as they happen.
``That is special responsibility and it sometimes means ranging into other
peoples' territory.
``Some of them feel on the detail of the Budget strategy they were not
consulted properly.
``To that extent, there will hopefully be much closer co-operation right across
the board when things are being planned.''
Some Shadow Cabinet members are thought to be unhappy at not being more closely
consulted about Mr Brown's announcement on a lower-band income tax target of
10p, which has been attacked by other parties and some independent experts as
not the most efficient way of helping the poor and denounced by the Government
as ``a gimmick.''
As well as giving Mr Brown his full backing, it is understood Mr Blair has
warned dissatisfied colleagues that dissatisfaction of this kind should be
settled within the Shadow Cabinet and not leaked outside where it could be
presented as a damaging row which neither the party in the country nor the
public would understand.
One Shadow Cabinet member said ``Gordon has been making assumptions about
certain things and people were getting sick of it, but I don't think there will
be a repeat in future.''
</TEXT>
