<HEADLINE>Sentence deferred on doctor who stole drugs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DOCTOR who fed his addiction with drugs stolen from the practice where he was
a partner has had his sentence deferred for six months.
Sheriff James Smith, at Kirkcudbright Sheriff Court yesterday, was told the
General Medical Council had started proceedings to determine Colin Malone's
professional future.
Sheriff Smith said he would defer sentence until the medical council reached a
decision.
Malone's agent, Mr John Innes, said the doctor had not taken drugs since the
offence came to light. He was making a determined and disciplined response to
his problem and had sought medical help.
Mr Innes said the problem had been brought on by a viral illness and that
Malone had suffered an undiagnosed depression caused by an increasing workload.
Malone admitted stealing 380 drug injections over a four-month period while
working in a Dalbeattie practice.
Malone, 32, of Rounall Avenue, Dalbeattie, pleaded guilty to having pretended
to four pharmacists that he required quantities of the controlled drugs
diamorphine, cyclimorph, and pethidine for use in connection with the treatment
of patients in the course of his business.
He induced the pharmacists to supply him with the controlled drugs and
thereafter appropriated them for his own use.
Procurator-fiscal Frank Walkingshaw said the offence came to light when the
principal of the chemists in Dalbeattie informed police.
The drugs are used mainly in the treatment of pain and in cases of terminal
illness.
Mr Innes, for Malone, produced testimonials which he said were evidence of the
high regard in which colleagues and patients held Malone and said preliminaries
to the hearing by the General Medical Council were proceeding.
``The next month or so will decide his future in the profession,'' Mr Innes
said.
</TEXT>
