<HEADLINE>Drink driver jailed after death crash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A VAN driver who killed a woman in a crash was jailed yesterday for three years
at Edinburgh Sheriff Court.
David Scott, 25, had been found guilty of driving carelessly with
one-and-a-half times the alcohol limit in his blood and causing the death of
Mrs Jennifer McGeachie, 49.
The sentence was welcomed by Mrs McGeachie's husband, John, 54, who was in
court to hear the outcome of the case.
``He got what he deserved, he should not have been drinking and driving,'' said
Mr McGeachie, of Woodside Drive, Penicuik.
``But at the end of the day this doesn't change anything, it will not bring my
wife back.''
The jury heard that Scott had been drinking beer and playing pool in a
Gorebridge public house on January 8.
Scott, a plumber, of Powdermill Brae, Gorebridge, later drove his van and
crashed with Mrs McGeachie's Mini at Cockpen Crossroads, Bonnyrigg.
Mrs McGeachie, an auxiliary nurse, was pulled from the wreckage after the crash
but was found to be dead.
Defence solicitor George More said Scott was ``full of remorse and regret''.
``He has had great difficulty coming to terms with what he did, it is something
that is with him every day of his life.''
Scott was a young man of previous good character who had made a ``dreadful
error of judgment'' and was very well aware of the consequences of his mistake.
Scott told the jury how he came to a bend at about 40-45mph and braked gently.
The back of the van began to slide away from him and he braked harder but the
van went to the other side of the road and hit banking.
Scott could not remember anything until after the crash with Mrs McGeachie's
car.
Police officers said that if Scott's van had been going at a safe speed, he
would have been able to stop before the crossroads.
</TEXT>
