<DOCNO>GH951124-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dealer tried to `get evidence'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DRUGS dealer wrote a letter from his prison cell asking a friend for help in
providing evidence for a police corruption probe, a court heard yesterday.
The High Court in Aberdeen was told that convicted drugs trafficker Ronald
Cormack wrote to an associate, Mr Gavin Clark, seeking help in corroborating
information for an investigation by officers from Strathclyde Police into
Grampian Police.
Details of the letter were revealed at the trial of Grampian Police constable
Neil Cooper, 36, who denies two charges of attempting to defeat the ends of
justice and one charge of corruption.
On the corruption charge, the Crown alleges that Mr Cooper accepted more than
#6000 from Cormack as a reward for providing information to him about Grampian
Police surveillance operations on him during 1994.
Mr Cooper has lodged a special defence against the corruption charge,
incriminating another Grampian police officer, Mr James Grimmer.
Charges of attempting to defeat the ends of justice relate to Mr Cooper's
investigations into an assault and a separate housebreaking, both of which are
said to have involved Cormack.
Mr Cooper's defence counsel, Mr Kevin Drummond QC, read Cormack's letter
yesterday during cross-examination of Chief Superintendent Ronald Coutts, head
of Grampian Police CID.
In the letter, Cormack says to Mr Clark: ``Expect to have a visit from the feds
investigating police corruption. Don't worry, you'll have no trouble coming to
you but you can help us by corroborating certain things for us.''
The trial, before Lord Macfadyen, continues.
</TEXT>
