<DOCNO>GH951124-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cardinal calls for anti-drugs `spearhead'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Roman Catholic leader Cardinal Thomas Winning last night called on
the Government to appoint a Minister responsible for co-ordinating the fight
against drugs.
He was speaking at a poignant service in Glasgow's St Alphonsus Church in the
East End attended by some of the families of the 93 people who have died as a
result of drugs in Strathclyde this year.
They were joined for the candlelit service by friends and relatives of other
victims of drug abuse.
The ecumenical service was organised by the Glasgow Association of Family
Support Groups which called for unity in the fight against drugs.
In his address, Cardinal Winning said that in the face of a worsening epidemic
of drug-associated deaths there was a need for a co-ordinated attack.
``The appointment of a Government Minister to create a national strategy
heavily concerned with enabling local people to spearhead the fight back should
be a matter for urgent consideration.''
There were, he said, an estimated 10,000 drug injectors in the West of Scotland
and one in 10 of all 10 to 13-year-olds experimented with drugs.
He said whatever the causes of drugs misuse it would be foolish to deny that
the problem was a symptom of spiritual poverty.
``Drug addicts are human beings. If compassion is to come alive among us it
will only do so when we see the drug addict as a person with a problem rather
than a problem in the shape of a person.
``Tonight, perhaps, and tomorrow, it will be somebody else's child, somebody
else's tears. Your pain, your witness here this evening in this Church is a
grim warning.''
</TEXT>
