<DOCNO>GH951124-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ferguson to be freed from jail on licence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224851</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNCAN Ferguson walks free from prison today, with half his three-month
sentence still hanging over him.
Ferguson, 23, is being freed from Glasgow's Barlinnie jail having served half
the sentence he received for headbutting fellow player John McStay.
However, the remaining half of his sentence could be reactivated if he falls
foul of the law before the sentence expiry date - in his case, 45 days' time.
In any event, he may not be able to resume his playing career until mid-January.
He still has 11 matches to serve out of a 12-match ban imposed by the Scottish
FA, although his present club, Everton, is seeking a judicial review - arguing
he is being punished twice over.
Ferguson will be one of at least 100 prisoners freed from Barlinnie early today
- Friday is traditionally a busy day for releases.
He is unlikely, however, to speak to the media waiting outside the grim
Victorian-built jail designed to hold 900 but now holding 1200 prisoners.
A prison service spokesman said it was likely that he would leave by a car from
the ``sterile area'' inside the gates.
Everton yesterday declined to discuss arrangements for his release but it was
thought likely he would be picked up either by club officials or members of his
family.
Ferguson made football history by becoming the first professional to be jailed
for an on-the-field assault on a fellow player.
It was his fourth conviction and Ferguson spent his first of his 44 nights in
Barlinnie on October 11.
The prison service said he had got on with his sentence in ``quiet and
unremarkable'' fashion.
</TEXT>
