<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Key farming sectors `at risk'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Our Political Staff</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Nationalists' leader Alex Salmond last night accused Scottish
Secretary Michael Forsyth of putting key sectors of agriculture in Scotland at
risk.
It follows the announcement in a Commons written reply that the Scottish Office
will conduct ``prior options reviews'' of the work of the Scottish Crop
Research Institute, Macaulay Land Research Institute, the Scottish Agricultural
Science Agency, the Fisheries Research Services and the Forestry Commission's
Research Establishments.
This would assesses whether units could be privatised further and whether there
is scope for further commercialisation.
Mr Salmond said last night: ``This is a clear threat to key industries in the
north of Scotland. ``These institutions provide crucial support to the vital
fishing and farming industries in Scotland.
``It is a further demonstration of the powder-puff policies of Michael Forsyth
by allowing key Scottish institutions to be threatened.''
He also criticised the January 8 deadline for interested parties to make
submissions about the work of the institutions, saying it was ``ridiculously
short''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Daughter sees Briton's murder</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224853</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHANNESBURG: A British-born man was murdered outside his home in South Africa
on Tuesday in a bungled car hijacking, it was revealed yesterday. Lee Jeremy
Bennett, who moved to South Africa in the 1970s, was shot dead in front of his
10-year-old daughter Samantha as he stopped his car outside the family's
Johannesburg home.
Justice Minister Dullah Omar pledged maximum sentences for the perpetrators.
Jackson wins
PARIS: Michael Jackson was voted best male singer and Iceland's Bjork best
female vocalist at the MTV Europe Music Awards. From Britain, Take That won the
live performance prize and East 17 was top dance group. Dog Eat Dog was named
best newcomer, and U2 the best group. Bon Jovi were best rock group and the
Cranberries won best song with ``Zombie''.
Milat for trial
SYDNEY: Ivan Milat, the 50-year-old Australian accused of murdering seven
backpackers - including two Britons - has had a legal aid appeal thrown out by
Australia's High Court. His trial will begin in March.
Plague in post
COLUMBUS: An Ohio man accused of illegally obtaining bubonic plague bacteria
through the mail has agreed to plead guilty to wire fraud. Larry Harris, who
ordered the freeze-dried bacteria from a Maryland laboratory last May, faces up
to six months in jail.
Briton held
WASHINGTON: A Briton who allegedly assaulted two flight attendants and a pilot
on a trip from Heathrow to Dulles International Airport was arrested by federal
agents when he got off the plane and will appear in court today. Janzen Coles,
who was drinking, had to be restrained in his seat until the plane landed.
Killer forgiven
ANKARA: As a Turkish schoolboy began a six-year prison sentence yesterday for
gunning down a British doctor, the victim's wife described the 15-year-old
murderer as a ``lost little sheep'' who needed psychiatric care. Zeki Demir
killed gynaecologist Dr Martin Kettle in June last year at Ula, where he was on
holiday. Demir's has had mental problems since his brother shot his father dead
when he was a toddler, and Mrs Frankie Kettle said she had forgiven him.
Four die in riot
PORT-AU-PRINCE: At least four people were killed in violent clashes in Haiti's
worst slum yesterday. Angry slum dwellers in Cite Soleil disarmed policemen,
ransacked a police station, and fired at police after an officer shot at a bus
and accidentally shot dead a six-year-old child.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Well done, UK</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>11</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNITED NATIONS: Britain has been congratulated for making huge strides in
stamping out ill-treatment of prisoners in the past five years. The UN
Committee Against Torture had previously criticised Britain's treatment of
prisoners in Northern Ireland. Canadian member Professor Peter Burns said:
``There has been a dramatic change.''
Chernobyl plea
GENEVA: Scientists are appealing for #133m to monitor about one million people
exposed to the Chernobyl nuclear accident over the next 15 years. The move
comes after a conference of 600 experts found a sharp increase in thyroid
cancers, especially among children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seven killed in `deliberate' fire Inquest told of batteries missing from detectors</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224855</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HOUSE blaze which claimed the lives of seven children was started
deliberately, a fire investigation officer told an inquest yesterday.
Clwyd Fire Service divisional officer Stuart Mason ruled out the possibility
that a carelessly discarded cigarette could have caused the fire at the house
in Nelson Street, Hightown, Wrexham, on August 10.
He said neither of the smoke detector alarms in the four-bedroomed council
house had batteries fitted at the time of the fire.
Matthew Foulkes, eight, Philip Foulkes, seven, and twins Stephen and Robert
Davies, three, died on the day along with family friend Louise Jones, 12, who
was staying with them for a few days. Sarah Foulkes, 11, and Heather Davies, 20
months, died later at Liverpool's Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
Their mother Mandy Devery, 35, and her 63-year-old husband Dennis, the father
of the youngest three, managed to escape from the fire after being woken by
smoke.
A fire service video of the gutted house was shown at the inquest yesterday and
Mr Mason said a polyurethane-upholstered rocking chair in the dining room was
the point where the blaze started.
He said his investigation had ruled out gas or electrical causes, leaving a
discarded cigarette or a deliberate act - though not a malicious one - as the
only possible causes.
Mr Devery gave evidence on Wednesday that he had been smoking while watching a
late-night film sitting in the rocking chair the night before the breakfast
time blaze.
He had gone to bed leaving his tobacco tin and disposible lighter on a table by
the chair.
``In my opinion, it had nothing to do with smoking materials,'' said Mr Mason.
``The fire was of a rapidly developing nature and not consistent with a slow
burning, smouldering fire that would be necessary for a carelessly discarded
cigarette to be the source of ignition.
``The time factor, six-and-a-half hours, would be too long a period of
incubation for such an incident to develop unnoticed.''
Coroner John Hughes reminded Mr Mason that there was no direct evidence that
any of the children had gone downstairs that morning before the fire broke out
and that all of them were found in their bedrooms in nightclothes when
firefighters got them out.
Mr Mason said this did not alter his conclusion.
Mr Hughes asked: ``The cause of this fire was a direct flame igniting a
polyurethane foam upholstered rocking chair?''
Mr Mason replied: ``That is my opinion, yes.''
He added that no batteries were found in either of the two smoke detectors
fitted by the council as a matter of policy on the stairs and first-floor
landing of the house.
``A survey of other houses in the vicinity indicated that this was the norm
rather than the exception,'' said Mr Mason.
Families removed the batteries to minimise nuisance when they were cooking or
to use in toys.
The coroner said: ``Given the enormity of this tragedy, it seems to be a pretty
trivial nuisance to have this bleeping when cooking if it could save a life.''
Mr Mason replied: ``Yes sir, I agree.''
The inquest was told by council officials that both smoke detectors were
checked and were working when the house was inspected in October 1994, before
the family moved in.
The coroner read a statement from 14-year-old Wayne Foulkes - who survived the
fire in which his brothers and sisters died because he stayed overnight at a
friend's house, in which he said he removed batteries from the detector above
the stairs.
He said he had not handled the detector on the landing.
Pathologist Dr Anthony Burdge told the inquest that the five children who died
on the day of the fire had all suffered lethal levels of carbon monoxide and
cyanide poisoning after inhaling toxic smoke of the type given off by furniture
foam.
Mr Devery had bought the rocking chair as part of a second-hand three-piece
suite for #24 from a local auction house.
Modern furniture has its foam treated to make it slower to catch fire but the
inquest was told that when the foam does ignite it still gives off cyanide and
carbon monoxide.
Wrexham Maelor Council principal building surveyor David Berwyn Davies said the
authority was one of the first in the country to instal smoke detectors in all
its council houses.
The inquest concludes today.
</TEXT>
