<DOCNO>GH951124-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sinking inquiry calls for new safety moves</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FISHING boats should keep equipment on board capable of releasing net-towing
wires in an emergency, a Government agency recommended yesterday.
The Marine Accident Investigation Branch issued its report almost a year after
the skipper of Inverness fishing boat the Heather Bloom died when his vessel
sank in heavy seas off Shetland.
The boat, with a crew of six, had been fishing in waters 100 miles west of
Shetland when she ran into difficulties on the night of December 3, 1994.
The skipper, father-of-five John McLeman, 53, from Avoch in the Black Isle,
died after being swept from the listing boat into storm-lashed seas. His body
has not been recovered.
The boat was dragged under after her fishing gear became entangled in an
underwater obstruction. The rest of the crew were rescued by a nearby trawler,
the Ambassador, and a coastguard helicoper.
In its report, the agency said the immediate cause of the accident had been a
sudden intake of water. The report said the vessel's electrical system had
subsequently failed, preventing the crew from releasing the snared fishing gear.
The report also said a Mayday signal had not been sent until just before the
boat sank. Because of the angle of the boat, the signal was weak and not picked
up for about an hour when a search and rescue operation was launched.
It also called on the Marine Safety Agency to issue information to skippers on
when to send out Mayday signals. It warned fishermen to send distress signals
at the earliest opportunity and to be aware that signals were weakened in
certain weather conditions.
</TEXT>
