<DOCNO>GH951124-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fox fends off challenge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224857</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIR Marcus Fox last night was re-elected chairman of the influential Tory
backbench 1922 Committee.
Sir Marcus, 68, successfully fended off a challenge from fellow right-winger
and former Minister Bob Dunn. Details of the voting were not released.
Later, Marcus said he was honoured by the vote of confidence in him.
It was the second year in succession that Sir Marcus had to see off a challenge
to his position as leader of the Tory back benchers.
Last year he defeated Sir Nicholas Bonsor - now a Foreign Office Minister - in
a contest widely seen to be testing the water for a possible leadership
challenge to John Major.
This year, however, with the mood in the party very different, the contest was
seen to be more about the contrasting personal styles of the two men. Some MPs
backing Mr Dunn wanted to see a younger chairman installed before the General
Election.
Mr John Townend, chairman of the backbench finance committee, failed in his bid
for one of the two posts of vice-chairman. Party grandees Sir Geoffrey
Johnson-Smith and Dame Jill Knight were re-elected.
All executive members of the 1922 committee were re-elected except Mr Donald
Thompson, MP for Calder Valley, who failed to submit nomination papers. His
place was taken by former Minister Sir Archibald Hamilton.
</TEXT>
