<DOCNO>GH951124-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Health unions' private fears</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNION leaders yesterday claimed the Government's private finance initiative,
used for capital NHS projects, could be expanded to nursing and other clinical
services.
The social services committee of the STUC predicted the move was on the cards
after a two-hour meeting with NHS managers, including chief executive Geoff
Scaife at the Scottish Office in Edinburgh.
Mr Campbell Christie, STUC general secretary, said: ``The prospect is that
large tranches of the health service in Scotland will be provided by the
private sector and run by the private sector.''
He said there had been an indication at the meeting that the restriction on
clinical services not being included in private finance initiative would not
apply in Scotland.
Mr Grahame Smith, assistant STUC secretary, added: ``This is the first time we
have had it confirmed to us that the privatisation of clinical services is
actually an option for trusts pursuing the finance initiative for building the
facilities.''
Mr Christie believes this is the biggest push yet on the road to privatisation
and warned that unions would campaign strongly against it.
Grampian Health Board invited private companies this month to tender for
contracts to build, equip, and run a hospital in Stonehaven.
The STUC believes the hospital will be used as a pilot for hospitals under
construction in Scotland, including the new Law Hospital in Lanarkshire and the
Royal Infirmary in Edinburgh.
Strong disapproval at the move was voiced by the British Medical Association,
which described such a move as ``a double-edged sword'' which went against the
ethos and principles of the National Health Service.
Opposition parties united in a chorus of dissent. A spokesman for the Labour
Party said: ``This simply confirms our worst fears.''
Dr Iain Glen, SNP health spokesman, said: ``Against the overwhelming wishes of
the Scottish people, the Tories are clearly set on fragmenting and privatising
Scotland's national health service.''
A spokesman for the Scottish Liberal Democrats said the party was opposed to
the private finance initiative being used for capital projects.
A Scottish Office spokesman said the STUC obviously had ``ideological
difficulty'' with the private finance initiative but stressed that the
potential was enormous, with several hundred schemes under active
consideration, including NHS schemes worth around #700m.
</TEXT>
