<DOCNO>GH951124-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cabinet backs changes to Scots government</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STUART TROTTER,, Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth yesterday secured Cabinet approval for his
plans to change the way Scotland is governed.
However, his hope of upstaging the Scottish Constitutional Convention on St
Andrew's day has been partially thwarted by opposition MPs who have insisted
that they be first to hear of the changes.
Mr Forsyth will produce a ``devolution to people rather than institutions''
package when he anounces changes in an eagerly awaited speech in Glasgow on St
Andrew's Day.
However, the Cabinet agreed yesterday that he should outline to the House of
Commons the procedural changes in their business arrangements which his plan
requires but he is thought to be planning to keep other details of the package
for his Scottish audience.
SNP leader Alex Salmond attacked Labour for demanding that Mr Forsyth announces
the changes in Westminster before making his speech in Scotland. He said:
``Surely on St Andrew's Day, of all days, the responsibility of the political
parties is to present their views first to the people of Scotland.''
Some of the changes Mr Forsyth will be proposing will affect the way Scotland
handles Scottish business. The Scottish Grand Committee is likely to be allowed
to take some Scottish Bills through all their stages without the whole House of
Commons being involved.
However, the thrust of many of the proposals will be the empowerment of
individuals through greater ability to make decisions about the area where they
live, wider choices over education and health, and more opportunities to make
their views known.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson, speaking in Inverness, said they
would be ``panic measures which amounted to an admission of failure''.
The Liberal Democrats Scot-tish spokeswoman Ray Michie said that while
Ministers talked about measures to improve the government of Scotland, the fact
was that Scotland was actually being sidelined by Westminster.
The Forsyth package may seek to address some of these problems by passing
comparatively uncontroversial Bills to be dealt with only by a Scottish
committee, although it seems certain they will have to preserve the right of
Westminster to deal with more controversial measures by the traditional
procedure, to ensure a Government majority.
Meanwhile, Labour and the Liberal Democrats claimed they were making political
history in Inverness yesterday when they signed the Constitutional Convention's
agreement to achieve equal numbers of men and women in the first Scottish
Parliament for three centuries, writes David Ross.
As such an occasion demanded, the ceremony was performed by a woman and a man
from either party. Rhona Brankin, who chairs the Scottish Labour Party said:
``This is a historic occasion and I think it now gives us an opportunity to
begin to create a parliament which is actually fit for the twenty-first
century, a parliament which seeks to represent all the people from Shetland
right down to the Borders.''
</TEXT>
