<HEADLINE>Slim hope of ending impasse in Ireland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
White House says Clinton `will
not pull rabbit out of the hat'
Slim hope
of ending
impasse
in Ireland
THE prospects for a UK-Irish summit ahead of US President Bill Clinton's visit
next week were looking slim last night after John Major and John Bruton failed
to clear remaining ``roadblocks''.
The British and Irish premiers are expected to speak again today. Their
officials worked overnight to try to find a way to end the log-jam.
There is still a possibility that they could meet in Dublin on Sunday before Mr
Clinton's arrival. However, last night there was no sign that Britain will
shift on the demand that the IRA must, at the very least, take some significant
step towards the decommissioning of its weapons.
London, Dublin, and Washington all agree that an independent commission should
be established to handle decommissioning, while Sinn Fein could be brought into
bilateral constitutional talks. Mr Bruton wants a target date limited to about
three months - but Mr Major is still resisting this approach.
Downing Street remains confident of an agreement based on the twin-track
approach, which involves establishment of an international commission to
oversee the decommissioning of paramilitary arms while providing an opening for
the two Governments and the Northern Ireland parties to consider round-table
talks.
Mr Bruton telephoned Downing Street on Wednesday night to spell out his
critical views of a speech delivered earlier in the day by Northern Ireland
Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew.
Sir Patrick repeated in stark terms Britain's demand for moves by the IRA
towards the decommissioning their stocks of arms before the entry of their Sinn
Fein partners into all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
In America, US officials were seeking to damp down expectations that Mr
Clinton's visit - which is being put back by 24 hours so he can address the
nation on Bosnia - will produce a dramatic breakthrough.
A senior White House official commenting on speculation that Mr Clinton ``is
going to pull a rabbit out of a hat in Northern Ireland'', cautioned: ``It's
not going to happen.''
He said the trip was more of a celebration of 15 months of ceasefire.
Mr Major was today said ``to fully understand'' Mr Clinton's decision to delay
the start of his visit. White House officals contacted Downing Street on
Wednesday night to inform them Mr Clinton would be putting back his arrival by
24 hours.
Meanwhile, one of the most bitter campaigns for votes in Irish history was
continuing to the last minute ahead of the referendum on divorce.
Accusations of lying and other strongly-worded comments were hurled around by
bishops and Government Ministers in the final days of the battle for support in
a plebiscite that has exposed deep rifts in Irish society.
At stake was one of Europe's final legal barriers to divorce.
A Government-backed bid to end the constitutional divorce prohibition failed in
1986, when the move was rejected by 2-1 majority. Polls this time suggest a
repeat result could be on the cards. Resistance to reform has been led by the
Roman Catholic church hierarchy.However, Ministers remained confident that the
swing against them had been checked.
