<DOCNO>GH951124-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Procedure wrong in job application</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224863</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROPER procedures were abandoned in the hiring of a councillor's daughter, the
inquiry into employment practices within Monklands District Council was told
yesterday.
Mr Ian Crawford, head of human resources, had been recalled to explain how Miss
Catriona Smith, a daughter of human resources convener Jim Smith, came to be
employed as a clerical assistant.
He told Mr William Nimmo-Smith QC, who is holding the inquiry in Coatbridge,
that he himself had conducted the interview late last year.
He admitted that the interview should have been carried out by the
administration and legal services department where the vacancy existed.
However, Mr Crawford insisted that Miss Smith's relationship to Councillor
Smith had ``no bearing'' on the outcome of the interview.
The inquiry heard earlier this week that Miss Smith and a friend of hers, Ms
Jackie Davies, who had worked together in a florist's shop, both secured jobs
as clerical assistants at Monklands.
Referring to Miss Smith, Mr Crawford said: ``Rightly or wrongly, I took the
interview myself. Whether I would still do that......''(he tailed off speaking
at this point).
Mr Nimmo-Smith said: ``With all the allegations about nepotism, surely proper
procedures should have been followed?''
Mr Crawford: ``I was trying to be very conscious of that. I took the decision
to interview her myself. I did not want to put pressure on other staff.''
q.Dover MP David Shaw, a persistent critic of Monklands, surprised Parliament
yesterday by stating that council leader Jim Brooks had threatened him outside
the inquiry room on Wednesday by saying he would visit him and his family.
Councillor Brooks said: ``I was astounded when I heard what Mr Shaw had said.
Many people witnessed the incident. No-one had the same view of it as he did.''
</TEXT>
