<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hope of swop dashed by kidnappers' demands Hostage captors renew threats</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224864</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Srinagar, Thursday
GUERRILLAS holding four Western hostage in Kashmir said today that the Indian
Government would soon regret its actions if it did not release jailed Kashmiri
separatists.
``If the government does not meet our demands as early as possible, they will
be sorry,'' the kidnappers, who have already killed one hostage, told
government negotiators.
The threats by the Al-Faran guerrillas were relayed by official sources who
said that negotiators had a 10-minute exchange with the guerrillas by telephone
or radio today.
The kidnappers asked for a radio and said they would contact the authorities
again on Saturday.
After Al-Faran captured the tourists in July, it demanded the release of 22
jailed separatists, including three members of Harkat-ul-Ansar, a
Pakistan-based Muslim militant group, in exchange for the hostages.
It later softened its demand, asking for the release of 15 separatists
including Harkat-ul-Ansar members.
Indian authorities have been in regular touch with the guerrillas since
November 9, when contact was re-established after a gap of more than 50 days.
Al Faran sent a hand-written statement today to some newspapers in Kashmir's
main city Srinagar to deny it was bargaining for the release of Maulana Masood
Azhar, a leader of the Pakistan-based militant group Harkat-ul-Ansar.
It described the story, given to the media this week by a senior official, as
``mere propaganda of the Indian Government'' and insisted: ``We still stand by
our earlier demands.''
Indian officials had hoped that an offer to bring Azhar to trial might buy
freedom for American hostage Don Hutchings, who is said to be critically ill
with frostbite.
The other hostages are Briton Paul Wells, said by Indian officials to have
recovered from viral fever, fellow Briton Keith Mangan, and German Dirk Hasert.
They were kidnapped while trekking. Norwegian captive Hans Christian Ostroe was
found beheaded on August 13.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cheers in court as killer on parole is jailed for life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224865</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 22-stone, 6ft 4in psychopath, who had killed twice and had an extensive
criminal record for acts of violence, was jailed for life at the Old Bailey
yesterday.
There were cheers in court as black-bearded Ian Baker, 36, was led handcuffed
to the cells.
Outside court, the grieving relatives of Baker's latest victim called for a
review of all cases in which excessively violent criminals had been released.
Relatives of 27-year-old graphic designer Michael Davis said they were
``shocked and stunned'' that a persistently vicious attacker had been ``free to
roam and take another innocent life''.
After the jury convicted Baker of murdering Mr Davis, they were told he had
been on parole on a manslaughter sentence at the time.
He had also been granted bail by magistrates, despite police objections, on
charges of dealing in crack and possessing three knives.
Baker, who always carried a lock-knife, was also convicted of wounding three
other people, including the dead man's girlfriend Ms Sue Parrish, 27, in a
frenzied and unprovoked attack in March this year.
Mr John Bevan, prosecuting, said Baker turned ``a jolly and friendly''
fancy-dress party at a pub in New Cross, south-east London, into a bloodbath.
Without any provocation, and posing as a bouncer although he did not work at
the pub, Baker stabbed Mr Davis through the heart and in the back after
ordering him to put out a cannabis joint.
Mr Bevan said Baker had deliberately gone out ``spoiling for trouble'' and was
looking for an opportunity to use the knife.
Miss Parrish stepped between the two men to try to save her boyfriend, who was
a foot shorter than his attacker, and was slashed on the arms. Two other men
who tried to intervene were also knifed, one almost fatally.
The court heard that Baker, of Alexandra Street, New Cross, was jailed for
three years in 1978 for plotting to steal, five robberies, three attempts and
carrying a knife.
He reappeared at the Old Bailey in 1982 and was jailed for seven years for
robbery and wounding. These included four knife-point muggings and stabbing a
prison officer in the heart while escaping from a prison van. In the ensuing
chase he stabbed a motorist and kept a police negotiator hostage during a
five-hour siege.
In 1988 he was jailed for nine years for the manslaughter of a youth outside a
pub. He was working as a bouncer and stabbed his victim through the heart
during a brawl. He was released on parole in May 1993.
Last November he was returned to jail for supplying drugs and possessing
knives.
Sentencing Baker, who was flanked by six prison officers, Judge Geoffrey
Grigson said: ``It is plain you are a grave and continuing threat to the
public. You carried a knife and didn't hesitate to use it. It is only a matter
of chance that you did not kill others.''
Afterwards Detective Inspector Andre Baker said: ``This is one of the most
dangerous men I have ever dealt with. He should not have been at liberty to
take another life.''
And the dead man's brother Mr Trevor Davis said: ``The family would like to
thank the police for putting this beast behind bars. He should not have been
mixing with ordinary people, his record shows he is an animal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sentence reduced for killer of molester</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE killer of a convicted child molester had his eight-year jail sentence
reduced to seven years by three appeal court judges yesterday.
Paul Strathearn, 34, stabbed Lawrence Leydon, 36, eight times, including once
through the heart, in a frenzied attack at the victim's home at Southhouse
Medway, Edinburgh, on February 11 this year.
He was charged with murder but, after trial at the High Court in Edinburgh, a
jury convicted him of culpable homicide on the basis that he had been suffering
from diminished responsibility at the time of the killing.
They heard psychiatric evidence that Strathearn's state of mind had been
bordering on insanity.
At the time of the stabbing, Leydon was serving a sentence of two years'
probation for indecency offences against a 10-year-child.
The trial judge, Lord Prosser, said he took into account that an attack of
murderous quality had been reduced to culpable homicide because of Strathearn's
dimished responsibility but it remained a very serious offence.
Before yesterday's hearing at the Court of Criminal Appeal, Strathearn's
supporters staged a demonstration.
Mr Jamie Gilchrist, for Strathearn, accepted that a significant custodial
sentence was inevitable but argued that, given the background to the case,
eight years was excessive.
Lord Ross, Lord Justice-Clerk, who heard the appeal with Lords Morison and
Gill, said it appeared that Strathearn had become obsessed with what he
perceived as the injustice of Leydon going unpunished for the sex offence.
``In the present case, we are satisfied that the diminished responsibility
should have been taken into account as having some mitigating value,'' Lord
Ross said.
``What the trial judge said in this regard to the effect that it did not have
any great mitigating value, was, we think, wrong.''
The trial judge also appeared to have attached some weight to the fact that
there was evidence that Strathearn had made earlier threats to Leydon.
However, that part of the indictment had been deleted by the Crown and, in
these circumstances, the appeal court felt that Lord Prosser's approach to
sentencing had, to some extent, been flawed.
Lord Ross added: ``Taking all the relevant considerations into account, we have
come to the conclusion that the appropriate sentence in this case was one of
seven years.''
Strathearn gave a thumbs up to supporters in the public benches as he was led
from the dock to resume his sentence.
Outside the court, his wife Katrina said: ``The more that would have come off
(his sentence), the better but he is just highly delighted that they took
something off.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clients left legal firm `in droves' Partner tells industrial tribunal he wanted to get rid of agency lawyers to improve service</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224867</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PARTNER in a leading Scots law firm yesterday admitted to an industrial
tribunal that clients had left the firm in droves because of poor legal
representation.
He revealed that lawyers frequently were only handed the case papers for trials
minutes before the trial was due to begin.
He also said that Ross Harper Murphy &amp; Co solicitors, trading as Ross Harper,
had been regarded as ``a very soft target'' by other solicitors who took
clients away.
The tribunal was hearing evidence into the case of lawyer Eileen Paterson who
is claiming unfair dismissal and sexual discrimination after being fired for
refusing to work at night because of her family commitments.
Mr John Carruthers, 34, the managing partner at Ross Harper Murphy's Ingram
Street office in Glasgow, gave evidence that when he was put in charge of the
criminal department in April 1994 he had no experience of criminal legal work
and had never conducted a criminal trial.
Questioned by Mr Jack Quar, representing Mrs Paterson, Mr Carruthers said he
wanted experienced lawyers on the night time call-out rota who would see
clients in the police station and then the same lawyer would represent them in
court next day when they appeared in the custody court.
However, he refused to confirm that, recently, a man who was in police custody
charged with murder and allegedly a client of his firm had been seen by an
unqualified paralegal assistant and not a solicitor.
He did admit that paralegals, as well as solicitors, were still used on the
night-time rota to see clients in police stations.
Mr Carruthers decided last December to put Mrs Paterson on the night-time rota,
after she had been off it for eight years because of her children and her
husband's work commitments.
Mr Carruthers said that when he took control of the criminal side they were
losing a lot of clients to other lawyers.
He added: ``People weren't coming to us things were so bad.''
He also claimed he didn't want to get into a ``mandate war'' with other
solicitors and if a client from another firm wanted to transfer to Ross Harper
Murphy he would send them back to discuss it with the other firm.
He added: ``We were looked upon as a very soft target. We had a very soft
underbelly.
``No-one had seen fit to do anything about it until I arrived. The place was
just under managed.''
Mr Carruthers placed a lot of the blame for losing clients on agency lawyers
used by Ross Harper Murphy and said: ``Some really didn't care.
``There was no real follow-up. No real input.
``We had, in some cases, some agency lawyers working for us who would not have
got full-time employment elsewhere.
``For some reason, they seemed to be attracted to our firm.'' As part of a
policy to improve service to clients, he said: ``We wanted to get rid of the
agency lawyers and get people on staff who wanted to do a good job, who wanted
to go that extra half mile.''
Mrs Paterson, 36, in giving evidence, said she had made it clear that because
of the ages of her two sons, nine and four, and the workload of her husband's
growing civil court advocacy business in Edinburgh, she couldn't work at night.
Earlier, Mr Cameron Fyfe, the firm's managing partner, told the tribunal that
he hadn't investigated Mrs Paterson's personal circumstances before firing her
earlier this year.
When asked by Mr Quar yesterday why her mother couldn't look after the
children, as suggested by Mr Fyfe, Mrs Paterson became upset and explained:
``My mother was very ill, suffering from cancer, during this period.''
Asked whether any compromise had been put to her before she was sacked, Mrs
Paterson confirmed that Mr Fyfe had suggested she should transfer to civil
legal work.
However, she said: ``I haven't done any civil work since 1979 when I was an
apprentice.
``I had 14 years' experience in criminal work and had no interest in doing
civil work.''
She also rejected evidence given by Mr Carruthers who claimed her husband
``wasn't away from home as often as was made out'' and also denied he had been
in her home more than twice as he claimed in evidence. When questioned by
tribunal chairman Alistair McArthur, Mr Carruthers confirmed that Mr Liam
O'Donnell, who joined the firm as a criminal lawyer last November/ December,
had complained about Mrs Paterson not being on the rota.
He said: ``It's an example of a fresh eye coming into the firm. Liam came from
one of our competitors.
``He asked about Eileen not being on the rota and said, `My wife is pregnant.
We have a baby on the way and I will be in exactly the same position as
Eileen'.''
He then told the tribunal that Mrs O'Donnell was a primary schoolteacher and
finished work at 3.30pm.
The tribunal continues.
</TEXT>
