<DOCNO>GH951124-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Firm is reported to Law Society</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224868</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF has reported a prominent firm of Scottish solicitors to the Law
Society of Scotland, for ignoring solicitor's practice rules and acting for
both sides in an ``unsavoury'' house purchase deal that went sour.
Sheriff Richard Davidson has accused the blue-chip firm of Blackadder Reid
Johnston, of Dundee, of ``a profound and cynical disregard for their
professional obligations'', in a written judgment that he has sent to the Law
Society.
In the judgment, the sheriff criticises solicitor Donald Hutcheson, a senior
partner at Blackadder Reid Johnston, for not being ``a credible and reliable''
witness.
Mr Hutcheson, a solicitor of 23 years' standing, acted for property developer
John Duncan in the sale of a flat to Miss Lesley McCann, a legal secretary at
Blackadder Reid and Johnston.
The firm also acted for the Alliance and Leicester building society in
arranging a mortgage for Miss McCann, now of Shielhill Gardens, Aberdeen.
The firm acted for Mr Duncan in the purchase of the flat in Morgan Street,
Dundee, for #9500 in April, 1989. Then, the following month, they acted for
both Mr Duncan and Miss McCann in the resale of the flat, for #12,000.
As part of the deal, Mr Duncan was to receive up to #9450 in improvement grants
to make the flat habitable but the council insisted on extra work and Mr Duncan
decided to sue Miss McCann for the additional costs.
Sheriff Davidson found that it put the defender (Miss McCann) in possession of
an unmodernised, uninhabitable flat, with just a personal obligation by the
pursuer to modernise the property''.
He found that the full circumstances and consequences of this were not
explained to Miss McCann, and noted that Blackadder Reid Johnston continued to
represent both parties in the house purchase from June 1989 to June 1990, in
contravention of the Practice Rules.
He also found Blackadder Reid Johnston in further breach of rules by acting for
the Alliance and Leicester in the transaction, when it had purchased the
property for Mr Duncan the previous month, for #9500.
The deal went sour when Dundee District Council insisted on extra works to the
property at Morgan Street, and Mr Duncan decided to sue Miss McCann for #5800
toward the cost of the additional works, after she sold the flat for #22,500.
Sheriff Davidson found the grant application ``tainted with fraud'', and
refused to find in Mr Duncan's favour.
He concluded that for the firm to maintain there was no conflict of interest
appeared to demonstrate ``a profound and cynical disregard for their
professional obligations''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leeson to face court on #860m charges</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER futures trader Nick Leeson is due before a Singapore court today to face
fraud and forgery charges over the #860m collapse of Barings Bank.
Mr Leeson, 28, ar-rived in Singapore yesterday after being flown from
Frankfurt, where he had been in custody since early March.
Mr Leeson was taken from Changi airport to the headquarters of the Commercial
Affairs Department, Singapore's financial police, for questioning.
His lawyer, Mr John Koh, said Mr Leeson would not enter any pleas at today's
hearing.
Mr Leeson is accused of forging documents and opening a fictitious account to
conceal his unauthorised trading while working as the Singapore general manager
of the bank's futures trading arm.
Singapore legal experts said that, after the hearing, Mr Leeson will probably
be remanded in custody for a week and sent to the Queenstown jail pending trial.
It is considered highly unlikely he will get bail.
Next week, the judge may set a date for a pre-trial hearing, which would allow
the judge and lawyers to narrow down the issues which will be at the heart of
the trial. A trial date will be set after that hearing. He faces a maximum
prison sentence of 14 years.
Mr Koh said Mr Leeson was calm but concerned: ``He's not scared but there are
certainly a lot of things going through his mind.'' Earlier, Mr Leeson was
escorted by officers from the fraud squad during the 12-hour flight from
Frankfurt. Also on the plane were his wife Lisa, 26, his British lawyer, Mr
Stephen Pollard, and Mr Koh.
A dozen reporters were on the same flight but security guards kept them from
ap-proaching the group.
Mr Leeson and his wife sat together through most of the flight but were
separated after breakfast was served, about two hours before the plane landed
in Singapore.
A flight attendant said there was a tearful parting as a Singapore policeman
took Mrs Leeson's place.
Mr Leeson was ar-rested immediately on his arrival by a Commercial Affairs
Department official, who told him: ``It is my duty to inform you that you are
taken under arrest for the 11 charges you have been extradited on.''
Mr Leeson made no reply.
Mr Leeson, who handled contracts worth millions of pounds as a derivatives
trader on the Singapore International Monetary Ex-change, originally fought
extradition to the city-state.
The Leesons left Singapore in February as news spread that the bank was in
trouble. He was arrested in Frankfurt on March 2 and initially resisted extra-
dition, saying he wanted to be tried in London.
Last month, he agreed to return.
</TEXT>
