<DOCNO>GH951124-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inquest told warder left hanged prisoner</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE warder who found a teenage prisoner hanging from the bars of her cell
window stopped supporting her legs in order to answer a panicked call from the
jail control room, a fatal accident inquiry heard yesterday.
The second day of the joint inquiry into the deaths of Kelly Holland and Arlene
Elliot at Cornton Vale Prison, Stirling, in June, heard evidence of delays in
cutting down the girls from their makeshift nooses. The two girls committed
suicide at the prison in separate incidents within four days.
Prison officer John McFadyen, 32, said he had been on active duty in the
Scottish Prison Service for only two months when he found himself working alone
in the remand block on the night Miss Holland died.
He said he had checked her cell at 15-minute intervals after coming on duty at
9.30pm on June 22.
He saw her writing a letter and noticed that her eyes were red but he thought
she was simply writing an admission letter which many prisoners did on their
first night. ``She looked as if she had been crying but I asked her how she was
and she said she was OK.''
At 12.30pm he saw her lying on her bed and thought she was asleep. At 12.45pm
he found her hanging. ``I saw her silhouette at the window.
``I shone my torch in and that's when I noticed the ligature from the top bar.''
Mr McFadyen said he ``immediately realised the enormity of the situation'' and
radioed for assistance.
He said: ``I opened the door and rushed to the window. I grabbed her body and
supported the weight of it.'' He then radioed again to ask the whereabouts of
the night patrol. They said they were on their way.
Miss Holland seemed lifeless, he said. ``I was looking for a wheeze, a gasp,
anything. There was nothing.''
Then he was distracted by a call from the jail control room on an intercom
outside the cell.
He said a ``panicky voice'' asked: ``What's happening, what's happening?'' The
night patrol still had not arrived.
He said: ``At this point, I realised I had to get Kelly down. This became my
priority.''
He let Miss Holland go, ran to the intercom, and stressed he needed immediate
assistance.
Then he ran to his office and grabbed a ``crash pack'' which he knew from his
college training would contain a knife to cut down a suicide.
When he got back to Miss Holland's cell the night patrol was just in front of
him. She was cut down and heart massage and resuscitation were attempted to
revive her.
Asked how long the delay was in getting the crash pack, Mr McFadyen said he
thought about 10 seconds.
Later, senior prison officer Pamela Ligget, 29, night shift supervisor in
charge of the jail after dark, denied there had been delays in reaching Miss
Holland. She said the night patrol had been on the scene no more than 30
seconds after receiving Mr McFadyen's radio call for help.
The inquiry, before Sheriff Principal John Maguire at Stirling Sheriff Court,
continues.
</TEXT>
