<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Killing goes on as Pope attacks Mafia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PHILIP PULLELLA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224873</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Palermo, Thursday
THE Pope launched a broadside against the Mafia today, using a visit to the Mob
stronghold of Sicily to demand an end to killing.
However even as he spoke, another organised crime murder was taking place
across the island in the eastern city of Catania.
Matteo Romeo, 21, son-in-law of a local Mob boss, was shot dead in Catania fish
market.
The Pope's 10-hour visit to Sicily had begun on a controversial note when
Palermo's anti-Mafia mayor, Leoluca Orlando, stalked out of a welcoming
ceremony in protest at the presence of a bishop suspected of having Mob ties.
Orlando's gesture focused on the sometimes blurred relations between organised
crime and the Roman Catholic Church in Sicily.
The Pope forcefully returned to the theme of a 1993 trip to Sicily which he
turned into an anti-Mafia crusade.
``Do not kill,'' he told a church convention. ``No man, no human association,
no Mafia can change or trample on the right to life, this most holy right that
belongs to God.''
The Pope praised Sicilians for continuing attempts to uproot crime. He said he
felt compelled to repeat his words of two years ago because they were ``a cry
from my heart''.
The Mafia responded to the 1993 crusade by placing car bombs at two churches in
Rome, including St John's Lateran, the Pope's cathedral in his capacity as
bishop of Rome.
Since his election in 1978, the Pope has thrown his weight behind bishops and
priests who have spoken out against the Mafia. Previously, the local hierarchy
had been accused of turning a blind eye to the Mafia.
Some Sicilian priests have openly defied the Mafia and paid with their lives
for their preaching. The last to die was Father Giuseppe Puglisi, who was
killed in Palermo in 1993.
Later the Pope celebrated a stadium mass for 35,000 people, including relatives
of judges killed by the Mafia, with a tribute to Father Puglisi.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Machismo and the mailman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224874</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE current dispute is only the latest of 100 wildcat actions which have hit
the Post Office in past two years.
In 1993 there were 32 illegal stoppages in the UK and last year this figure
doubled to 65, including protracted disputes in Liverpool and Newcastle which
achieved national prominence.
Both sides were set on a collision course as a result of heavy investment in
computer technology during the abortive run-up to privatisation and new
legislation curbing powers of unions, according to Peter Bain, lecturer in
human resource management at Strathclyde University.
``I think it is all about cutting costs,'' he said. ``It is clear that large
numbers of line managers and local managers are being told from national level
this is the way you will manage. That is coming across as a heavy-handed and
macho style.
``If this is not the case, it must be a fantastic coincidence that up and down
the country in dozens of locations similar events have taken place.''
The 1990 legislation requiring unions to repudiate unofficial action was
introduced in the wake of a spate of unofficial strikes the previous summer.
In the Post Office at least, it has achieved the opposite effect, particularly
in the light of 1993 legislation which made the ballot process much more
cumbersome and difficult.
``That's really what's causing much of the trouble at present. It is a very
long drawn-out process before employees can get to the point of legal
industrial action and workers confronted with certain situations are now acting
spontaneously,'' Mr Bain said.
The penalties for unions who fail to issue sufficiently strong repudiations can
be harsh. In the biggest dispute in London which involved 15,000 workers, the
CWU made repeated public statements and even sent out individual warning
letters to its members.
Nonetheless, it was fined #7000 and ordered to pay costs of #100,000.
The Post Office, like other public sector bodies, has had to embrace an
aggressive managerial style from the private sector which many private firms
have long since abandoned.
It was also geared into a new philosophy for privatisation which was abandoned,
leaving it in limbo. Mr Lane thinks privatisation may still be on the agenda.
Many employers welcome the discipline unions can give to the workforce, but if
law removes this, then industrial anarchy prevails. At this year's conference,
rank and file postal workers rejected their own leadership's recommendations to
co-operate with management on certain changes.
``Some of the more far-sighted employers are concerned about these events. A
lot of them are worried that the law is so restrictive and prohibitive,'' Mr
Bain said.
Either way, as attitudes harden, there is a broader risk of a legacy of
bitterness which may sour industrial relations in the Royal Mail for some time
to come.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trials and tribulations of `Postman Pat'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224875</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIS workmates jokingly call him ``Postman Pat'', remarks made by several postal
workers as they left a highly-charged meeting in Edinburgh yesterday.
Mr John Keggie, divisional officer for Scotland and Northern Ireland and
national executive council member of the Communications Workers' Union, would
probably agree because for 12 years he was a postman, delivering mail around
Edinburgh.
For the past eight years he has been a committed member of the union and says
that he realises the frustration of his colleagues in the latest dispute which
is affecting mail deliveries all over Scotland.
Before joining Royal Mail, Mr Keggie, 36, a bachelor, was a welder working for
10 years with former Leith shipbuilders, Henry Robb and Co, where he became
full time convener of the Boilermakers' Union.
He was appointed to the national executive of the Communication Workers' Union
and, despite his call to get his members back to work, is adamant that talks
must take place with management.
Having been shouted down at a stormy meeting in Edinburgh yesterday, he
retorted at one point that he had the microphone and could talk louder than the
audience.
His tactic did not work - his members decided that they wanted to stay out.
During an unofficial strike over similar issues in May, the union leader was
pelted with coins and beer mats by workers when he asked them to return to
work.
Over the course of the dispute he also clashed with management, accusing them
of ``trying to take second deliveries behind the backdoor and actually
hoodwinking the public''. Yesterday, Mr Keggie told The Herald: ``I delivered
mail around Edinburgh for 12 years and I fully understand the anger and
frustration.
``I also understand that we must work within the legislation and have a ballot,
and I am prepared to sit round the table, for 24 hours or more if necessary, to
resolve this.''
He denied allegations that his union was acting illegally and said there was no
evidence of unofficial union involvement in any of the strikes. ``We have a
long tradition of abiding by legislation,'' he said.
Mr Keggie admitted that he was frustrated by the situation, but repeated that
he could understand the attitude of his members.
He felt Royal Mail was gradually chipping away at staff and the service it
claimed to provide. ``Latest proposals take out 156 second deliveries in
Edinburgh alone,'' he stated.
He also claimed that with a profit of #481m last year in a postal service which
was the most efficient in the world, Royal Mail was insistent on imposing
conditions affecting staff by the desire to remove second deliveries.
Mr Keggie, responsible for some 13,000 members in Scotland and Northern
Ireland, said: ``I think there will always be a service, but it could decimate
second deliveries, particularly in rural areas.''
The union leader added that it was not an impossibility that a ``poste
restante'' system, as operated in France, where customers have to collect their
own mail, could be introduced by Royal Mail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Director defends a  first class service  in time of change</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Chris Holme</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224876</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Mail boss Alex Gibb strenuously denies he is the hard man at the face of
macho management.
``I'm definitely not one of the new management breed,'' said the 49-year-old
Royal Mail delivery director for Scotland and Northern Ireland who has been
given the tough job as the public voice of management in the increasingly
bitter dispute.
His own career in the Post Office started 30 years ago as a junior executive.
Since then he has taken in London, Oxford, Bristol, and Aberdeen before
returning to Edinburgh.
Mr Gibb defends the Royal Mail's industrial relations policy during a period of
dramatic change in working practices.
``We have not made one person compulsorily redundant despite the fact that we
have virtually fully automated the sorting process in Scotland. I think that's
a good record,'' he said.
The process of change has been rapid. Mail volumes are increasing and through
use of aircraft and automated processing it is getting through faster. ``Almost
90% of the mail is now available to go out in the first delivery whereas
previously it was 60%.
``The impact on second delivery is that we have less mail. We have no intention
of getting rid of the second delivery but it is the number of people available
to make that second delivery. That is the issue at the core of this particular
industrial action,'' he said.
Royal Mail has sought to introduce a computerised system Card to revise
delivery rounds. That means fewer posties.
Mr Gibb says there is extensive consultation with the Communication Workers'
Union over the introduction of changes and ample time is left should the union
wish to ballot.
``Mail volume is increasing and with it the workload of postal workers. I think
they genuinely feel a bit under pressure, but we do increase the amount of time
into those deliveries to help them.
``There is always a strong resistance to change. It is not about managers
pushing harder, it is about people managing that change,'' he said.
Mr Gibb concedes that management could at times explain better the reasons
behind moves to its staff and take them with it. However, he insists this was
not the case at Portobello, where the current dispute broke out. Managers had
proposed converting seven duties to part-time but then agreed to a staff
proposal reducing this to four.
``What we asked them to do in Portobello were the new duties the postmen
themselves proposed to us. It was the intervention of their divisional union
representatives which changed this. They said these were not acceptable and not
in line with the union's policy.
``That's how crazy this is. I don't think the postmen themselves understand it
and I find the whole thing absolutely incredible''
Mr Gibb claims the union's position is further compromised by the presence of
some officials on picket lines when the union had told its members to go back
to work.
He said the Royal Mail's job was to improve services to customers, using new
technology and taking its staff with it. ``This is about changing so that we
grow the business and jobs. We want to improve quality and value for money.''
he added.
The trouble is that for all the technological investment the Royal Mail is
still heavily labour-intensive at the point of delivery. Posties still have the
power to exercise their industrial muscle, legally or not.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>couriers up and running as business booms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Industrial Correspondent Roy Rogers reports on the probable long-term damage of Royal Mail</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224877</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Mail fears the postal dispute could permanently damage its business,
as Scottish couriers reported booming trade yesterday.
The Union of Communications Workers - which has repudiated the unofficial
action - dismisses this claim as ``scare tactics''.
But industry analysts maintain postal workers are shooting themselves in the
foot by forcing business to look at alternative services for delivery of legal
and financial documents.
``Business cannot grind to a halt and many documents have to get through,''
said Mr Bill McCall of Edinburgh stockbrokers Tilney &amp; Co. He added that the
Royal Mail should be concerned that firms would not return with their business
after the dispute because of the standard of service rendered by competitors.
ScotRail never recovered a large number of customers forced to use alternatives
such as buses or cars during a recent series of strikes.
``For the postal workers it could be a self-fulfilling prophecy,'' said Mr
McCall.
``Depending on the amount of business Royal Mail loses, they could find
themselves out of a job. But for the independent contractors - it's a
heaven-sent opportunity for them to make their mark.''
Royal Mail confirmed it was worried about the potential loss of business.
``All past experience of strikes means that we will lose customers,'' a
spokesman said. He suggested that all the strikers were doing was damaging the
long-term prospects of the business ``and in effect their jobs''.
Courier firms across Scotland were reporting greatly increased activity. Pony
Express in Edinburgh said its workload had doubled: ``Mainly from lawyers and
accountancy firms.'' The company charges about #7 for an overnight door-to-door
delivery, but firms are willing to pay the price and it has even had to turn
away business.
Mr Donald Hendry, at Falcon Couriers in Glasgow ,said it was equally busy. ``We
are building up a head of steam. We hope that some of the business will remain
with us after the dispute is over. It is making companies realise they have
other options.''
Eagle Couriers in Edinburgh reckons its normal workload has increased ``at
least six-fold over the past few days and is continuing to rise''. It has been
transporting franked Scottish bulk mail, destined for addresses in England,
across the border in a bid to get mail moving.
On Wednesday night the plan to ship mail to a sorting office in Newcastle ran
into difficulties when local management refused to accept Scottish mail in case
it caused a knock-on dispute. The mail was eventually accepted at Darlington.
A broadly similar dispute over changed working practices, which the CWU sees as
undermining second deliveries, closed Royal Mail operations throughout
Newcastle during April when official action by 900 staff at 15 offices halted
deliveries in the area for two weeks.
Earlier this year the union was fined #7500 and made to pay costs of some
#100,000 by the High Court when it was deemed not to have acted sufficiently
firmly to damp down an unofficial stoppage by members in North-west London in
protest at moves to improve first deliveries.
The union maintains that the action by its Scottish members, which it wants
legitimised through a legal ballot but is unable to achieve because ballot
papers are caught up in the postal backlog, is designed to preserve postal
services not undermine them. It accuses the Royal Mail of seeking to delay
second deliveries in order to load first deliveries.
Management rejects this, claiming that more post is going first delivery and
therefore fewer postal workers are required for second deliveries - which they
emphasise are not at risk.
The Royal Mail - subject to poor industrial relations - has suffered a series
of disputes over the closure of Crown post offices and revised working
practices, both of which impact on jobs.
The union sees little long-term damage to Royal Mail business because it still
enjoys a monopoly of letters under #1 and few businesses tend to stick with the
far higher courier rates once regular postal deliveries are restored.
Parcels are a different matter, but even so the Post Office's ParcelForce
subsidiary, which is the only carrier with an obligation to deliver nationwide,
still handles some 90% of domestic packages. But other carriers, such as TNT,
DHL, and United Parcels Service continue to make inroads.
</TEXT>
