<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mandela lunches with his prosecutor</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224878</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pretoria, Thursday
WHEN Nelson Mandela last met Percy Yutar, 31 years ago, the diminutive
prosecutor was trying to lock him up forever. Today, they had lunch.
Mandela has shown a knack for charming former enemies to bring reconciliation
to South Africa, but the meeting with Yutar stood above most.
In 1964, Yutar prosecuted Mandela and nine others for plotting sabotage to
bring down white minority rule in a trial that came to symbolise the injustice
of apartheid. All received life sentences.
Yutar criticised the defendants for appointing themselves to ``tell the entire
(black) population of this country, and indeed the whole of the world, that
they were suppressed, oppressed and depressed.''
Now 84, Yutar saw Mandela freed in 1990 and elected the nation's first black
president last year. That he was invited to lunch with the president
represents, say Mandela's staff, South Africa's need to forgive without
forgetting.
What does Yutar say now, after Mandela dined with him, put his arm around him,
shook his hand before the news media, and gently joked about remembering him
being taller?
``It shows the great humility of this saintly man who has done so much in this
short space of time, and I have no doubt whatsoever that he will achieve very
much more,'' Yutar said. ``All I can say, with all the sincerity at my command,
is may the Almighty bless him with good health and years.''-AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anger over MPs' New Zealand trip</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224879</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NINE members of the Commons Scottish Affairs Committee set off yesterday for a
12-day visit to New Zealand, at a potential cost to the taxpayer of more than
#50,000, leaving Westminster fuming at what one MP described as a ``costly and
nonsensical junket''.
Although the MPs - three Labour, one SNP, and five Tories, of which three are
English - were given permission to travel, they will miss next week's
announcement on constitutional changes by Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth,
as well as Tuesday's Budget.
Last night, MPs on all sides expressed dismay at the length and purpose of the
visit, which is part of the committee's study of Scottish agriculture. Some
Scottish MPs questioned the usefulness of any research by a committee which
includes a number of English Tory MPs.
They said it was inappropriate for the committee to undertake a questionable
fact-finding mission just weeks after the Commons agreed to tighter controls on
MPs' behaviour. Conservative, Sir Teddy Taylor, said there was nothing for the
committee to learn about Scottish agriculture in New Zealand.
``It's the most costly and nonsensical parliamentary junket I've ever seen in
31 years at Westminster,'' he said.
The MPs are travelling business class - current full-fare #4544 - and will
receive a daily living allowance of #120. Their visit includes several nights
in Queenstown, the exclusive mountain resort used by Commonwealth leaders at
the recent summit. A frontbench Labour MP dismissed the committee as ``a bunch
of wasters'', and added: ``I hope they're slated for it'', while an adviser to
Labour leader Tony Blair said, with obvious irony: ``I'm sure they will derive
a lot of benefit from it.''
Two members of the committee, Tory Allan Stewart and Liberal Democrat Ray
Michie, refused to go.
A spokesman for Ms Michie said: ``She would have liked to have gone but felt it
was too far and too long to be out of the country, and I'm sure the cost factor
was in her mind.''
The MPs who have gone are: Chairman William McKelvey, Labour MP for Kilmarnock
and Loudon; Mr David Marshall, Labour MP for Glasgow Shettleston; Mr Robert
Hughes, Labour MP for Aberdeen North; Mr Phil Gallie, Tory MP for Ayr; Mr Bill
Walker, Tory MP for Tayside North; Mr Andrew Welsh, SNP MP for Angus East; and
three English MPs, Mr Terry Dicks, Mr Tim Devlin, and Mr Peter Atkinson.
The presence of urban Labour MPs on an agricultural mission amused Tory MPs.
Dover MP David Shaw said: ``The interest of Glasgow Labour MPs in agriculture
is perhaps eccentric'', while Mr Alan Duncan, MP for Rutland, said: ``I look
forward to the greening of the Gorbals on their return.''
According to committee staff, the MPs will return on December 4. Two members,
Mr Dicks and Mr Marshall, left last Friday, a week ahead of their colleagues.
The MPs have permission from their whips to be away. They will be back in time
for the vote on the Budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nato leadership crisis deepens</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224881</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels, Thursday
NATO members are becoming worried over the time it is taking to find a new
chief for the Alliance - just as it faces the job of sending thousands of
troops to Bosnia.
``We have to settle this soon, but we don't seem to be making any progress. No
new candidates are emerging,'' said senior Alliance diplomat.
The delay is being blamed on a clash between the US and France.
When Belgium's Willy Claes resigned as secretary-general on October 20 over a
corruption scandal, Nato sources predicted he would quickly be replaced.
Former Dutch Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers emerged as the first choice of the
main European allies but was vetoed by Washington, which was concerned about
his knowledge of Bosnia.
The US subsequently made it clear it favoured former Danish Foreign Minister
Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, but Paris has said no to him.
France has shown no inclination to back down even though most other allies, and
particularly Britain and Germany, have indicated he would be acceptable.
Paris is upset about outspoken Scandinavian criticism of its nuclear tests in
the South Pacific and French diplomats say privately that President Jacques
Chirac will not give in, even at the cost of straining Alliance unity.
Last week Spanish Foreign Secretary Javier Solana was mentioned as a possible
compromise candidate, but Madrid has yet to present him and an early bandwagon
in his favour appears to have run out of steam.
Nato Foreign Ministers meet in Brussels on December 5 and want to anoint a new
secretary-general before despatching 60,000 Alliance troops to Bosnia in Nato's
riskiest operation yet.
``It is inconceivable that we have every one here and cannot name a new
secretary-general,'' said one Alliance source.
Diplomats say the issue is complicated by domestic American politics and by the
failure of London and Bonn to come out strongly for Ellemann-Jensen and
persuade France to fall into line.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Catholics to pool Lourdes efforts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224882</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Catholics are finding it too expensive to travel to the shrine at
Lourdes in France, according to the Scottish Catholic Observer newspaper.
All of Scotland's Roman Catholic bishops are due to meet on Monday to discuss
ways to cut the cost - including pooling resources for a national pilgrimage by
Euro-rail, instead of separate diocesan trips.
Sentence delayed
A YOUTH who grabbed and stripped a lollipop lady on her way to her duties in
Helensburgh, Dumbartonshire, was ordered to the High Court for sentencing
yesterday. At Dumbarton Sheriff Court, William McPhee, 21, of East Princes
Street, Helensburgh, admitted assaulting Mrs Mary McLean, 60, and resisting
arrest after he had been drinking.
Braveheart plea
AN SNP councillor has criticised Falkirk District Council for failing to mark
the Battle of Falkirk - when William Wallace fought the English - this year
instead of on its 500th anniversary in 1998. Councillor David Alexander claims
the area could benefit from an annual celebration to cash in on the so-called
Braveheart effect.
Motor cyclist killed
A MOTOR cyclist died last night after a four-vehicle pile-up on the A75 Gretna
to Stranraer road between Annan and Carrutherstown. The dead man's identity was
not disclosed as police tried to contact his next-of-kin. No-one else was
injured in the incident which happened near Stenries.
Deacon Billy
COMEDIAN Billy Connolly is to star as Deacon Brodie in a new 90-minute Screen
One film for BBC TV. The film will be shot in Scotland and London, starting on
January 22. Brodie was convicted in 1788 of a series of crimes in Edinburgh and
sentenced to be hanged on gallows he had designed.
Bomb warning
THE RUC issued a warning yesterday after phosphorous flares were washed up on
beaches along Northern Ireland's Antrim coast. Similar devices washed up in
Donegal were dealt with by the Irish army. Hundreds of the flares, believed to
have been dumped in the Irish Sea by the Army, have been washed up on
Scotland's west coast.
Pump alert
LOTHIAN Trading Standards warned yesterday that Penn Plax aquarium pumps,
possibly issued to 1000 outlets in Scotland, fail legal standards on electrical
insulation. They should be returned to vendors.
Wedding belle
ERSKINE-based designer Betty Macmillan won the Best Scottish Designer award at
the Best of British Bridal awards in London yesterday with a wedding outfit
modelled by Eileen Catterson - who is engaged to Wet Wet Wet singer Marti
Pellow. Ms Macmillan set up in business only a year ago.
Somerville inquiry
METROPOLITAN Police are to investigate how details of the arrest of ITN
newsreader Julia Somerville, 48, and her boyfriend Jeremy Dixon, 56, over
family snapshots, became public, it was announced yesterday.
Body found
A 28-YEAR-OLD Ayrshire man was found dead in Ruchill Park, Glasgow, yesterday.
Mr William McKenzie, of Darg Road, Stevenson, was found in bushes in the park.
His death may have been drug-related. A report will be sent to the
procurator-fiscal.
Fox rescue
FIREFIGHTERS in Edinburgh last night struggled for two hours to release a fox
trapped between two houses in Dean Path. They had to remove parts of an
internal and external wall before finally freeing the animal into the hands of
the Scottish Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police officer cleared of assault</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224883</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLICEMAN was cleared yesterday of elbowing a grandmother in the face during
a fight among guests in the foyer of Inverness Railway Club.
Mr Neil Robinson, 27, was accused of hitting Mrs Elizabeth Gribbins of Wyvis
Place, Inverness, when police raided a reception held after three christenings
on July 3. There were six arrests.
Woman shot
POLICE are investigating an incident in which a 20-year-old woman was shot in
the leg with an airgun pellet in the Allars Crescent area of Hawick.
Torness veto
BERWICKSHIRE councillors have called on the Health and Safety Executive to
postpone an application by Scottish Nuclear for a new site licence at Torness
nuclear power station following a leak at the Hartlepool power station until
reassurances are given on safety.
Menu of choice
A SHORT-LEET of 22 establishments have been drawn up from 91 nominations for
the final stages of the Scottish Borders Tourist Board's Best Eating Place
competition. The winners will be announced in January after secret visits by
judges.
Poppy card win
A 79-year-old ex-soldier yesterday won a #100,000 jackpot on a scratchcard game
which aims to raise #1m for the Poppy Appeal, organisers said. The Shropshire
pensioner, who has not yet been named, is the second person in two days to pick
up the #100,000 top prize in the Scratch-n-Win lottery game - run by Lord
Mancroft.
OBE for Braid
SCOTLAND'S oldest serving councillor, 83-year-old James Braid, who has
represented the East Neuk of Fife for more than 60 years, was presented with an
OBE yesterday for services to local government. He is a former provost of St
Monans.
Mole hunt
METROPOLITAN Police are to investigate how details of the arrest of ITN
newsreader Julia Somerville, 48, and her boyfriend Jeremy Dixon, 56, over
family snapshots, became public, it was announced yesterday.
Stab death
KIDNEY dialysis patient Barry Bosley, in his thirties, was found stabbed to
death at his home in Sarisbury Close, Tadley, Hampshire, yesterday.
</TEXT>
