<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour celebrates political sting</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor Brussels</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224884</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR was last night celebrating a St Andrew's Day political sting against
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth by making him subsidise plans for a Scottish
parliament.
Through the Labour-dominated Convention of Scottish Local Authorities (Cosla),
devolutionists have booked Scotland Europa, in the heart of Brussels, for a
presentation of its plans for a parliament in Edinburgh.
The presentation will be made by STUC general secretary Campbell Christie and
Labour Lothians Euro-MP David Martin, a vice president of the European
Parliament, on November 30 on behalf of the Scottish Constitutional Convention.
It will form half of a dual presentation for Labour's Home Rule plans. At the
same time Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson will be formally unveiling
the convention's blueprint for Scottish Home Rule in Edinburgh.
Mr Forsyth, an implacable opponent of a Scottish parliament, has made elaborate
plans to torpedo Labour's efforts by making his own St Andrew's Day
announcement on how the Tories would return a measure of political
decision-making to Scotland.
But last night it emerged that he had been outflanked in Brussels where the
Scottish Office is the paymaster of Scotland Europa whose members include
Labour-dominated Cosla.
As one of Scotland Europa's main members and financial subscribers, Cosla is
entitled to the use of the Brussels premises at no extra charge. Scotland
Europa - Scotland's ``embassy'' in the European Union - is funded by Scottish
Enterprise but makes a loss which is annually written off by the Scottish
Office under Mr Forsyth's direction.
This means he will, in effect, be subventing Labour's home rule presentation
which has the backing of the Liberal Democrats, trade unions, churches and many
other organisations, excluding the Tories and the SNP.
Mr Christie was travelling last night and unavailable but his deputy, Mr Bill
Spiers, confirmed the convention's move. ``In our campaign for a Scottish home
rule parliament we have in the past toured around the embassies of several EU
member states and petitioned the European Parliament,'' he said.
``It is entirely appropriate, therefore, that the Scottish embassy in Brussels
should be the launching pad for a parliament which is supported by such a wide
section of the Scottish people.''
Under Labour's proposals Scotland Europa would be transformed from a lobbying
force into a stronger political presence, in the style of a powerful German
lnder, and made directly answerable to a Minister in the Scottish parliament.
A Scotland Europa official last night described the booking as ``routine''. He
said a Cosla booking was not something which would be interfered with because a
conference room for a presentation was ``something which they have already
bought into''.
He added: ``This is not something we would refer to Edinburgh.''
</TEXT>
