<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Beatles' penny fame</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAOTIC business deals cost the Beatles a fortune and contributed to their
eventual split, a new documentary claims.
As their first new single in 25 years is about to hit the charts, Channel 4's
All You Need is Cash, to be screened on Monday, reveals that the Fab Four
received only 1p for a double sided record in royalties from EMI in their
heyday because manager Brian Epstein was so desperate to get a deal.
George Martin, who produced the records said: ``I don't think the deals he did
were too bad. He had no option and EMI were notoriously tight-fisted.''
The royalties even had to be split between the four and Epstein so they
actually only ended up with a fifth of a penny each.
Better contracts were renegotiated in 1967 and 1969 but by then Epstein was
dead after having also missed out on lucrative American merchandising deals
allowing an American company to take 90% leaving them only 10%.
The documentary, the result of extensive research in Britain and America, says
that when the Apple Corp was formed to look after their business affairs things
improved dramatically but the more Paul McCartney became involved, the more
John Lennon became annoyed and it began to sour their relationship.
Their accountant Harry Pinsker says that in their early days they had even
turned down a $3m Coca-Cola contract because they were afraid it would all go
in tax.
Now with the release of the new single, a series of albums and a six-part
documentary they are set to make around $100m this year alone, the programme
says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peres was next target, murder suspect claims</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANNY GUR-ARIEH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tel Aviv, Thursday
A SUSPECT in the assassination of Yitzhak Rabin told investigators that Prime
Minister Shimon Peres was to have been the next target, it was revealed today.
Police investigator Arieh Silberman told a Tel Aviv Magistrate's Court that
Dror Adani, suspected of conspiracy in the murder, admitted that he plotted
Rabin's assassination along with confessed killer Yigal Amir.
``Investigators asked Adani: `Was your ultimate intention to strike at both
Rabin and Peres and in this way to halt the peace process?' '' said Silberman.
``His response was: `Let's just say that both were defined as murderers whose
fate was death but we did not decide who was first. Perhaps if things had gone
smoothly with Rabin, we would have moved on to Peres'.''
Judges today ordered both Adani and Yigal Amir's brother, Hagai Amir, to be
held until November 30 when police expect to issue indictments.
Yigal Amir, a 25-year-old religious Jew, said he murdered Prime Minister Rabin
on November 4 to halt the handover of land for Palestinian self-rule but
insists he acted alone.
Police have arrested at least eight others since the murder, all religious Jews
in their 20s, suspecting them of various offences including conspiracy to
murder the 73-year-old leader and planning attacks against Palestinians.
In other developments today, new Foreign Minister Ehud Barak said Israel should
hold on to large tracts of occupied territory in any final peace settlement
with the Palestinians.
In a speech in central Israel, the former army chief made a clear grab for the
security mantle of his slain mentor, Rabin.
``We are now considering the possibility of making compromises with the
Palestinians and also with the Syrians. But we will not do this in a way that
will harm the basic security of the state of Israel,'' he said.
Barak went on to draw a map for the area in which East Jerusalem and areas in
the occupied West Bank captured in the 1967 Middle East war would remain under
Israeli control.
Israel, Barak said, should keep the Jordan Valley and Etzion areas in the
occupied West Bank as well as a corridor of Jewish settlements just over the
pre-1967 Middle East war border in the western part of the region.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Signing threat over pilots</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224887</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RELATIVES of French peacekeepers killed in former Yugoslavia threatened to
disrupt the signing of a peace deal in Paris unless two French pilots believed
held by Bosnian Serbs are freed.
The group said the formal signing of the peace deal clinched in Dayton,
expected early next month, must be put off until Captain Frederic Chiffot and
Lieutenant Jose Souvignet are released.
They have been missing for 11 weeks since their Mirage 2000 was shot down over
Bosnia during Nato raids around the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Pale. The group
said it ``demands that the Paris conference for the signing of the peace
accords be postponed indefinitely until the release of our fellow-
``If this is not done, a spectacular action may take place,'' it said.
The French National Assembly foreign affairs committee decided today to send a
mission to Belgrade to investigate the fate of the        two airmen.
The pilots were caught by Bosnian Serb forces but Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic has since said they were seized from a hospital by unknown kidnappers.
French officials have voiced fears they have been killed.
The relatives had earlier urged President Jacques Chirac to veto the lifting of
UN sanctions imposed on Serbia for its armed support of separatist Serb forces
until the pilots were released, but the request came hours after the Security
Council suspended the embargo.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Popski's Private Army parades again</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224888</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Veterans of No.1 Special Demolition Squadron - better known as Popski's Private
Army - recalled their glory days when they were reunited on the steps of the
Imperial War Museum in London, yesterday. The Special Forces unit, one of the
Second World War's most remarkable, was formed in October 1942 by Belgian-born
Lieutenant Colonel Vladimir ``Popski'' Peniakov, to carry out long-range raids
behind enemy lines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stand-off as mail dispute escalates Strikers jeer at union line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH and ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TALKS in a bid to end the postal strike broke down for the third successive
time last night. A three-hour meeting between union leaders and Royal Mail
managers in Edinburgh ended in deadlock.
A Royal Mail official claimed that progress had been made on a number of key
issues. However, management stuck to its three demands of an immediate return
to work, flexibility to deal with the backlog of mail, and resolution of the
flare-up at Portobello, which led to the strike, on terms agreed with the staff
before the intervention of officials of the Union of Communication Workers.
The postal workers continued to defy their full-time union officials yesterday,
despite having been told that the union could not help them unless they went
back to work.
The unofficial strike spread to Perth and Dundee, crippling deliveries across
the whole of Central Scotland. Up to 5000 workers have now gone on strike and
those attending meetings in Glasgow and Edinburgh voted to continue their
action.
Police in Edinburgh said a 28-year-old man was arrested after an incident
involving a Royal Mail van in Craiglockhart Avenue. A police spokesman said a
report was being prepared for the procurator-fiscal.
Earlier in the day, Mr Alex Gibb, Royal Mail delivery director, said they could
not resolve the dispute while the workers remained on strike. Management
attempted to persuade workers not to join the dispute by setting up a
confidential helpline on which management put their case. The strike began at
Portobello in Edinburgh where staff are unhappy at changes to their working
day. The changes would mean more mail going out in the first delivery. They
fear that it would eventually lead to the loss of thousands of full-time jobs
across Scotland and the greater use of part-time and casual workers.
The strength of support elsewhere suggests that postal workers are fed up with
what they describe as bullying tactics by a thoughtless, macho-style of
management.
Mr Gibb claims their fears are ``total rubbish''. He said: ``This illegal
action is taking place because of the last-minute intervention of the CWU in
objecting to plans worked up and agreed with staff in Portobello which were
aimed at improving service to customers who want to get their mail as early as
possible.
``The reality is we are now getting a great deal of mail through for the
morning's first delivery and we need to change the staffing structures to
ensure we have enough postmen and postwomen to deliver the extra mail on the
first delivery but that we are not over-staffed for the now very light second
delivery.''
Mr Bill Speirs, deputy general secretary of the STUC, said it was obvious from
the way the strike was spreading rapidly that something had gone badly wrong
with industrial relations in the Royal Mail in Scotland.
He urged management to ``see sense'' and set aside the changes imposed at
Portobello until they were properly negotiated with the union.
The Royal Mail confirmed that staff in Dundee, Perth, Inverclyde, Renfrew,
Bridge of Weir, Cupar, Glenrothes, and Burntisland had joined the action taken
by colleagues in Edinburgh and Glasgow.
More than 400 staff walked out in Perth and Dundee after they were asked to
process mail normally handled in Edinburgh.
Mr Joe Malone, CWU Tayside branch secretary, said: ``Staff decided on
industrial action after they were asked to carry out duties they wouldn't
normally carry out. As this is an unofficial strike, I must ask my members to
return to work but I fully understand their frustration and their reasons for
this action.''
He added: ``We are working to resolve the situation but when workers are asked
to carry out the duties of their striking colleagues, it is no wonder the
dispute has spread to Tayside.''
A Royal Mail spokesman said it had not been an unreasonable request. Because
the strike is unofficial, any support from the union could leave it open to
punitive damages in the courts. The union has attempted to stay within the law
by giving each striker a letter from the union's general secretary stating that
the union repudiated their action.
That was why Mr John Keggie, CWU East of Scotland organiser, told the workers'
meeting in Edinburgh: ``The official position is that until such time as we
return to normal work, we are going to have a difficulty and must abide by
trade-union legislation. There is no question of the union supporting us
without a ballot.''
However, he was shouted down and slow-handclapped by his members who voted
unanimously to stay out.
Later, on leaving the talks with Mr Gibb, Mr Keggie said he was deeply
disappointed no solution had been found.
He said: ``At first, the Royal Mail had been making very positive noises and
were even talking about arrangements for the recovery period for clearing the
backlog of mail when everyone was back at work.
``Then we had an adjournment and, for whatever reason, when we came back into
the room the mood of the management had changed. Yet again, talks broke down,
which we find very disappointing. And so the strike continues`.
Mr Gibb said: ``The stumbling block again concerns the work duties of staff at
our Portobello depot as implemented on Monday.
``While the union are prepared to discuss clearing the backlog of mail that's
gathering, the offer they made to us about the Portobello depot was quite
frankly rather woolly. Their attitude is one of let's wait and see what happens
once the backlog is cleared. We can't accept that attitude.''
Meanwhile, courier firms in Edinburgh say their business has doubled in the
last two days, and Jobcentres are making provisions for unemployment benefit
giros caught up in the mail backlog to be reissued in person.
Last night Royal Mail admitted it was using contract lorries to send batches of
mail for sorting at English centres to clear mail due for delivery south of the
Border.
The union's divisional officer, Mr George Robertson, said he was aware of the
practice but the union had issued instructions against any sympathy action.
``This is a Scottish issue at the moment and we have made it quite clear to our
colleagues in England that we do not want them to take any action. This is an
unofficial dispute and all we want to do is get our members back to work.''
q The public service union, Unison, has predicted a spring-time of industrial
unrest if the Government does not provide financial support for future pay
increases in the public sector.
</TEXT>
