<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour says leader of rail bid is debtor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224890</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE head of the company appointed by the Government to run one of the only rail
franchises to make it to privatisation was exposed last night as a director of
a double-glazing firm that went into liquidation with a trail of debts.
According to documents obtained by Labour, Mr John Ansdell was one of two
directors of Conservatories and Windows (UK) Ltd, which was wound up in May. He
is now director of Resurgence Railways, the Government's approved bidder for
the Great Western franchise.
Labour's transport spokeman Brian Wilson last night called for the resignations
of Transport Secretary Sir George Young and franchising director Roger Salmon
in the face of what he called ``a farce''.
``It confirms the depths of farce and desperation into which rail privatisation
has descended, that they are prepared to hand over the historic Great Western
Railway to a failed double-glazing salesman.
``This company has no record of running a passenger railway, yet they have
cleared every hurdle prior to the franchise being granted,'' he said.
Great Western Railway, which runs from London to the West Country and Wales, is
one of only three passenger franchises to have emerged with a chance of being
privatised before the next election, despite the Government's promise to sell
half of them by 1997.
Earlier this month, the Government announced it had chosen Resurgence Railways
Holdings Ltd as its favoured bidder for the franchise. Mr Ansdell is managing
director of the company, an off-the-shelf company set up earlier this year.
According to Labour, Conservatories and Windows Ltd had about 30 creditors when
it was wound up in court in Southampton. Mr Wilson said: ``Young and Salmon
must answer some questions. Did they know about Mr Ansdell's business record?
If not, they are incompetent beyond belief. If so, why was a liquidated double
glazier deemed fit to run a railway?''
</TEXT>
