<DOCNO>GH951124-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SAS killed 30 unarmed IRA men, says book</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUC chiefs in Belfast were yesterday considering an offer to pinpoint the
burial sites of 30 unarmed IRA suspects allegedly killed by the SAS in Northern
Ireland.
The killings are alleged in a book by a man, who uses the pseudonym Paul Bruce,
and claims to be a former SAS soldier.
The author faxed a letter to RUC Chief Constable Sir Hugh Annesley offering to
identify the exact position of the alleged burial sites.
In his book The Nemesis File, published this week, he alleges his squad carried
out the killings between 1971 and 1972 as part of a covert war against the IRA.
But the Ministry of Defence said it had serious doubts about Bruce's
credentials as a member of the SAS.
A spokesman said the book contained consistently inaccurate descriptions of SAS
recruitment and selection procedures, as well as references to SAS capabilities
that did not exist at the time.
Referring to the author's claims about the murders of members of the IRA, the
spokesman said: ``If that were the case it would be extraordinary if they had
not come to light before now.
``If the RUC take these allegations seriously then we are sure they will
investigate them.''
A Sinn Fein spokesman described Bruce's claims as ``totally outlandish'', and
said they should be taken with ``a large pinch of Siberian salt''.
</TEXT>
