<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scanning a less painful image</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224892</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW scanner which will revolutionize diag-nosis of a wide variety of medical
problems was unveiled at Ayr Hospital yesterday.
Mr Matthew Torrance, 43, from Cumnock, became the first patient to use the
Magnetic Resonance Imaging scanner at Ayr - and received the good news that his
knee problems may be treated without surgery.
The #1m scanner, the first of its kind in a district general hospital, has been
bought by Ayrshire Medical Support Ltd and will be operated by hospital staff.
The company is a non-profit making organisation headed by local businessman Sir
Donald Maclean, who stressed that there is no question of any patient having to
pay for the MRI service.
He said: ``This is an excellent example of a joint venture between the private
and public sectors.
``The facility will operate within the NHS and there is no question of patients
having to pay. It's a free NHS service, full stop.''
The new scanner uses a powerful magnetic field and radio waves to transmit the
clearest internal pictures possible for use in detecting and diagnosing a wide
range of problems, especially in the fields of orthopaedics, vascular
disorders, ENT, and gynaecology.
Dr Keith Osborne, consultant radiologist, said: ``The MRI scanner opens up a
wide range of possibilities for us where other investigative methods are not
available.
``It means in many cases that invasive surgery will be avoided because we
obtain such a clear picture of the area involved.''
Mr Torrance gave the scanner full marks for avoiding the need of an exploratory
operation.
q A similar scanning facility has now been installed at Crosshouse Hospital,
giving Ayrshire a choice of two of the revolutionary machines.
</TEXT>
