<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Serb leader wins over hard-liners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK Sarajevo, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224893</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Milosevic, boosted by lifting of UN
sanctions, wins pledge to negotiate.
SANCTIONS on Serbia ended and Bosnian Serb leaders agreed to accept the Bosnian
peace deal negotiated by Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic despite
objections to key parts of it, Yugoslav news agencies reported today.
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said Milosevic summoned hostile Bosnian Serb
leaders, including ``president'' Radovan Karadzic, to talks near Belgrade where
they endorsed terms he negotiated in their name at a summit in Dayton, Ohio,
this week.
However there was no authoritative confirmation from Bosnian Serb leaders and
the Bosnian Serbs' own media said tonight that the results of the Belgrade
talks were not yet known.
Bosnian Serb leaders have denounced the deal as a betrayal. The Bosnian Serb
news agency SRNA issued a commentary tonight demanding that its key territorial
provisions, including the handover of Serb areas of Sarajevo, be renegotiated.
Tanjug said Karadzic and the rest of the Bosnian Serb leadership had agreed to
``implement it in its entirety''.
The independent Belgrade news agency Beta quoted an unidentified ``high Bosnian
Serb official'' as saying: ``We had no choice, we must accept all points
provided by the peace agreement.''
Bosnia's Prime Minister welcomed the news. ``If it's true then it's good news
for all in Bosnia-Herzegovina,'' Haris Silajdzic told government television.
``We should start with co-operation for implementation as soon as possible,''
he added.
Bosnian Serb television told its viewers the results of the Belgrade talks were
not yet known.
Bosnian Serb agreement to the Dayton pact would be a fillip to President Bill
Clinton's drive to overcome opposition in Congress to the deployment of 20,000
US troops in a 60,000-strong Nato peacekeeping force.
Diplomats in Sarajevo say they fear Serbs might attack UN personnel to frighten
Congress into refusing to send them.
Karazdic's participation in the Belgrade talks was possibly one of the last
decisive acts of his role in the Bosnian Serb rebellion against Bosnian
independence.
He and army commander General Ratko Mladic are wanted by a UN war crimes
tribunal and so are barred from power by the treaty.
Some Bosnian Serb leaders are furious that Milosevic surrendered the Serb
sector of Sarajevo and agreed to impose a corridor across their territory from
the capital to the Muslim enclave of Gorazde.
Milosevic was determined to put the war and sanctions behind him and to stop
one million or so Bosnian Serbs holding hostage the economic future of rump
Yugoslavia, comprising Serbia and Montenegro.
Any serious violation of the treaty he agreed in the United States could lead
to the re-imposition of the trade and oil sanctions which the United Nations
suspended yesterday.
The sanctions were imposed in May 1992 to punish the Serbian leader for helping
the Bosnian Serbs fight Bosnian independence and have helped to cripple the
Yugoslav economy.
Countries neighbouring Serbia and Montenegro began to lift border controls as
ordinary Yugoslavs hailed a rebirth. The daily Vecernje Novosti trumpeted:
``Goodbye Sanctions!''
However economists ruled out a swift improvement in living standards and called
for market reforms of the state-dominated economy.
Yugoslavia will still lack access to credits, through organisations like the
International Monetary Fund or World Bank, to revive its decrepit economic
infrastructure.
Many people hoped that supplies of essential foreign goods and petrol would
improve.
Bosnian Serb leaders have only limited scope to defy Milosevic since their part
of Bosnia is effectively bankrupt and depends on economic and military support
from Serbia.
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic weighed in with a warning that his
Muslim-led government would pull out of the peace treaty if Nato did not arrive.
Several thousand from the Nato contingent are already in Bosnia as part of the
UN peacekeeping contingent that Nato will replace. They will simply switch
allegiance.
US Defence Secretary William Perry said during a visit to Macedonia today that
25 countries had said they would send troops to join the force.
Newcomers, including the US troops, will be deployed next month after the
presidents of Bosnia, Croatia, and Serbia formally sign the treaty in Paris.
The Nato mission will be laid down at a follow-up conference in London on
December 8-9.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
