<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman tells tribunal of abusive gestures</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN who claimed she was sexually harassed said she confronted her alleged
harasser and asked if he was aware of the stress he was causing.
The 47-year-old telephonist and receptionist claimed the man made abusive and
offensive gestures in front of her in the street on two separate occasions and
had deliberately bumped into her.
She also claimed he used to glare and stare at her while she was working at the
reception desk.
The woman and a 37-year-old colleague have taken their employer and the man
they accuse of sexually harassing them to a Glasgow industrial tribunal. The
tribunal has ordered that none of the parties can be identified until its
decision is issued.
The 47-year-old woman told the tribunal how the man had made a rude gesture to
her in the street. She said he had raised his hands and moved his lower body in
a thrusting motion.
On another occasion, she claimed he stuck his fingers in his mouth as if to be
sick.
She claimed her alleged harasser used to miaow as he passed her after they had
been to the theatre to see Cats.
She confronted him and asked if he was aware of the stress he was causing. ``I
was informed he was receiving counselling. I pointed out that I also was in
distress.''
She claimed he was trying to poison the atmosphere at the workplace and
contacted the Equal Opportunities Commission.
She received an advice booklet and decided to confront him over the telephone
but she said he replied: ``Don't be silly.''
After complaining about him, it was agreed that there was to be no eye contact
between the two for a period of four weeks.
She admitted a mirror was perched on the reception desk and used to see what
was going on behind as well as for cosmetic reasons. She also brought in a tape
recorder so that she could ``speak into it if things were happening to me''.
Solicitor Raymond Williamson, for the company, asked her: ``Wouldn't colleagues
think it odd you sitting at your reception desk with a rear-view mirror and a
tape recorder?'' Referring to the mirror, she replied ``It is sitting there in
front of me. It is dual purpose.''
The company and the alleged harasser deny sex discrimination. The EOC is
supporting the two women in their fight. The hearing will continue for a week
in the New Year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
