<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greenock wins race to harbour Tall Ships</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224895</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREENOCK has been selected as a destination for the Cutty Sark Tall Ships' Race
in 1999, raising hopes that up to #30m could be injected into the local
economy, it was announced yesterday.
The event was a big success when it was held in Edinburgh earlier this year. Up
to one million tourists provided a multi-million pound boost for the capital.
The ships' four-day stay in the town could bring similar benefits.
Around 100 of the world's most historic ships, with 3000 crew members, will
sail into Greenock for the event. The town beat off competition from 10 other
destinations in Belgium, Denmark, France and the United Kingdom.
The Greenock bid was backed by Inverclyde District Council, Renfrewshire
Enterprise and Clydeport.
Inverclyde provost Mr Allan Robertson said: ``This is a major event which will
give worldwide publicity to our area and will set the seal on the current
redevelopments under way in the town.''
The 1999 event will involve a race from St Malo in France to Greenock. From
there the ships will cruise up the west coast and on to Lerwick before
completing the final stage of the race to Aalborg in Denmark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Does being Chancellor not count for much?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Commons Sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INFLATION was 9.5% when he became Prime Minister. Now it was 2.9%, Mr Major
said proudly.
The Opposition howled with laughter, remembering, as Mr Major apparently
didn't, that his previous job was Chancellor of the Exchequer, to whom the
higher figure could be attributed.
A couple of Labour MPs thought the Commons should join the rest of the nation
in discussing Princess Diana's broadcast but Mr Major was constitutionally
correct or stuffy about that, though he did snap out one of the most menacing
one-liners of his career when asked about the intervention in the
post-interview debate of Mr Nicholas Soames. ``I do not expect any more
comments,'' he said quite fiercely.
The massive Mr Soames could crush Mr Major by sitting on him, but Prime
Ministers punch at a much heavier weight than Ministers of State. Mr Soames
could indeed be reduced to the role of butler to the Prince of Wales ascribed
to him by the populist Mr Andrew Mackinlay (Thurrock - Lab.) if, indeed, a
royal butler does rank lower than a Defence Minister in the great scheme of
things.
In the last Treasury exchanges before the Budget, the Chancellor perhaps spoke
for many of us in saying he was getting fed up with Labour harping on about
economic league tables. We have dropped from 13th to 18th in a world prosperity
league headed by Luxembourg, we were told for the umpteenth time. We are 20th
out of 24 in the OECD employment growth league. We are 21st in something called
the World Economic League.
Mr Michael Jack, a Treasury Minister, suggested this was Fantasy League stuff
and one would be inclined to sympathise if it were not that Ministers look with
such a benevolent eye on education league tables.
Mr Clarke, one of the few Chancellors bold enough to deliberately conjure up
the picture of a predecessor's resignation, said cheerfully that his Shadow's
position now looked ``unassailable''.
Mr Brown and Mr Alistair Darling challenged Ministers to deny that Labour's 10p
income tax band target was fairer than Mr Major's aspiration to abolish the
inheritance and capital gains taxes.
Mr Jack performed a couple of arias about the wonders of inherited wealth which
seemed to make it clear that the Budget will be aimed at those lapsed from the
true faith rather than seeking converts among the less well-off.
Mr Major successfully countered the latest Blair sound-bite about the 7p in the
pound of extra tax raised by his Government, saying that people now had much
higher net disposable income and lower mortgages than they had when his
Government started. The election will tell us which argument the electorate
find most impressive.
Mr Clarke, being lofty about Mr Brown's 10p tax, told him: ``I am not going to
counter you with 5p - we are not in a silly auction.'' So there we are. We know
in advance there will be no question on Tuesday of taxes being cut while we are
still borrowing heavily - don't we?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Student lending company passes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224897</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Glasgow-based Student Loans Company is working well, the Government's
financial watchdog has found after a thorough review of operations.
But university chiefs say the loan repayment system remains fundamentally
flawed. They say it is off-putting, unfair to students and graduates, and
should be changed.
Sir John Bourn, head of the National Audit Office (NAO), began an investigation
after the state-owned company's system for processing loans for repeat
borrowers broke down last year. The break-down resulted in lengthy delays
before about 35,000 students received their money, leaving many in distress and
hardship.
Sir John blamed weaknesses in planning and management in the company but these
difficulties had since been corrected, he said in his report.
About 50% of eligible students now take out a loan. According to the latest
figures, the company had collected almost 95% of monies due to be repaid.
However, the NAO said that, of a total outstanding loan portfolio of #1.8bn,
the company estimated #127m may not be recovered because of its borrowers'
entitlement to defer payment.
In an effort to recover money from defaulters, it has forecast a 75% increase
in collections department staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister's views on royals banned Major orders Soames to keep quiet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Photograph</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARMED Forces Minister Nicholas Soames is to play no further part in defending
the Prince of Wales against the media onslaught by his estranged wife.
The Prime Minister told the Commons curtly yesterday: ``I do not expect any
more comments.'' He was being urged to sack Mr Soames for accusing the Princess
of Wales of ``paranoia''.
Mr Soames, former equerry to the Prince of Wales, has been told by the Palace
and by the Prime Minister that he should make no further public comment.
At the same time, Mr Soames remains in his ministerial post with the full
confidence of the Prime Minister.
Mr Major's brief observation at Commons Question Time yesterday follows his
audience with the Queen last Tuesday night and a further meeting with her on
Wednesday night at the annual reception for foreign diplomats.
The Queen has not asked the Prime Minister to offer advice as to the
constitutional implications of the princess's insistence in her BBC Panorama
interview that she is not seeking a divorce. Both the Prince of Wales and his
wife have now publicly admitted adultery.
Yesterday's Cabinet was not obliged to discuss the situation because the Queen
has not asked her Government for advice.
The princess left yesterday for an unofficial ``charity'' visit to Argentina
and chatted happily to journalists on her plane during the 13-hour flight.
She expressed her delight that British public opinion after her broadcast -
watched by more than 21 millon viewers - has swung behind her in sympathy for a
woman who believes that the royal establishment cold-shouldered her when she
needed help and support, when suffering from post-natal depression and bulimia.
Buckingham Palace officials are now trying belatedly to bring her onside and
find a way to fulfil her publicly stated desire to be of service to the nation.
Yesterday the logistical details of her sensational broadcast - which is to be
repeated in Argentina and the United States over the next 48 hours - were
emerging.
The princess and the BBC worked on the Panorama interview over 17 hours of
filming which was edited down, with her having the final say, to an hour-long
broadcast. She was word-perfect and professionally projected as a result of
this immense effort.
In the Commons yesterday, Mr Major dead-batted an attack on Mr Soames from
Labour MP Andrew MacKinlay, who asked: ``Can you tell us whether or not you
will tolerate the Minister of State for Defence continuing to act as the Prince
of Wales's butler?
``Can we have an undertaking that the Minister will not speak on constitutional
matters, which are the sole preserve of the Prime Minister? Will you sack the
Minister of State for Defence for speaking out of turn against the Princess of
Wales?''
The Prime Minister replied: ``I do not expect any more comments, Madam
Speaker.''
Earlier, another Labour back bencher, Mr Tony Banks, had asked Mr Major: ``Do
you agree with the words of Mr Soames that Princess Diana is in an advanced
state of paranoia?''
The Prime Minister said that he had no intention of getting drawn into any
comment.
Immediately after the princess's Panorama interview on Monday, Mr Soames went
on television to state that she seemed paranoic in her comments about the
establishment - which she also described as ``the enemy'' - being against her.
q.There was no little evidence of support for Mr Soames among Tory MPs. Mr
James Hill, secretary of the Conservative Constitution Committee, said the
Prime Minister was ``quite right'' to take the action he did.
Sir Teddy Taylor, Tory MP for Southend East, said: ``I am delighted the Prime
Minister has made this statement. To have the Government involved in any way
whatsoever in this difficult and complex situation does no good for anyone.
``Most of us have sympathy for the Princess of Wales and what she said.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gonzalez aide in `dirty war' quiz</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Madrid, Thursday,
SPAIN'S Parliament today stripped a former Interior Minister and close ally of
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez of his immunity so that the Supreme Court can
interrogate him on a 1980s ``dirty war'' on Basque Eta rebels.
In one of the worst blows suffered by Gonzalez in his 13 years in office,
Parliament voted to allow the top tribunal to question Jose Barrionuevo,
Interior Minister during the illegal 1983-87 campaign, as a suspect on charges
of kidnapping, misuse of public funds, and association with an armed band.
``I have nothing to say, beyond accepting the outcome and facing the
circumstances ahead, legally and politically,'' Barrionuevo told reporters.
The vote does not in itself disprove the government's assertion that it knew
nothing of the ``dirty war'', but it brings the charges closer than ever to
Gonzalez.
Far from distancing himself from his former superior, Barrionuevo described him
after today's vote as ``one of my companions and one of my friends''.
The premier, who has reluctantly promised an early General Election in March,
blames a huge conspiracy by dark economic forces for mounting accusations over
the anti-Eta campaign and a series of corruption scandals. The opposition
scorns the theory.
Barrionuevo was Gonzalez's first Interior Minister from 1982 until 1988, when
he took over transport and communications in a reshuffle coinciding with early
court inquiries into the campaign of bombings, kidnappings, and murders which
killed 27 people between 1983 and 1987.
The Supreme Court heard a former head of covert operations testify yesterday
that Spain's military intelligence service had provided arms, forged documents,
and crucial information to the Anti-Terrorist Liberation Groups (Gal) - a front
for security forces and hired gunmen.
Gal's campaign, most of which took place in southern France, was a war of last
resort aimed at ending the bloodshed by Eta (Basque Homeland and
Freedom).-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strike gives SSO movement problem</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224900</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
in Bordeaux
THE BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, which is on tour in France, looks set to
be marooned in Bordeaux today by a 24-hour national transport strike.
The 72-strong orchestra - due to give a concert tonight - was to fly north to
Metz, near the German border, and set out for Bordeaux airport early this
morning, with no real idea if its charter plane would be able to take off, or
any guarantee of reaching the next destination in its two-concert tour.
Paris-based tour promoter, the IMG group, was in constant touch with the French
Ministries of Transport and Culture in a bid to find alternative routes and
methods of transport for the orchestra.
Last night, after a highly successful concert with percussionist Evelyn Glennie
in Bordeaux, BBC's head of music Hugh MacDonald announced to the orchestra that
the group would assemble early and go to the airport this morning.
``There is just a small chance that our plane might be able to take off,'' said
Mr MacDonald. ``We won't know until we get to the airport, but we really ought
to try.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour council raps accountant for doctoring department's books to tune of #317,000.   Call for action over false accounts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224901</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE councillors are insisting that disciplinary action against a
council accountant, who admitted doctoring a direct labour department's books
to make them look good, does not go far enough.
The minority Conservative group on Strathkelvin District Council feels that as
well as instituting disciplinary proceedings against Mr Alex McKenzie for
falsifying the accounts of the authority's Community Maintenance Services, a
report should be submitted to the procurator-fiscal.
The Conservatives are expected to push for this at a full council meeting next
week.
Councillor Ian Young, leader of the Conservative Group on Strathkelvin
district, declared: ``I've got reservations about the whole issue. In addition
to the disciplinary action, I want a report sent to the procurator-fiscal.
``I'm also concerned that the report has been collated, to a greater or lesser
extent, by people who were potentially culpable in allowing the situation to
arise. In so doing, they are being protected by the administration group who
for years have held up the CMS as a prime example of a direct labour
organisation.''
According to a council report, Mr McKenzie had admitted falsifying the accounts
in order to protect CMS and ensure it achieved its statutary 6% rate of return
for maintenance services.
The initial problem had arisen as a result of unexpected additional costs of
around #100,000 in respect of municipal trading contracts with Clydebank
District Council. These accounts had effectively been closed by the end of
1991/92 minus the additional costs which meant that these had to be ``lost''
during 1992/93.
It had also been established that certain other costs relating to purchases of
material and services had not been included in the correct years. Having
discovered the cost omission error, Mr McKenzie had decided to write the
balance of costs against 1992/93 trading.
However, this did not succeed because of reduced profit levels and the scenario
was carried on into 1993/94.
Consequently, CMS's results for the trading years 1991/92 to 1993/94 were
distorted by a final total of more than #246,000 arising from the
``fraudulent'' action taken by the accountant, plus nearly #71,000 arising from
accounting errors, giving a total of just over #317,000.
It was established that the falsification of income figures was effected by
arbitarily adding seemingly random amounts to genuine entries to achieve the
desired result.
Explaining his course of action to his superiors, Mr McKenzie said he had
perceived a distinct need to protect and support the organisation, especially
as the main problem contract was with another local authority.
While municipal trading was lawful, he had been aware of the Accounts
Commission's hostility to such trading and feared that a poor performance in
this particular contract might have provoked a prohibition order from the
commission which in turn would have had a detrimental effect on CMS's future
commercial viability.
Mr Michael Donohoe, a senior member of the Labour-controlled council, said the
council would take steps to address the problem and might possibly call for
further investigation.
q.THE Scottish Office said yesterday it had saved more than #10m on the
contracts for the by-pass linking Edinburgh to the M8 extension and the A74
extension.
A statement said that, under its Alternative Tendering Initiative, launched six
years ago by the Scottish Office Roads directorate, #8m had been saved on the
#40m M8 by-pass and #2.6m on the #13m A74 project.
The initiative allows contractors freedom to design and manage works - speeding
the resolution of difficulties.
The A74 Ecclefechan-Eaglesfield by-pass is being opened today by Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton, the Scottish Office Roads Minister. On December 11, he will
open the M8 extension (Claylands to Edinburgh city by-pass).
</TEXT>
