<HEADLINE>`No escape' as Tamil rebels surrounded</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Colombo, Thursday
THE Sri Lankan army has cut off the rebel-held town of Jaffna, leaving no
escape route for an estimated 2000 Tamil tiger guerrillas holed up there, an
army spokesman said today.
Brigadier Sarath Munasinghe told a news conference: ``Tigers are trapped in the
town. They have to jump into the sea, bite cyanide, or surrender.''
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam usually carry a cyanide capsule to avoid
capture.
Munasinghe said troops had killed at least 100 rebels in heavy fighting, and
wounded more than 250. Seventeen soldiers were also killed, with five officers
and 88 soldiers wounded.
The capture of the Jaffna to Kandy highway - a supply lifeline - and a ban on
travel across the Jaffna Lagoon, a waterway used by civilians and rebels to
reach the mainland, had also helped tighten the army's grip on the rebel
capital, he said.
Earlier, officials said the army advance on Jaffna had been slowed, but not
stopped, by the fatal crash yesterday of a transport plane loaded with
troops.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
