<HEADLINE>`Gagging' teacher goes back to school Hotline set up for worried parents</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HEADTEACHER who gagged a chatterbox pupil with sticky tape has kept his job.
Mr Alex Christie, 46, will go back to work on Monday at the school in Central
Scotland where he assaulted a 10-year-old boy by wrapping tape around his mouth
in the classroom.
The reprieve was revealed yesterday by Central Regional Council.
An education authority spokeswoman said a special telephone ``hotline'' had
been set up for any anxious parents who wanted to discuss ``concerns'' about
the teacher's return to school.
Last night, the boy's father, who cannot be named for legal reasons, said: ``I
am not making any comment until I have seen my lawyer.''
After the assault earlier this year, the boy's parents demanded that Mr
Christie be given the sack. They said then: ``We don't want that man anywhere
near our son again.''
Yesterday, the region's acting director of education, Dr Graeme Young, said a
disciplinary hearing had found the head teacher guilty of ``gross misconduct''.
He said: ``The education service held a disciplinary hearing to discuss Mr
Christie's case and try to make sure an incident like this does not happen
again.
``We found Mr Christie guilty of gross misconduct. He has been issued with a
final written warning, which will remain in force for two years, and cautioned
on his future behaviour.''
Dr Young added: ``In making this decision, we have taken into account Mr
Christie's long record of teaching with the school and the education authority.
``Mr Christie himself has assured us that he wants to put the incident behind
him and that he will do his best for the pupils at the school.
``We believe Mr Christie will use all his efforts to achieve this.
``In the interests of the pupils, we hope we can now consider this matter
closed and allow the school to return to normal.''
Last month, Mr Christie was put on ``probation'' by his profession's watchdogs,
the General Teaching Council.
The council's disciplinary committee branded his action as ``professionally
disreputable and foolish''.
Nevertheless, they left the door open for him to go back to the classroom by
deferring judgment for a year.
His career hinged on the decision by his employers, Central Regional Council.
Mr Christie was fined #350 at Falkirk Sheriff Court in June this year, after he
pled guilty to the assault.
Mr Christie had been suspended on full pay in February, when police launched an
inquiry into the primary classroom assault.
The court heard that the teacher taped the boy's mouth as a joke after the lad
kept talking instead of getting on with his school work.
However, procurator-fiscal Sarah Livingstone said: ``The joke went too far and
the youngster was humiliated in front of his pals.''
She added: ``Mr Christie was taking the class because the normal teacher was at
a funeral.
``The boy had been shouting out answers in response to various work in the
classroom.
``Mr Christie beckoned the boy out with his finger. He put Sellotape around the
child's mouth.
``It didn't completely cover the boy's mouth or nose but the boy had difficulty
breathing.''
The fiscal said the boy later told police that he was beginning to cry because
he was humiliated. ``He felt uncomfortable in front of the class who were
laughing at him.''
After five to 10 minutes, the headmaster helped the boy remove the tape.
In a statement to police, Mr Christie, head of the school for 12 years, said he
had done it as a joke. He said: ``The child was amused by it.''
His solicitor, Mr Stewart Neilson, said Mr Christie deeply regretted his
actions. ``It was foolish and wrong.
``He had no intention of causing any suffering, harm or distress to the child.''
Mr Christie said after the court hearing he would not comment until all
disciplinary procedures were complete.
</TEXT>
