<HEADLINE>Boy denies #4000 robbery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224904</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN 11-year-old boy charged with stealing more than #4657 from a locked safe
told a police officer his mother and his solicitor had advised him not to
answer any questions.
The boy, who cannot be named for legal reasons, also swore at another police
officer shortly after he was arrested in Dundee on suspicion of stealing the
money, Aberdeen Sheriff Court heard yesterday.
He denies stealing the money from the safe at the Cocket Hat South Filling
Station in North Anderson Drive, Aberdeen, after opening it with a key in
January this year.
Detective Constable Laura McKay, 27, of Grampian police, told the court that
shortly after starting an interview with him, the boy pulled a piece of paper
out of his pocket. ``It stated, and I saw it: `On the advice of my solicitor
and my mother I am not prepared to answer any questions','' said DC McKay.
Earlier, the petrol station's assistant manageress, Marie Glennie, told the
court the boy had been found at the rear of the offices after his mother had
reported him missing.
The trial was adjourned until November 28.
</TEXT>
