<HEADLINE>Row over separate time zone for Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224905</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FRESH Commons row broke out yesterday over the prospect of Scotland being in
a different time zone from the rest of the country, and indeed the rest of
Europe. Dumfries, for example, could be on different time from Carlisle.
The idea was strongly attacked by Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, who put
himself at odds with Mr John Butterfill, the Tory MP for Bournemouth West, who
is putting forward a measure to move the clocks forward an hour, bringing
Britain into line with Central European Time.
His proposal has topped the ballot for Private Member's Bills in the coming
session of Parliament, but last night Mr Forsyth argued it was unworkable and
could undermine the Union.
The effect of Mr Butterfill's proposal would be that if the sun rose in London
at 9am it would be at least 10am, or even 11am, in Scotland before children
could walk to school in daylight, farm workers could take to the fields in
daylight or construction workers could work without using floodlights.
Mr Butterfill's Bill may not become law, but the fact that he is first in the
ballot means that at least the subject will once again be raised in the Commons.
He told The Herald yesterday that the statistical evidence supported his
proposals, but he said that if Scots MPs tabled amendments against his plans he
would not stand in their way.
He questioned whether ``the whole of British time and the whole of how we run
should be dictated by crofters in the west of Scotland,'' and added: ``If
Scotland wants its own time, it would then be different from the rest of
Europe, but if Scottish MPs want to propose that on my Bill I would not oppose
it.''
Mr Butterfill, who claims to have support from organisations such as the Royal
Society for the Prevention of Accidents, the Police Federation, Age Concern,
the British Tourist Authority and the CBI, said there would be huge benefits
from what he is putting forward.
He claimed there would be 660 fewer deaths a year from road accidents because
there would be more light in the evenings, the benefit to tourism would be
about #1bn a year, and the reduction in road accidents would save health
authorities about #200m annually. ``There are other major reasons for this,
quite apart from the benefit to business,'' he said.
Mr Forsyth said: ``I would be very surprised if the Government gave such a Bill
the time of day, because the case for change has not been made.''
He claimed it would profoundly disadvantage Scots and was not something
farmers, in particular, would welcome. ``It is the sort of thing I would expect
to hear from a Scottish Nationalist, not a Conservative and Unionist.
``We are one United Kingdom and we do not want to be divided by a time zone. I
think if something is working and working well there is no need to fix it.''
Opinion among Opposition Scots MPs varied, but most were hostile.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said he personally was opposed to
the idea but recognised there would be a range of views within the Scottish
group. He said he had seen the statistical evidence, but was not persuaded by
it. However, Labour MPs would have a free vote on the Bill.
Scottish Labour MP George Foulkes (Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley) said he
would support the Bill. He realised Scots MPs were divided on the matter, but
he believed there was evidence that road accidents would be reduced by a change
to ``universal time.''
For the Liberal Democrats, Fife North-East MP Menzies Campbell said: ``We have
no party line on this, but my views on this issue are based entirely on the
interests of my constituency because the further north you are in Britain the
more disruiptive change would be.
``In a rural seat like mine, farming would be substantially inconvenienced and
school children who have to travel many miles to school by bus would have to do
so in the dark.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said he was concerned about Scottish children going to
school in the dark, and argued he would be happy to have a separate time zone
if it reflected ``geographic reality.'' He also said that if Mr Butterfill was
in favour of Scotland having its own time zone, perhaps he could extend that to
supporting Scottish independence in other areas.
</TEXT>
