<HEADLINE>Terrorist trial told of gun in pub</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LOYALIST delegate at the Northern Ireland peace talks came to Scotland with a
gun, it was claimed yesterday.
The High Court in Glasgow heard that Mr Lindsay Robb lifted up a man's leg in a
Falkirk public house and placed what looked like a gun in a polythene bag under
his trouser leg.
Mr Michael Anderson, 23, told Mr Ian Bonomy, QC, prosecuting: ``It felt like it
was there for two minutes. Then he lifted my leg up again and took it back.''
Mr Anderson said Mr Robb had arrived from Northern Ireland on June 22 at Tam
Bain's public house in Laurieston, Falkirk, with fellow members of the
Craigavon Protestant Boys' Flute Band.
While they had gone by bus, Mr Anderson claimed that Mr Robb had come by plane.
However, Mr Anderson said Mr Robb had asked one of the band members to get his
bag out of the bus and he brought out what appeared to be a gun.
Mr Robb, 28, of Mournview Avenue, Lurgan Avenue, is one of six men on trial
accused of conspiring to further the cause of the outlawed Ulster Volunteer
Force by acquiring firearms, ammunition, and explosives, intending to endanger
life or cause serious injury to property in the UK or the Irish Republic.
They also deny trafficking in drugs to raise money for terrorism.
On trial with Mr Robb are: John Johnston, 49, of Campbell Crescent, Laurieston;
Francis Hives, 45, of Prescott Road, Liverpool; William McArthur, 42, of Ure
Crescent, Bonnybridge; David White, 23, of Northburn Avenue, Airdrie; and
Alexander Davidson, 23, of Greenhill Park, Lurgan, Northern Ireland.
Mr Anderson claimed Mr Johnston said he was going to Liverpool to ``see two
gangsters'' to get sub-machineguns and ammunition for the UVF.
Earlier, Special Branch detectives and tactical firearms officers told of a
surveillance operation on Mr Johnston and the two other Scots accused, Mr
McArthur and Mr White, who travelled by car from Falkirk to a Liverpool public
house.
On the return journey, the car was stopped in Airdrie by armed police. The jury
heard that the three men were hauled out at gunpoint.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
