<HEADLINE>Price rises for water to be kept within 15% Backlash feared</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EXCLUSIVE By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government                                                   ...</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224907</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHARGES to be levied by the new water authorities which take over council-run
services in April are causing concern at the Scottish Office.
Ministers are understood to have told the three new public authorities that
they will not sanction increases of more than 15% next year.
They have apparently decided that any larger rises in the first year of the
controversial new quangos would not be publicly acceptable.
The chairman of the new Scottish Water and Sewerage Customers' Council, Mr Dick
Douglas, has already warned that rises of 15% would be hard to justify.
Even if the rises were eventually pegged at 15%, increases of four or five
times the rate of inflation would be bound to provoke a damaging political row,
with the Government's opponents united in claiming that the services should
never have been removed from council control.
The threat to cap charges is also likely to worsen the extremely difficult
financial situation facing the water quangos, some of whose members and
officials are now complaining privately that the Scottish Office has seriously
underestimated the cost of changing over to the new regime.
The Herald understands that the East of Scotland Authority, based in Edinburgh,
has calculated that it actually needs an increase of around 25% in charges
compared to this year to meet its spending requirements. However, it also
recognises that such a huge increase would be unacceptable.
ESWA takes over water and sewerage services previously run by Lothian, Borders,
Fife, Central, and Tayside regions. It is known to be facing a serious lack of
funding in its first year and severe Government restrictions on the amount of
money it can borrow. Also, it cannot call on any reserves. These were spent by
the regional councils last year to keep down charges.
As a result it is believed already to face serious problems in carrying out
even essential parts of its planned capital spending programme.
Earlier this year, ESWA identified a shortfall of #300m in the total spending
plans of the outgoing regional councils over the next five years and the amount
of Government funding likely to be agreed.
Charges proposed by the three new authorities have to be approved by the
customers' council, which was set up to act as a public watchdog. Charging
schemes were originally due to have been submitted to the council by the end of
last month but have been delayed.
In the event of a confrontation between any of the new authorities and the
customers' council, the matter goes to Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth to be
resolved. At this stage, he would be expected to refuse any increase of more
than 15%.
</TEXT>
