<HEADLINE>West will guard her secrets Police forces told not to expect any fresh information</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224908</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Journey's end for Rosemary West as she arrives by prison van at Durham's
maximum security jail.
THE detective superintendent who headed the inquiry that led to Rosemary West's
conviction on 10 counts of murder yesterday warned other forces, including
Strathclyde Police, not to expect any assistance from her in investigations
into other possible killings.
``She is a prisoner and has the rights of a prisoner but she has never helped
this investigation from the first day,'' Detective Superintendent John Bennett
told a news conference. ``I can't see, in the short term, that she will help me
or anyone else.''
He can only hope that once appeal procedures have been completed, West might be
able to throw some light on investigations into other deaths.
In Scotland, it is possible that Fred West killed four young girls.
He had spoken of 20 additional victims in the Gloucestershire area before he
committed suicide in prison on New Year's Day.
Yesterday, Gloucestershire Constabulary made it clear there would be no fresh
diggings for bodies based on speculation.
However, it was equally obvious that the force fear that the remains of other
young girls lie buried somewhere in their area.
As Gloucestershire officers yesterday spoke about the investigation which began
on the suspicion that only Heather, eldest child of the Wests, might have been
buried at 25 Cromwell Street, Rosemary West was being transferred from
Winchester to Durham prison.
Police motorcycle outriders led the way as her van pulled out of Winchester.
The police driver and the officer who sat in the passenger seat wore
bullet-roof vests. In the back, Rosemary West was in a special cage with
officers sitting just outside but keeping a close watch on her.
She will be scrutinised 24 hours a day to ensure that she does not attempt
suicide. The prison authorities are well aware of Fred West's suicide note in
which he declared that he waited for her to join him and fulfil their promise.
In Durham, Rosemary West will renew an acquaintanceship with Myra Hindley.
The pair met when Rosemary West was sent there as the investigation into her
crimes proceeded.
It was a decision which infuriated her trial judge, Mr Justice Mantell.
Rosemary West and Myra Hindley are the only women in Britain who know that they
are likely to spend the rest of their natural lives in jail.
Yesterday, in Cheltenham, Chief Constable Tony Butler told journalists that,
despite speculation about other bodies, there was no evidence to support a
search for more remains.
He would await recommendations from Detective Superintendent Bennett about
future actions and would not be pushed into decisions based on media
speculation.
Mr Bennett said that following the police appeal concerning nine untraced girls
immediately after Rosemary West had been sentenced, information had come from
12 individuals. That, he said, was a reasonable response.
The police, he said, were seeking information on the nine girls who had been
linked to 25 Cromwell Street for the sake of completeness. Nevertheless, he had
good information on one of the nine girls. He would not elaborate on what that
meant.
His team alone still had more than 1000 further lines of inquiry of all
descriptions.
Rosemary West's solicitor joined in the criticism over the money being paid by
the press to witnesses.
What has not been disclosed is that, in the midst of the trial at Winchester, a
London-based tabloid newspaper put in a bid for her story. Had she been
acquitted, the money on offer was far in excess of anything that will be paid
to anyone as a result of this trial.
Torment goes on  17
</TEXT>
