<HEADLINE>SNP plea to Clarke on whisky tax</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robbie Dinwoodie Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224909</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By ROBBIE DINWOODIE, Scottish Political Correspondent
THE SNP yesterday urged the Chancellor to stop ``victimising'' the Scotch
whisky industry and called on Labour to back its call for a 10% cut in duty as
a step towards equalising tax on drink.
The #7.37 taken by the Government on each #11 bottle of Scotch means that of
the eight billion nips downed each day the value of 5 billion are ``washed down
the Treasury's gullet,'' the SNP said.
Party business spokesman Fergus Ewing said Scotland had suffered the hangover -
``12,000 direct jobs have been lost, tens of thousands more indirect, and 40
distilleries have closed since 1979.''
The SNP's recent budget provided for a 10% cut in excise duty on spirits, which
would have cost a Scottish Exchequer up to #13m but boosted the industry.The
SNP figures were checked with the Scotch Whisky Association, which - although
it shies away from party politics - confirmed their accuracy.
The SNP implied tacit SWA support yesterday, and also disbursed, with
permission, nips of Macallan malt - again hinting at covert industry support
fuelled by growing frustration with the Government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Threat to ban payments to witnesses</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224910</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAW chiefs yesterday threatened to ban the media from making payments to
witnesses in court cases in the wake of the Rosemary West trial.
The Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay, has commissioned a high-level report into
cheque-book journalism after several witnesses in the case at Winchester Crown
Court admitted receiving up to #100,000.
Attorney General Sir Nicholas Lyell yesterday argued there was ``a strong
case'' for a change in the law.
Lawyers fear the lure of massive payouts may encourage witnesses to exaggerate
their evidence to boost its financial value.
Sir Nicholas told BBC Radio Four's Today programme that he was ``seriously
considering'' making cheque-book journalism illegal in court cases.
The newspaper watchdog, the Press Complaints Commission, announced on Wednesday
it would review the issue of payments to witnesses at a full meeting next week.
At least seven witnesses at the West trial admitted taking payments from the
media, ranging from #750 to a possible #100,000. There were allegations that
some witnesses were not called at all because of concerns that their evidence
would be undermined by the cash they had received.
The chief constable of Gloucestershire is preparing a report on media
involvement in the West trial which is to be sent to the Attorney General.
Sir Nicholas told Radio Four's Today programme: ``This case has seen more
buying up of witnesses' stories than we've seen for very many years. It does go
back to the Moors murders and since then in the Jeremy Thorpe case and in the
Yorkshire Ripper case there has been some incidence of it.
``But here we've got something like 20 incidents and it goes absolutely
contrary to the code of practice that was agreed by the newspaper industry
themselves.''
Both defence and prosecution lawyers had expressed concern over press buy-ups,
he said.
However, solicitor Christopher Murray, head of law at Kingsley Napley - a law
firm involved in the Jeremy Thorpe trial - said he would not ``be very
comfortable'' with a change in the law.
He told BBC Radio Four's World at One that ``as soon as you start to put
statutory legislative controls on the press, it is perhaps the first step down
the slippery slope.''
Top media barrister Geoffrey Robertson QC - who conducted an inquiry into the
commission's predecessor, the Press Council - denounced press self-regulation
as an ``utter fraud''.
He said: ``It is a confidence trick played by an organisation called the Press
Complaints Commission, which is funded by and acts entirely in the interests of
the media and the newspaper industry.''
Chief Constable Tony Butler, the man preparing a report on media involvement in
the West trial, told a Cheltenham press conference yesterday: ``My concern is
that the officers felt there was a sense of Russian roulette being played in
this trial.
``We were never sure that there was something that would not happen tomorrow
that would blow it out of the water. We should not have these anxieties.
``Are we running criminal justice as an entertainment business, or something
that the public has confidence in and that will deliver justice?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yarrow contract staves off 100 redundancies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON and KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224911</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YARROW Shipbuilders clinched a major new contract yesterday which will
temporarily safeguard the future of more than 100 jobs at their Glasgow yard.
A total of 415 redundancies were announced two months ago and the future of 315
workers still hangs in the balance as the company waits to hear if any other
orders are in the pipeline.
Yesterday's contract was for a 1500-tonne gas tanker hull for shipbuilders A&amp;P
Appledore. Work will start immediately at the Scotstoun yard and is expected to
be completed mid-1996.
Mr Murray Easton, Yarrow's managing director, said the contract came about as a
result of months of effort to reduce redundancies.
The results of tenders submitted for a contract to build three Type 23 frigates
are expected next month. Even if Yarrow wins the contract, Mr Easton said it
will not safeguard the future of the 315 workers.
``The contract will affect any future redundancies we may have to make in the
New Year,'' he said. ``But we are searching for work in the market and we have
lots of enquiries in that respect.''
A shop steward at Yarrow, who did not want to be named, said last night: ``The
news that we have got the Appledore contract has been welcomed by everyone at
the yard.''
Ferguson shipbuilders of Port Glasgow yesterday launched the third ship it has
built for an English ferry company and the fourth vessel it has launched this
year.
However, the company admitted that it is still trying to secure its first order
since the yard was taken over by millionaire businessman Frank Dunnet five
months ago.
The #8m ship Red Eagle was built for the Red Funnel Group and will be the new
flagship for the Southampton-Isle of Wight ferry operator.
Ferguson's made a pre-tax profit of #1.5m last year on sales of #19.3m.
Mr Dunnet described yesterday's launch as a highlight, because it was the first
since the takeover, and said he was delighted for Ferguson's workers ``who can
be proud of another splendid vessel''.
The new 500-tonne deadweight Raptor-class ship will join the Ferguson-built Red
Falcon and Red Osprey ferries, which entered service last year, when it does
likewise next March.
</TEXT>
