<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SB Holdings income accelerates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224912</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SB Holdings, the largest bus operator in Strathclyde, yesterday announced a
212% jump in pre-tax profits to #6.55m in the year to March 31.
The company was created by an employee buy-out of Strathclyde Buses from
Strathclyde Regional Council in 1993 and operates a fleet 1350 buses under the
banners of Strathclyde Transport, GCT, and Kelvin Central Buses.
The company doubled its profits despite an exceptional #1.1m charge relating to
its merger with Kelvin Central Buses 12 months ago.
Turnover was up 24% at #72.1m as passenger numbers continued to grow, but
before it can expand further it must settle the future of a controversial 20%
stake owned by Stagecoach.
The Perth-based bus group is resisting a Government order to sell the stake in
SB Holdings, which it purchased for #8.2m in December 1994.
The Board of Trade ordered the divestment in April after protests that
Stagecoach was infringing competition rules, but the case comes up for judicial
review in January.
SB Holdings is delaying decisions on future acquisitions or a possible stock
market flotation until the issue is resolved.
``We are in a position to pursue a number of alternative strategies but, until
we know how this (divestment ruling) turns out, it's hard to commit to any one
course,'' said executive chairman Peter Shaw.
``We are clear about our objectives, which are to enhance shareholder value
while taking account of the interests of our employees and customers,'' he
added.
Mr Shaw said, that if Stagecoach was forced to sell, SB Holdings would buy its
stake. The 20% share will not be sold to another minority investor.
SB Holdings has increased the number of passengers carried per year by 3% since
1986-87. That compares favourably to a 20% decrease in bus passengers
throughout the UK during the same period.
Mr Shaw attributed the company's success to the efforts and positive attitudes
of its 3700 employees, who own 80% of its shares.
SB Holdings has spent #9m on new buses over the last year and #16m has been
committed to purchases in 1996 to help modernise the fleet.
All its buses meet the latest European emission control standards. ``There is
no current requirement to conform to the Euro Two standards, but we thought it
was the best way to go,'' Mr Shaw said, adding that these would probably be
made mandatory in the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aitken wants a birthday present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224913</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN manager Roy Aitken will celebrate his thirty-seventh birthday today
with one wish in mind - to upstage his one-time understudy, Dundee manager Jim
Duffy, once again.
The pair were rivals at Celtic Park for a central defensive role, but it was
Roy who emerged the winner.
Duffy, who will face his former adversary in the Coca-Cola Cup final at
Hampden, admitted: ``It was no contest really for that first-team place at
Celtic, more of a slaughter.
``Roy won hands down. Only twice did we ever play in the same team. He went on
to captain them as a teenager and win almost everything the game had to offer.
``But I was never envious of his achievements. Those sort of feelings can
destroy a person.
``I moved on from Parkhead to Morton and various other clubs and have enjoyed
my own magical moments.
``Never for a minute did I ever think we would meet up as rival managers at
Hampden.
``This is my first-ever national final and undoubtedly the highlight of my
career. I am very proud that I have managed to take Dundee to such an occasion
for the first time in 15 years.''
Aitken, who has led Aberdeen to Hampden after less than a year in charge,
added: ``I knew Jim at Parkhead, but we were never friends.
``He was a Glasgow boy whereas I was from Ayrshire.
``He has done exceptionally well at Dundee and I'm sure it will be a very
entertaining final for the fans.''
q PARTICK Thistle defender Steve Welsh's move to Lincoln City could be on the
verge of collapse.
The English third division side have agreed a #60,000 fee with Thistle, but
Firhill manager Murdo MacLeod refuses to release Welsh until he has found a
suitable replacement.
Last night, Lincoln manager John Beck warned he wasn't prepared to wait forever
to land his man. He said: ``The delay causes major problems for us. We agreed a
fee with the club and personal terms with the player and thought that was it."
q.LIBERIAN striker George Weah scored both goals as AC Milan beat Sparta Prague
of the Czech Republic 2-0 in the UEFA Cup third round, first leg in Italy last
night.
Weah's first came in 32 minutes when he headed home a Franco Baresi cross. He
added the second 14 minutes from time when he volleyed home a Marco Simone
cross.
q Final focus - Page 45
</TEXT>
