<HEADLINE>All light on the night</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill McLean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224914</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bill McLean describes the spectacular package which will accompany the
switch-on of Glasgow's Christmas lights
GLASGOW has never been a city to hide its light under a bushel, but Shine On
Glasgow '95, a visitor-attracting initiative on the part of the Glasgow City
Centre Association, will reveal the dear green place in all its glory when the
Christmas lights are switched on in George Square on Sunday.
Now in its second radiant year, the Shine On Glasgow campaign is being
sponsored by Coca-Cola, whose Alternative Christmas party earlier in the
afternoon before the switch-on ceremony, performed by Burgermeister Dr Pieter
Schnlein, the Mayor of Nremberg, will be a spectacular city centre occasion
to remember. Some of the country's top dance bands will be taking part, and joy
is likely to be unconfined.
Adding lustre to what promises to be a brilliant Sunday afternoon will be the
Parade of Light starting at around 4.30pm when almost 2000 participants from
local amateur, youth and community groups will process via the pedestrian
precincts of Sauchiehall, Buchanan and Argyle streets to the official switch-on
in George Square. Glasgow celebrates not only the 10th anniversary of its
twinning with Nremberg but also the second of enterprising Shine On in a
golden moment.
Instantaneously 20,000 colourful balloons will be released, fireworks will be
set off from the roof of the City Chambers and 850,000 glittering gold stars -
one for every man, woman and child in the city - will fall like snowflakes.
Colour and light will combine harmoniously to make Shine On Glasgow '95 with
Coca-Cola the most sensational civic Christmas event in the whole of the UK.
The Shine On Glasgow campaign receives funding from Glasgow City Council,
Strathclyde Regional Council and Glasgow Development Agency as well as the
private sector. In its second year its aim once again is to attract as many
visitors as possible to the city centre in the run-up to Christmas to do their
festive season shopping, with a four-week programme of entertaining events, and
exciting illuminated features.
From November 26, with a focus on Sundays, the main shopping streets will be a
great draw in themselves, offering a back-drop for entertainers and performance
art with visual works of light and sound.
Project director Alastair Wyllie said: ``There really is nowhere in the country
outside of London that compares to Glasgow in terms of shopping and
entertainment.
``Where else can you find the range of designer labels and quality merchandise
at such down-to-earth prices in one of the finest shopping environments in
Europe? The city's choice of hotels, restaurants, theatres and bars only
underlines what a great place Glasgow is to shop in - it really can't be
beaten!''
Throughout the Shine On programme three custom-built illuminated structures
will grace Glasgow's three city centre pedestrian precincts. At the corner of
Buchanan Street and Gordon Street a 17m steel Christmas Tree donated by British
Steel and British Steel Distribution will dominate the scene with choirs to
make it sing.
At the corner of Sauchiehall Street and Cambridge Street a giant Cuckoo Clock
designed by Steve Edgar will open its doors every 15 minutes to reveal a
circular stage where live performances will take place to delight passers-by.
In Argyle Street a 20ft orrery - a steel and mechanical sculpture of the
circulating planets and stars - designed by Jules Goss will add its seasonal
magic.
Neil Butler, director of Uz Ltd, the Shine On events and illumination producer,
said: ``Pre-Christmas Glasgow offers an excellent opportunity for local
performers and artists to promote their work and entertain the city and its
visitors. It is very satisfying to work in both the UK's Christmas shopping
capital and its events capital at the same time.''
The Parade of Light plays a significant part in the Shine On Glasgow '95 with
Coca-Cola proceedings. It involves close co-operation and participation among
local amateur, youth and community groups which have been working resolutely
together over the past three months. Costumes and floats have been created with
materials provided by Shine On, and design and build expertise and experience
by a dedicated group of community artists.
The volunteers come from unemployed workers' centres, community centres, youth
projects, after-school care programmes, women's groups and performing arts
groups. They will present a theme of shining light, bringing together images of
the sun, moon, stars and candle-glow, reflecting their light on the seasonal
elements of snow and ice. ``Pure, dead brilliant'' in Glasgow patois.
The big parade will be divided into sections led by 20ft-high constructions
depicting specific images of light. There will be visually striking costumes
and an ice-cracking sound from marching bands, and bands aboard the decorated
floats, highlighting the energy of this winter carnival.
</TEXT>
