<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Story of success in which everyone benefited After devising an award-winning upgrading exercise in staff training and office procedure, Monklands District Council is reaping the benefits in terms of an improved service for tenants, as James Currie reports</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Currie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONKLANDS District Council last week notched up what is believed to be a UK
first - and certainly a unique event in Scotland - when its housing department
was presented with the prestigious Investors in People National Standard Award.
The award was handed over by Mr Tom Farmer, chief executive IIP (Scotland), who
is himself one of Europe's leading business figures, courtesy of his other
position as founder and chief executive of Kwik-Fit.
At a ceremony in Coatbridge, Mr Farmer made the presentation to representatives
of the housing department management team, including director of housing, Tom
McKenzie, housing convener Betty Leitch and senior housing officer, Joe Dewar,
who also acted as project manager during the run-up to the event.
Investors in People is an initiative with the express aim of raising the level
of commitment to training and development amongst employers, no matter their
field of operation.
The National Standard is based on the principle that employees' skills are a
major factor in the success or otherwise of any organisation and it identifies
commitment, planning, action and evaluation as key areas for assessment.
In some other businesses, such as manufacturing or distribution, these
standards, it could be argued, are not quite so difficult to attain. With
BS5750 or ISO 9002 in place, the daily routine is - or should be - a matter of
following a defined routine, with ready access to manuals whenever anything
unusual occurs.
But to attempt to apply the same standards to what is essentially a people
business, where every member of the public to visit an office has different
problems and varied expectations, elevates matters to a different plane
altogether.
Individual responsibility becomes vitally important in a decision making
process, and the old stalling tactics of I'll need to check that out, or can
you come back next week and see what Mr or Ms has to say? simply will not
suffice. Not if you want to reach IIP standard.
Monklands District Council Housing Department says it regards the award as a
vital part of its overall strategy and plans for future development. This is a
strategy that will come to fruition through the most effective training and
development of all personnel to meet their main aims and objectives - which
involve providing the best possible service to the department's tenants.
Its successes to date indicate that these efforts can produce positive results,
the bottom line being that IIP can be achieved through what it terms natural
communication from the top to the bottom of the chain.
Director of housing, Tom McKenzie, said at the ceremony: ``Through the total
commitment shown by all of the department's employees, we have demonstrated
that we have a highly trained, highly motivated workforce better able to serve
the needs of our tenants.
An equally jubilant Betty Leitch, housing convener, added: ``The housing
department's success follows two years of intensive work by everyone on the
staff and we are delighted to be the first to have reached this position.''
As senior housing officer, Joe Dewar is very well aware of what is required
when dealing with people on a one-to-one basis. He said of the award: ``As well
as helping with regard to staff training, motivation and morale, the winning of
this award also sends a clear signal to the people who are our tenants that the
council has been working very hard on their behalf, and that far from being the
end of the story, the process of continuous improvement remains in place, to be
fine-tuned as and where necessary.
Mr Dewar pointed out that Monklands District Council housing department
administers the letting of 21,000 houses, making it one of the largest public
sector housing providers in Scotland.
Recent improvements to this stock have resulted in 100% having some form of
central heating installed. Another 80% are double glazed, and 60% of
multi-storey blocks have been structurally improved, most having a concierge
service. A further eight blocks will shortly be upgraded to the same standard,
giving tenants better security, a quieter living environment and an enhanced
lifestyle.
Given the spectacular progress made over the past few years, perhaps this in
itself would have qualified the department for an award.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A standard measure of quality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Currie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224916</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OUR overseas competitors used to regard British industry as something of an
anachronism when it came to the business of training and motivating staff. They
wondered how on earth we managed to survive in a competitive environment when
many of our training procedures owed more to the gaining of hands-on
experience, usually through costly trial and error, than by following a
carefully structured plan.
We in turn were faintly amused by the sight of German workers marching to their
machines at the start of each shift or the Japanese singing company songs and
spending part of their lunch breaks attempting to devise methods whereby
productivity could be increased and an advantage gained over the perceived
opposition.
But while we, quite rightly, continue to shy away from extremes, we have
conceded in recent years that what was once good enough for us is no longer
what will suffice for a greatly expanded market - or even for our own.
It was to help raise standards that the Investors in People initiative was
launched by the Department of Employment in 1990, and it started with the
express aim of raising the level of commitment to training and development and
increasing an awareness of its value among British employers.
So what is the real value of IIP? Perhaps its primary attraction is that it
offers an audit of existing training and development practices against a
national benchmark. It is always easier to measure progress when you have
something to aim for, a standard to reach, no matter how difficult it may
appear at the outset.
IIP has proved a useful tool in identifying those awkward gaps in training
programmes, the point at which people stopped and asked where now?
But in the case of Monklands District it also helped to encourage and motivate
staff at a time when sections of it, such as the housing department, were
already in the process of major change.
The IIP National Standard is based on the simple premise that the success of
any organisation depends to a great extent on the various skills of its
employees.
It then goes on to consider four general principles: commitment, planning,
action and evaluation. Taking each of these concepts, it adds assessment
indicators: six to commitment, seven to planning, six to action and five to
evaluation.
That makes 24 IIP indicators to be taken into account, which should already
dispel any notion that the achievement of IIP standard is simply a matter of
getting your head down and following a set of simple guidelines.
The department doesn't claim it was easy, but quite rightly feels that the
sense of achievement runs all the way through the various offices under its
roof. And this in itself, they would argue, is sufficient to justify the effort
required.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A revolution in staff attitudes and morale</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONKLANDS District Housing Department's drive to IIP began in earnest in 1993
when external consultants were drafted in to carry out an in-depth survey of
staff attitudes.
The results were mixed. Staff generally saw themselves as being involved in a
task-oriented service which was good at achieving results, but there were areas
which caused some concern.
The prevailing level of staff morale, which was rated as being low, was the
most obvious worry. Employees in general showed signs of low self-appreciation
and considered there was both a need to alter management style and to improve
channels of communication.
It was hardly what the management team could have hoped to hear, but rather
than sweep the findings under the carpet and either forget the whole project or
employ another consultant in the hope that he would come up with a different
result, all of the findings were acted upon and remedies introduced. Management
weekends were arranged at which the way forward was charted and an action plan
drawn up for implementation.
Several working parties were formed, including a housing action team and a
communication working party as well as the appointment of an employee to attend
management meetings.
At the same time the IIP project manager, Joe Dewar, was involved in a
continuous programme of training and development, (training courses were made
available to all employees), and their parallel evaluation.
When it was felt that significant progress was being made in these areas a
second employee attitude survey was commissioned, this time with markedly
different results.
Some 88% of employees indicated that they now understood the aims and
objectives of their section. A similar number better understood the aims and
objectives of the department they worked in, and a hugely encouraging 92% said
they knew what was expected of them in their present role.
Similarly good results were achieved when employees responded to questions
relating to the department's aims and to whether improvements had been achieved
with regard to better services, operating efficiency, quality and customer
satisfaction.
Encouraging feedback was also received with regard to the department's record
in the provision of equipment and resources, investing in training and
implementing programmes and processes.
Perhaps best of all from the department's point of view were the findings that
91% of employees enjoyed the work they were doing, and 78% would recommend the
department as a good one to work for. And this bearing in mind that, by general
consent, such departments in any district council are by nature more subject to
customer-driven stresses than any others.
By now the department had put together a portfolio of evidence to support each
of the prescribed 24 IIP indicators, these ranging from the aims and objectives
of the housing department through employee appraisal schemes, minutes of
working parties and training plans to a complete evaluation of the department
in its development of its personnel.
It was a lengthy process, with a requirement for each part of the structure to
be examined in minute detail before the final appraisal by IIP administrators
took place.
Lanarkshire Development Agency had been charged with overseeing the entire
project, but assessing standards were IIP, with an external assessor from IIP
(UK) examining the organisation.
The inspector selected 33 employees from the personnel roll and embarked on a
two-day period of individual and group interviews.
The assessment of the portfolio of evidence and plan took another week and it
was then presented to the IIP recognition panel.
On September 29 Monklands District Council Housing Department became the first
in Scotland to be formally recognised by IIP.
Given its day-to-day workload it has to be rated a considerable achievement .
Joe Dewar, who was instrumental in taking the process from the idea stage to
implementation, says the ultimate beneficiaries will be the department's 21,000
tenants.
``Our role is to provide the very best service we can, with resources that are
necessarily limited. Having a motivated staff who take great pride in what they
do is an enormous help in this regard, he said.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>One-stop service speeds inquiries</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224918</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONKLANDS District Council Housing Department currently employs 265 people, 173
staff and 92 manual workers.
Earlier this year it went through a restructuring process which saw it with
four offices covering Coatbridge North, Coatbridge South, Airdrie North and
Airdrie South, each administering around 5000 properties.
One of the most important benefits here from a tenant's point of view was the
creation of a one-stop inquiry service, meaning the end of waiting in three
different queues or - worse still - different offices, to get the answer to
several questions.
A recent poll of tenants in the area showed that most felt that there was still
room for improvement, a narrow majority (47%) claiming to be generally
dissatisfied with the service they received from the housing department, while
45% claimed to be generally satisfied.
Areas for concern centred on repairs, capital improvements,
security/anti-social behaviour and estate management (gardens).
The housing department intends to get to grips with these concerns by
continuing the decentralisation process, giving staff a wider remit, setting up
a new complaints procedure, establishing tenant panels and providing an
improved information and advice service.
These objectives are being pursued despite the fact that even bigger changes
are on the way.
Next April 1, the housing departments of Monklands, Motherwell, Cumbernauld,
Kilsyth and part of Strathkelvin will merge, giving North Lanarkshire around
63,400 houses, 53% of the total North Lanarkshire housing stock and making it
second only to Glasgow in terms of size.
Staff numbers will climb to 530 full-time and 50 part-time and the combined
budget will be #167m, including #83m revenue and #36.6m capital.
All of this means more headaches in store. Each merging authority apparently
has a different housing allocation policy, Monklands and Motherwell favouring a
date of application/category scheme while Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Strathkelvin
use a points-based system.
There is also the fact that none of the other areas has either the same
percentage of homes with central heating or - in the case of Motherwell - such
a high proportion of refurbished multi-storey blocks, so some earnest budget
discussions will have to be implemented.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stewart planning a double whammy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224919</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE weakness of Scottish athletes in recent years has been a reluctance to test
themselves against England's best, either through lack of ambition, fear of
failure, or simply fear of blowing a hole in the pocket.
Glen Stewart has had to endure some criticism since rejecting selection for an
international at Margate earlier this month. Tomorrow, however, he plans to
race twice in the Safeway international meeting at Gateshead.
Last year, Andrew Pearson won both the 1900 metres event for track athletes and
also the 3500m international event. Tomorrow Racing Club's Stewart will have
just 30 minutes between the two, and the chance to put some outstanding
Scottish performances into perspective.
The short race includes English internationalists Matthew Yates, Adrian Passey,
and Darren Spawforth, plus his Scottish clubmate Frank McGowan, Ian Gillespie
(Birchfield), Chris Robison (IBM Spango Valley), and Gary Brown (Falkirk).
Pearson, top Briton at this year's world cross-country, contests only the
longer race, because he heads the UK team for the European championships a week
tomorrow at Alnwick.
Other Scots with the possibility of high placings include Clydesdale's Des
Roache, who runs in the junior event, and Kilbarchan's Robert Quinn, over 6900m.
q CHANGING for Bellahouston's meeting on Sunday is at Cartha Rugby Club.
Declarations from 11am.
Doug Gillon
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aztec Camera, Barrowland, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Williamson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224920</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE infuriating journey of Roddy Frame around the margins of genius continues.
Much as his entire recorded output has teetered on greatness before taking one
of its innumerable diversions, cul-de-sacs or hiatuses, it is hard to tell from
Aztec Camera's current live show quite where Frame's head or music is at in
1995.
There are contradictions everywhere: Frame's last three albums have seen him
veer from r&amp;b to punk to more laid-back soundscapes, and before that Dylan and
Knopfler seemed to be his major influences. Now, with a new album, Frestonia,
which contains some of his best songs in 10 years, he has the chance to shine.
He merely glitters round the edges.
The main complaint is the show's apparent complacency. The band, for all their
ability, do little to augment or accentuate either the tenderness in Frame's
lyrics or his wistfully soulful vocals.
After they have bludgeoned their way through Black Lucile, it comes as some
relief to see Frame don his acoustic for Boy Wonders but it fares little
better: another leaden version of a timeless song.
Admittedly Spanish Horses and Pillar to Post fare better, and the wholly
acoustic interlude does much to redress the balance in favour of Frame's
songwriting talent.
Method of Love, Sun, and Rainy Season are all fine adverts for his recent work,
where the songs are given ample breathing space, but his reliance and in some
cases destruction of his back catalogue will do little to entice his audience
into buying the new album.
Much as the set still contains more than its fair share of brilliant songs,
Frame's muse seems to have become steadily more erratic with age. The hope
remains that one day Frame will do something wholly rather than partially (like
this show) great.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bargain routes to bright sites</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224921</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPECIAL travel arrangements have been made to make Glasgow easily accessible
during the four-week programme. ScotRail, for example, is offering a 25%
reduction on cheap day return fares from Edinburgh, Dunblane and Stirling to
Glasgow Queen Street station on Sundays November 26, and December 3, 10 and 17.
Telephone 0345 212282 or 0131 556 2451 for further information.
With Strathclyde Transport's Park `n Ride scheme cars may be left at local
stations free of charge with the puchase of a Day Tripper ticket on rail, bus
or Underground. Glasgow Roundabout tickets offer unlimited travel on rail and
Underground in Glasgow itself and Zonecards are available for use on rail, bus
and Underground for periods of one week or more. Telephone 0141 332 7133 for
information.
There is also a free Shuttle Bus service from either the Charing Cross or High
Street car parks to and from the main shopping area using the car park voucher.
Shine On Glasgow '95 will be bigger and better than last year, and it is
expected to pull in more Christmas shoppers to the city centre than before. It
will certainly let Glasgow flourish because in Coca-Cola terms, it is the real
thing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
