<HEADLINE>Record prices for top quality spring barley</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Ross</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224922</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Record prices for top
quality spring barley
EXCELLENT weather conditions this year saw many spring barley growers achieve
record prices.
Most spring barley was combined in exceptionally good conditions and grain
quality was rated superb in South-east Scotland with low nitrogen and excellent
grain size. A high proportion of the crop made the malting grade with the main
varieties - Chariot, Derkado, and Prisma - all yielding above average.
Malting barley was attracting a premium of #42.66 over feed prices which
averaged #102.75 a tonne.
Speaking after the judging of the National Malting Barley Competition for
Scotland, Robin Pirie, of Pauls Malt, Newmarket, said record tonnages had
accompanied record prices. ``So far, the malting industry has bought more than
750,000 tonnes of spring barley in Scotland, compared with 685,000 tonnes last
year,'' he said.
During the harvest some 60,000 tonnes were sold for export. In UK terms,
400,000 tonnes were exported from a total supply of 1.5 million.
The good summer also resulted in more demand for malt from the lager industry,
Mr Pirie said.
The malting barley competition, organised by the Institute of Brewing, was won
by Marcus Findlay, of Pitcox Farm, Dunbar. His winning sample of Derkado had
been entered by Hugh Baird and Sons of Pencaitland, who hosted this year's
judging at Pencaitland Maltings.
Runner-up was Hamilton Farmers of East Linton, again with a sample of Derkado,
entered by IM Cowe &amp; Co, of Edinburgh.
The Tayside, Fife, and Central regional winner was David Arnot, of Hatton Mill,
Arbroath, with Camargue. Highland and Grampian winner was JM Fraser, of Lethen,
Nairn, with Prisma.
The competition, now in its eighteenth year, is designed to encourage the
production of malting barley of the quality required by the distilling and
brewing industries at home and abroad. The winners will receive their awards in
London in the new year.
</TEXT>
