<HEADLINE>BBC seal five-year deal with WPBSA</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224923</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE world championship will continue to be shown on terrestrial television
after the sport's governing body yesterday announced a five-year deal with the
BBC.
The agreement means the BBC have retained the rights to broadcast the event,
along with three other leading tournaments, until the year 2001.
The new deal, which starts from season 1996-97, also covers the Royal Liver
Assurance UK Championship, Benson and Hedges Masters, and the Grand Prix
Championship.
Jonathan Martin, head of BBC Sport, said: ``This new contract means the many
millions of viewers, who remain keen snooker fans, will still be able to see
the world's best players compete in the most prestigious tournaments into the
next century.
``We are delighted to maintain our links with a sport which continues to hold
such a wide appeal, particularly the world championship, which is firmly
established in the portfolio of top sporting events.''
The BBC's coverage of the Royal Liver Assurance UK Championship at Preston
begins tomorrow.
q.ENGLAND'S David Lilley reached the final of the world amateur championship in
Bristol yesterday when he defeated No.1 seed Rom Surin, of Thailand, by four
frames in their best-of-15 semi-final. He will meet Thailand's Sakchai Sim-Ngam
in the best-of-21 frame final. The Thai beat London 16-year-old David Gray 8-4.
</TEXT>
