<HEADLINE>Chapter records the verse</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Boss Grooves</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224924</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXACTITUDE is all when you're assembling a bible. That's why there's a six-page
style guide for each contributor to the newly-launched six-volume second
edition of the Guinness Encyclopaedia of Popular Music. Grandly sub-titled
Amended Version XVIII, the guide offers considerably more than ten commandments
on the proper annotation of rock and pop.
Thou wilt give neither hyphen nor capital letters to country rock, although
country and western shalt abbreviate to C&amp;W. Thou shalt distinguish between
b-sides and T-shirts. Covet ye not greatest-hits compilations when thou
compileth discographies.
Rock'n'roll raciness? Just the one inadvertent bit: ``the term rock `n' roll
should be written with inverted commas in the 69 position.'' Oo-er.
More importantly, Guinness compilers must heed a host of rigorous prohibitions.
Bangeth ye not on about chart positions. No wild-eyed opinionating - reflect
the critical consensus! Above all, servants of the Guinness encyclopaedia must
eschew lazy rock-hackisms.
I am thus unable to describe Guinness editor Colin Larkin as having cracked the
charts or scored a hit with a tome which offers a plethora of facts. Helmed by
Larkin, the book is no cheesy organ.
This po-faced air of pop-picking nit-pickery is, however, misleading. Let us
record the truth that Colin Larkin smiles a great deal in his north London
office, pulsing with a palpable love for music and the minutiae of its making.
He jokes zestfully at the ridiculousness of the unending task he's set himself
and his select band of fact-checkers and their ever-expanding data-bases.
Whence does his passion spring? Larkin recalls precisely. From falling in love
as a child in 1953 on the Dagenham council housing estate where he was raised.
``It was hearing Guy Mitchell's She Wears Red Fathers - brackets - And A Huli
Huli Skirt, close brackets. On the Columbia label.''
Larkin embraced artier forms of rockaboogie music in his teenage years, yet in
one crucial respect he stayed true to the working-class origin of his love for
twang'n'thump.
``I developed a real chip on my shoulder about rock and pop not being accorded
the respect given to `serious' musical forms.''
Having begun his own publishing business, Larkin became obsessed with
establishing a rock and pop version of Grove's, the authoritative guide to
classical music. Against a fraught background of home-remortgagings and marital
disintegrations, he succeeded. So much so that this year the US publishers of
Grove's decided to distribute Larkin's Guinness work in America.
``They came to us, having decided not to do their own version, having accepted
us as the definitive work.''
Larkin's four-volume first edition, published in 1992, sold almost 5000 copies
at #195. ``Erring on the side of caution, I actually predicted less demand for
the second edition, around 3000. In fact, we sold all 3000 copies in the first
week of publication, and are confidently expecting sales of 6000.''
At #295, it's predominantly a music-industry purchase. ``Jools Holland carries
the books everywhere on a special leather strap. He's on his second set of the
initial edition, someone having stolen the first lot. He quotes us on telly on
Later With Jools Holland. It is gratifying to be acknowledged.''
Not everyone is as honest. Larkin was miffed to see most of Jerry Garcia's
Fleet Street obituarists pilfering his book. ``Hacks all re-writing the same
entry for cash. Very sad. And frightening. The power we have. Our
responsibility to get things right.''
Because mistakes are always noticed. Popsters love their heroes, well-kent or
not, with a ferocity which can manifest itself in heated missives. Woe betide
any pop encyclopaedia that misidentifies the birth-date of Syd Gubbins, of Syd
Gubbins and His Gub'nors fame.
``An angry Rare Earth fan wrote in berating us most horribly for having missed
out three of their albums, and for having mis-spelt one group-member's name.
``He was right to complain, but people often don't appreciate the nature of our
task. We have no malice. We don't go to town on the acts we loathe.
``Unfortunately, however, we're perceived as dull, boring pen-suckers. I reply
politely to all the letters we get, patiently thanking the writer for having
spotted any errors and assuring them we will rectify them - and add the
writer's name to our list of acknowledgements. Sometimes, though, I'd love to
employ the same abusive tone as the complainer.''
Of course, it's not only fans who write in. Jack Bruce volunteered his own
obituary. And orchestral arranger Martin Ford wrote in very pleasantly,
pointing out that, contrary to his first-edition entry, he hadn't actually
faded into relative obscurity over 20 years ago. He had in the interim made
contributions to chart-topping albums by Phil Collins, Paul McCartney, Elton
John, Bryan Ferry, and Harry Nilsson, to name but a few.
Ignorance: the encyclopaedia-editor's ultimate failing. Larkin laughs a
terror-stricken laugh as he recalls Martin Ford's reasoned reproach.
It contrasted strongly with that of one member of free-thinking folk-rockers
the Oyster Band, who wrote a series of inexplicably truculent letters which
culminated in a threat of legal action if all mention of their career wasn't
expunged from the Guinness book.
Larkin complied. Now under the second edition's heading Oyster Band, the
there's simply a sentence explaining the band's decision, an erroneous one
which makes them look silly and sad.
Mistakes, mistakes. They happen. Larkin shudders. ``We wrote about Steve Race
in the past tense, which is potentially sue-able.''
Indeed, the Guinness contributors' list has been drastically pruned since 1992,
reduced from 82 to 26, with a nucleus of 14. ``Inability to adhere to house
style,'' Larkin hisses, shaking his head.
Heck, but there's an up-side, too. Doors opening backstage at the Hammersmith
Odeon where Larkin was given a hug and a sweaty plectrum by one of his heroes,
BB King. Lost guitar-hero Peter Green, well again, wandering into Larkin's
office one Monday afternoon a few weeks back with news of his re-born career.
``And we took a stand at the Midem music festival where I met Jac Holzman, the
man who founded the Elektra label and discovered the Doors. And publisher Del
Bryant came along and quietly read the entry for his mum and dad, Felice and
Boudleaux, the creators of the Everly Brothers' hits...... and as he read it, I
saw a tear run down his face.
``When he'd finished, he just said: `OK.' That was rather special.''
Just like Colin Larkin's good book, by Guinness goodness. It's the gospel. Amen.
The world of popular music has been condensed into a new six-volume guide.
David Belcher meets the man with all the facts at his fingertips
</TEXT>
