<HEADLINE>UEFA drawn into Rovers brawl</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRAWLING Blackburn stars Graeme Le Saux and David Batty face a carpeting from
manager Ray Harford today after their astonishing fight during the European
Champions' League defeat in Moscow.
But while Harford has indicated the two England men face disciplinary action -
with both likely to be landed with fines of two weeks' wages - it is probable
their punishments will not be made public.
Harford and his squad refused to comment further on the affair when they
arrived back from Russia yesterday.
But chairman Robert Coar gave a brief, official response to the amazing scenes
he had witnessed in the Luzhniki Stadium, a game missed by millionaire owner
Jack Walker and Kenny Dalglish.
``The club is disappointed with the incident,'' said Coar. ``Ray Harford will
sit down with the players tomorrow. If disciplinary action is deemed necessary,
it will be carried out.''
Whatever punishment Rovers hand out to the two players, who had to be separated
by skipper Tim Sherwood, Henning Berg, and Colin Hendry when the punches were
flying, it seems unlikely it will be the end of the matter after the Football
Association urged UEFA to investigate.
FA spokesman Steve Double said chief executive Graham Kelly had authorised a
letter sent to UEFA's headquarters in Nyon, Switzerland, asking the European
game's governing body to act - which could lead to European bans for both
players.
`We are very concerned at what happened in Moscow,'' said Double. ``Something
must be done and we want it to be done.
``We cannot do anything as the game was not under our jurisdiction. It is up to
UEFA to act as they see fit but they have the power to charge players under the
code of unsporting behaviour.''
Unlike the FA, UEFA are reluctant to accept video evidence of incidents on the
field of play, and a spokesman said no action could be considered until they
had received the reports from Italian referee Pierluigi Pairetto, and the
Danish official delegate.
Certainly the Batty-Le Saux fight was an embarrassment for the 250 Rovers fans
who braved the near-arctic conditions to watch a match of only academic
importance.
Supporters flying home admitted a sense of shame, and Rovers legend and former
England captain Ronnie Clayton, still an Ewood Park regular, spoke for many of
them.
``I just could not understand it,'' said Clayton. ``It cannot do anyone any
good and the club will need to act.''
</TEXT>
