<HEADLINE>Caligari, The Arches, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224926</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAIRGROUND or madhouse? Therapist or murderer? Lunatic or lone voice of reason?
What makes a tale like The Cabinet of Doctor Caligari so abidingly fascinating
is the way it plays sleight of plot with truth and illusion. Just as you think
you know, for sure, who's to be trusted and who is the manipulative maniac -
the situation spins one more time and, like an Escher drawing, you're left with
a trick perspective where water falls up and stairways never come down to
earth. Nothing, no-one, can be taken at face value here.
Visually, this Arches version of the story effectively suggests an
out-of-kilter time and place without following slavishly in the surreal
imprints of the German silent film. Instead of wildly drunken angles and
oversized furniture, there's a grim rookery of doors and crannies that
compresses all the action into one claustrophobic enclave.
Murders are sudden silhouettes against upper blinds, while down below - in
faded costumes of black, white, and occasional red - the fairground continues
its freakish dumb shows. A twitching aside of various veils - and the place is
an asylum where Caligari and his somnambulist slave, Cesare, are part of
another freakish ploy.
Where things come adrift is in the text and its delivery. Andrew Dallmeyer's
device of using blank verse as a means of conveying the heightened pitch of
expressionism really needs a more pointedly stylised delivery than the cast
give at present. There really needs to be a chilling sense of something
extraordinary, strange and estranging, in the way even ordinary words strike
our ears.
As it is, we have to rely on Derek McCluckie's Cesare - with make-up that would
do justice to Nosferatu, if Andy Arnold does decide to do that one - to give us
the thrill and the sense of weirdness that haunts the film but doesn't
sufficiently haunt this staging.
</TEXT>
