<HEADLINE>tale of three bridges tolls for thee</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gavin Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224927</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
On the day they hoisted the first of the massive chains supporting the Menai
Bridge in north Wales, friends who went looking for the engineer to
congratulate him found him on his knees engaged in prayer.
Thomas Telford, the son of a Scots shepherd, was giving thanks for the success
of one of his greatest engineering achievements, and possibly adding a plea
that it might endure as a monument to his vision and skill.
If that were the case, his supplication was heard. Some 170 years after it was
built, his handsome suspension bridge with its twin piers of rough-hewn stone
is still standing, and carrying more traffic than ever between the Isle of
Anglesey and the Welsh mainland at Bangor. Apart from providing a lifeline to
the island, it is beautiful to look at. A slender structure extending from a
wooded hillside, it spans 580ft to an island village named after it with lofty
grace.
Local folk regard it with the kind of pride and affection Scots profess for the
Forth Railway Bridge. It features on paintings and coffee mugs in island shops;
if the Welsh made shortbread, it would be on the tins.
It has the additional attraction, as critics of the Skye Bridge have pointed
out, of being free of tolls. Skye and Lochalsh councillors have indicated they
may cite it in a legal challenge to the tolls, based on the 1707 Act of Union
between England and Scotland which states that taxes must be the same across
the two countries. Telford's construction, they believe, established the
precedent of toll-free bridges.
Unhappily, that is not the case. A Herald investigation has discovered that
anyone who wished to cross the Menai Bridge on the day it opened, and for years
afterwards, was required to pay a penny. The charge for a mule or an ass was
twopence, for a drove of oxen, cows or ``neat cattle'' a shilling per score,
and for a stagecoach 2/6d. History does not record any protest demonstrations,
although tolls continued to be collected until 1940.
Elizabeth Jones, who runs a bookshop in Menai Bridge village, vaguely remembers
her parents complaining about paying to cross the bridge. ``I can't imagine
what it would be like if they imposed the tolls again,'' she says. ``A lot of
people rely on the bridge to get to work in Bangor every day. It would be
awful. I don't think people would accept it.''
There is no suggestion of tolls returning to Menai, but reports of charges on
the Skye Bridge have reminded the residents of Anglesey how fortunate they are.
``There's a lot of sympathy here for the people of Skye,'' Jones says. ``We
know how they must feel. It seems terribly unfair.''
It is a common sentiment on the island, which like Skye retains an independent
spirit despite its technical attachment to the British mainland. Sue Davis, who
manages a bistro perched on the island side of the bridge, says she would
object vigorously to paying tolls. ``It's still Wales on the other side, and
we're all Welsh after all,'' she says. ``I don't know how they put up with it
on Skye, it's almost like they are being segregated.''
A measure of the islanders' resistance to such impositions was when the
authorities installed parking meters in the village a couple of years ago. The
locals promptly sealed them with super-glue, and a desultory war of attrition
between repairmen and the saboteurs is still going on.
There is, of course, a price to pay for maintaining the bridge, but Gwynedd
County Council on the mainland is happy to meet the expenses from public funds.
Wynne Jones, its assistant director of highways, takes the view that the bridge
is a vital public service which should be financed by local taxpayers.
It has required strengthening over the years with new chains and girders,
painting it is an on-going job, and the two-lane roadway was recently
resurfaced with waterproof membrane at a cost of #250,000. Jones estimates
general maintainance at about #1m every five years, but he reckons it is money
well spent.
``I think it's enough to pay your road fund licence without having to pay
transport tolls on top,'' he says. ``The problem is this Government seems
hell-bent on private enterprise, regardless of the cost.''
There are other similarities between Skye and Anglesey - both are essentially
rural communities dependent on farming and seasonal tourism. However Telford's
bridge is no longer the only road link over the Menai Straights. In 1977 a road
deck was added to a nearby railway bridge, which now carries most of the heavy
commercial traffic on a Euroroute to and from the ferry terminals for Ireland
at Holyhead. But the original bridge is still favoured by local traffic,
amounting to an estimated 14,000 vehicles a day.
Its admirers include Meurig Owen, a committee clerk on the island borough
council and local historian. ``Once upon a time,'' he recalls, ``if there was a
serious crime committed on Anglesey the first thing the police did was block
the bridge, then they'd say `that's the front door shut'.
``When you think about it, it's a marvel it's lasted so long and coped with
modern traffic. It's done well up till now, very well indeed.''
At the opposite corner of Wales, a very different public attitude is developing
towards a more modern bridge. The #330m River Severn Bridge, due to be
completed next April, will be the longest in the UK and one of the longest in
Europe. With an overall length of more than three miles, it is designed to
carry up to 27 million vehicles a day between Avon and Gwent, thereby relieving
intense pressure on an existing bridge two miles to the north.
It is badly needed to service high-tech industries which have proliferated
along the so-called M4 corridor in south Wales following the demise of the coal
mines, and to improve access to channel ferries for commercial traffic from
Wales and Ireland.
All this, it will assuredly do. The only problem is that, like the Skye Bridge,
it was conceived under the Government's private funding initiative - which
means it will be a toll bridge. Not only that, but as part of the deal the
consortium building it has acquired the existing bridge which opened 30 years
ago and sharply increased the tolls on it. So anyone driving to south Wales
from the West Country will have to pay more than ever for the privilege, unless
they are prepared to make lengthy detours.
The result is a growing protest movement, with motorists being urged to boycott
the bridges, and Swansea city councillors suggesting that lorry drivers mount a
French-style blockade of the crossings. The more moderate reaction of the
Freight Transport Association has been to petition the Government for
concessionary tolls.
The issue is complicated by a system of tolling in only one direction - on
entering Wales. To improve traffic flows, no tolls are charged on leaving the
country. As a result, an estimated 1000 commercial vehicles a day heading for
Wales make a detour around Gloucester and through the Forest of Dean, to the
intense annoyance of local residents. One supermarket distribution centre on
the Welsh side, serving the West Country and the Midlands, reckons it is saving
#200,000 per annum by instructing its drivers to avoid the Severn on their
return to Wales.
Yet despite recent increases, the tolls are still substantially lower than
those of the Skye Bridge. It now costs motorists #3.80 and lorry drivers #11.50
to cross the Severn both ways, while standard one-way charges at Skye are
between #4.30 and #5.20 for cars depending on season, and #9.80 to #25.40 for
goods vehicles. Even with a book of 10 tickets, a private motorist ends up
paying #4.88 for a two-way crossing.
The explanation is simple - a great many more people cross the Severn than Loch
Alsh. While the Skye Bridge hopes to attract 500,000 paying customers a year,
the operators of the new Severn Bridge expect more than 20 million. On this
basis, they should pay off their debts and presumably make a tidy profit within
their concessionary period of 30 years, after which both bridges revert to
public ownership. The rationale here, as on Skye, is that the bridges should be
paid for by the people who use it.
Norman Haste, the project director for the new bridge, is justifiably proud of
the achievement, and pleased that it has attracted 40,000 visitors for lectures
and tours of the construction site since work began four years ago. ``It may
sound twee, but one of my personal campaigns on this job was to bring civil
engineering closer to the people it serves,'' he says.
Hostility to the tolls is thus a disappointment, but Haste insists there is
little the consortium - led by John Laing Construction and GTM-Entrepose of
France - can do about it. ``We have to raise financially viable tolls to pay
back our lenders in a reasonable period of time, and we have no freedom to
adjust the tolls to suit ourselves. They are engraved on tablets of stone in
the Severn Bridges Act, and can be changed only by a movement in the retail
price index.''
The construction industry is seriously concerned about such restrictions,
according to Haste. ``While we are prepared to accept Government policy on
private funding quite willingly, and the risks that go with it, we would like
to see greater flexibility in operating such schemes. We cannot, for example,
offer discounted tolls to attract customers, and strict controls leave little
room for innovation in design and financing. Public accountability is rightly
important, but where private companies are taking commercial risks they should
have greater flexibility in dealing with them.''
Such views are shared by Frank Cook, the regional director of the Freight
Transport Association in Bristol, whose members regard the tolls as highway
robbery. Cook says it recently commissioned a study which indicated that a
relatively small concession of around 10% would pay for itself through
increased customers. ``On this basis, we're calling on the Government to
reconvene a meeting with the bridge company that began last January, at which
it said it would consider sympathetically any proposals for discounts that fell
within the existing concession agreement.''
Compared with the higher charges and fewer options for residents of Skye,
however, the people of south Wales are getting a better deal. Neil Jones,
business editor of the Western Mail in Cardiff, agrees and says most locals
have adopted a philosophical attitude. ``Tolls have been charged on the first
Severn Bridge since the start, so we Welsh are used to them. It seems curious
they only operate one way, but I suppose we have to expect to pay for the
privilege of entering Wales.''
Regrettably, the days of stagecoaches trundling over marvels of Victorian
engineering for 2/6d are long gone.
</TEXT>
