<HEADLINE>Clarke must address political demands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lord Weir</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<FLAG>budget countdown</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224928</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVERY year as the Budget draws near an avalanche of paper descends on the
luckless Chancellor. Somewhere in the Treasury, I imagine there must be a very
large room and, as the great day approaches, the piles of recommendations,
submissions, suggestions, and complaints remorselessly grow towards the ceiling.
It is not just from such quarters as industry, chambers of commerce, trade
unions and trade associations, economists and the Economist, companies large
and small, charities and the like that all these helpful offerings come.
Newspapers feel that their readers will be shortchanged if they do not also
contribute to this great national festival of advice.
It is a game where - as with the National Lottery - a very modest and
superficial numeracy is the only qualification required to play. Unlike the
lottery, however, there are no real losers. If, by complete coincidence, the
Chancellor actually follows your advice, you have won. If he does not, then you
have the warm satisfaction of knowing that you were right and he was wrong. In
such circumstances, I was delighted to be asked to write this article, and
contribute my own advice to Mr Clarke.
The first self-evident proposition about all Budgets is that they must
reconcile political and economic demands. On the rare occasions when the
political and economic weather is simultaneously balmy, the Chancellor is a
lucky man and this task is not so very testing. Today, with a General Election
rapidly approaching, and with the opinion polls showing his Government held in
extraordinarily low public esteem, the Chancellor is placed in a most
unenviable position. But he is a throughly capable and clear-thinking man, with
a robust attitude. How should he react - and how will he react - in the face of
such problems?
Clearly the emphasis of his Budget must be to address political demands. He
must, however, show great care in the way in which he does this. Otherwise our
low rate of inflation which is a hard won and invaluable prize could easily be
jeopardised by imprudent actions. Second, the foreign exchange markets are
nervous and fragile.
Whatever he does, the Chancellor must also avoid any market perception that he
has acted rashly. Any sustained fall in sterling, as a market reaction, would
have direct repercussions on inflation quite apart from other undesirable
consequences. Moreover, given the electoral timetable, such inflationary
consequences would be likely to feed through with the worst possible timing
from a political point of view.
We should ask ourselves what these political demands really are, and then how
far the Chancellor can go towards meeting them while avoiding the penalties
which inflation and the loss of market confidence would impose.
In political terms, the Chancellor should direct his action at the middle
section of taxpayers. That is where elections are won. The upper echelon of
taxpayers, in spite of their grumbling, will mainly vote for his party in any
event, and the lower echelon generally will not, so there is little political
mileage in doing anything significant in those particular directions.
As to the specific tax cuts he should make, the choice will surely be dictated
more by the need to meet fixed perceptions than by reality. The fixed
perception in the minds of most people is that tax is higher or lower depending
on whether the standard rate of income tax moves up or down. The fact that the
overall tax burden on the middle band of taxpayers has increased considerably
since 1992 through changes in allowances and National Insurance is an
interesting subject for the fiscally sophisticated. To the voter it is the
standard rate which matters.
Mr Clarke will reduce it for the best political reasons. It is also pretty
clear that he has headroom for a meaningful reduction, without severely
prejudicing his overall financial position, and undermining market confidence.
Incidentally, what the markets will be watching for is whether the general
shape of his budget seriously prejudices his longer term policy of reducing
public borrowing.
Just as the perception of high or low tax is so specifically linked to the rate
of income tax so, for a great number of people, the perception and indeed the
reality of their own wealth is inextricably linked to the housing market, and
the value of their home. The fall in house prices, negative equity in mortgaged
homes, the fear and reality of repossession, and the like have surely been the
largest influences in political disillusionment with the Government.
There are dangers, however, in attacking this problem. The housing market is so
large that any wholesale dramatic measures are prohibitively expensive. There
is also the ghastly precedent of the damage done to the economy by previous
runaway housing booms. The Chancellor's position is considerably eased however
by two important factors.
First, there is no supply side constraint. There is plenty of slack in
construction and building materials where employment continues to fall. Land
prices have weakened and mortgage lending is feeble. So there is little fear of
a runaway boom.
Second, the most politically sensitive part of the housing problem is at the
fringes of the market. Thus, wholesale measures which could cost an enormous
amount are not needed.
Major political benefits can be won, with a little ingenuity, by affordable
marginal changes. I would be very surprised if we do not see measures in such
areas as stamp-duty, and temporary or tapering increases in mortgage tax-relief
as examples.
Not only would such measures be politically popular, and help to alleviate a
real social problem, but they would quickly help to revive the economy
generally at a time when it is clearly slowing down, and ease unemployment.
I also believe that the Chancellor should concentrate on income tax and
housing, and try to avoid cluttering his Budget with too many other proposals
which would simply distract from the political impact of those two measures.
Now that Mr Clarke knows what to do, I can happily await Budget Day and enjoy
either the satisfaction of seeing my advice taken, or the equal satisfaction of
his being wrong and myself being right. I just hope he reads The Herald in time.
</TEXT>
