<HEADLINE>CBI reports weakening in manufacturing demand</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224930</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURING industry in the UK reported a slight weakening in overall demand
in November confirming - if any confirmation was needed - that the recovery has
slowed but the prices outlook remains promising, according to the latest
Monthly Trends Enquiry from the Confederation of British Industry which is now
forecasting a ``sustainable'' interest rate cut of half a point in early 1996.
It will, though, require a ``prudent'' Budget on November 28, which takes no
risks with inflation and maintains a credible downward path for public
borrowing. The CBI is also forecasting that economic growth will continue at a
sluggish rate into 1996, leading to a growth rate of 2.5% next year. However,
stronger growth from the middle of next year is expected to raise the growth
rate to 2.8% in 1997. Manufacturing output is also projected to grow strongly
over the next two years.
The survey shows that 20% of firms said their order books were above normal and
29% below normal, giving a negative balance of 9%, one more than the preceding
month. Total order books have now been below normal for the past three months.
Demand from overseas also continues to be less buoyant than earlier in the
year, with a balance of 1% reporting order books below normal. Companies have
reported export demand to be close to normal for the third survey in a row,
although this month's balance is the lowest in a monthly survey since June 1994.
More firms expect to increase domestic prices over the next four months rather
than reduce them. November's positive balance of 15% is four percentage points
up on last month, although half of the companies surveyed expect prices to
remain unchanged.
However, Sudhir Junankar, the CBI's associate director of economic analysis,
said the ``prospects for factory gate price inflation remained more promising
than in the first half of the year, as competitive pressures in the home market
continued to restrain the ability of firms to push up prices. The pick-up in
price expectations this month was not surprising, as it partly reflected the
revisions to price lists that companies undertook at the turn of the year.''
Kate Barker, chief economic adviser at the CBI said: ``With the recent slower
rate of growth now expected to persist over the next few months, inflationary
pressures in the economy have lessened. The balance of risks points more to
concern over weaker growth than over higher inflation.'' That the CBI's
interest rate forecast of a 0.5% cut next year is linked to the Budget is not
surprising. The CBI has been stressing the need for a cautious Budget for
months.
On a positive note, Mr Junankar said that consumer spending had performed
better than expected so far this year, and was set to underpin economic growth
in the next two years. He added: ``Encouragingly, private business investment
seems likely to make an increasing contribution to the growth forecasts for the
next two years.''
</TEXT>
