<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charges put group #13m in the red</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224931</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE-OFF charges totalling some #30m sent fuel distribution and port services
group Powell Duffryn plummeting #13m into the red, half year results showed
yesterday.
Discounting exceptionals, the group would have made a pre-tax profit in the six
months to September 30 of #16.8m.
In the corresponding period last year, the group made a taxable #17m profit
after exceptional gains of #2.2m.
The latest one-off costs were made up of #13m in settlement of a long-standing
German lawsuit, net losses estimated at #10m following a fire at a fuel storage
depot in the United States and a goodwill write-off following the purchase of a
bulk powder tanker producer.
The Reading based company listed subdued trading in many of its markets and, in
particular, in the oil and gas distribution business where the weather and fuel
prices had a major impact.
On the positive side, its port division, which recently bought interests in the
ports of Tees and Hartlepool and in Humberside Holdings, was trading well.
Itsengineering division was also enjoying expansion.
Chairman David Hubbard said the board was concentrating on businesses which
provided the best opportunities for growth.
``Prospects for the second half are tempered as always by the unpredictable
effect of the winter on our oil and gas distribution activities, where
automotive fuel margins are also under intense pressure.
``That apart, there is no reason to believe at this stage that the year will
not see another sound trading outcome for the group.''
Shareholders will receive an interim dividend payout of 8p, unchanged from last
year, while earnings per share of 17.9p last time were converted into losses of
18.5p.
</TEXT>
