<HEADLINE>Batsman passes test with a century That's more like it from Thorpe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<FLAG>cricket round-up</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRAHAM Thorpe finally left the starting blocks yesterday and ended any
lingering doubts about his right to a place in next Thursday's second Test
against South Africa.
The left-hander has spent the first five weeks of England's tour in a daze,
worrying about problems at home while struggling to find his feet on South
African soil.
But against a friendly Orange Free State attack, and given a flat Springbok
Park pitch, he scored a century that will have delighted manager Raymond
Illingworth.
Thorpe had flown home           earlier in the month to comfort wife Nicky
after she had lost the baby the couple had been expecting.
Then, on his return, he failed twice during the defeat by South Africa A before
being dismissed cheaply when the Test series began in Pretoria. But yesterday,
Thorpe looked much more like the batsman who has become a highly consistent
member of England's middle order over the last 18 months, helping himself to an
undefeated 131.
``I had only played four innings before this, so it was a bit early to be
putting pressure on myself,'' said the 26-year-old. ``But you could say it was
a relief to make some runs here.''
Illingworth, with only a hint of a smile, had suggested Thorpe should steer
clear of the pavilion if he repeated the ugly shot which led to his second
innings stumping against South Africa A. In fact, there were a couple of loose
drives outside off-stump yesterday.
But with Surrey team-mate Alec Stewart providing inspiration and advice from
the other end, Thorpe gradually settled, then blossomed into an innings that
yielded 20 confidence-boosting boundaries.
``It was good to get into some form and rhythm with the second Test coming
up,'' he said.
``I do not think I was really with it at Kimberley, having just flown back from
England, but I knuckled down here and now, hopefully, I can carry on.''
With Stewart blazing his way to 110 in 182 deliveries and with 21 fours, the
county colleagues added 141 at the rate of a run a minute after England had
slipped to 45 for two.
Mike Atherton's ninth ball duck, fending off a bouncer from Nicko Pretorius
into Louis Wilkinson's hands at gully, was no real cause for concern, given the
captain's high class first Test knock of 78.
But Mark Ramprakash's failure, dragging on a delivery from medium-pacer Chris
Craven after having made 15, should give England food for thought.
They seemed determined to stand by Ramprakash next week, despite his poor track
record at Test level, and their loyalty is commendable.
But an alternative for the No.3 spot exists for John Crawley, who had little
chance to shine here, with England declaring after he had contributed 28 to a
total of 316 for four.
The Lancashire youngster is, however, in prime form and clearly brimming with
confidence. Scoreboard:
