<HEADLINE>Cruise in a desert ship</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<FLAG>road tests</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN Arab countries, wealthy families who used to go into the desert with their
camels nowadays often use Toyota Landcruisers instead. In Third World
countries, it is remarkable how frequently aid workers and staff of development
agencies are seen doing the same.
The Landcruiser seems to be omnipresent in places where really tough, powerful,
but in certain specifications air-conditioned and quite luxurious transport is
required. Toyota has built more than 2.5 million examples since going into the
all-terrain vehicle business seriously in 1951.
Some 4x4s sold here are lifestyle accessories, but the Landcruiser is a
massively built rough-country vehicle or impressive tow car. It has the ground
clearance, traction and tremendous pull to make it a fine mud-plugger, but
somehow the usual British off-road exercises seem quite small beer when you
look at a four-wheel-drive machine like this, designed to batter along for long
distances in real journeys through difficult terrain.ddddddd
Toyota believes in plenty of power and plenty of torque for its top-line 4x4.
The eight-seater Land- cruiser VX automatic at #38,689 comes with a 4477cc
six-cylinder petrol engine peaking at 202bhp, but I have been driving one of
the turbo diesel versions, able to meet the European Step 2 emission
regulations coming into force next year.
This engine is fitted to the VX manual at #39,120 and the more modestly
equipped five-seater GS manual at #29,630. All three models are provided with
serious off-tarmac items like a high and low ratio transfer box, as well as
front, centre and rear-locking differentials.
The 4164cc turbo diesel engine is one of the few in the world using multi-valve
technology. Its 168bhp output will haul the Landcruiser to 60mph in 12.5
seconds, but the most important performance element is the 280lb ft of torque,
which gives it immense mid-range pull. Lumbering along in slow traffic, the
diesel engine sounds like something which ought to be powering a bus. Moving
more quickly, it is quieter and freer of vibrations than most of its rivals.
With a high seating position and easy power steering, the Landcruiser is simple
to drive, although really wide in the rear flanks and with a large turning
circle. Scrapes on the nearside rear wheel arch, caused when I skelped the test
car against my own garden gate, are embarrassing evidence of that.
From its general specification many people might suppose that the Landcruiser
scores virtually no marks for ride quality. One of the surprises of this
well-matured       design is that the suspension intended to take so many Third
World shocks lets            it progress remarkably smoothly on ordinary
Scottish roads.
</TEXT>
