<HEADLINE>New assets benefit Currie European</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New assets
benefit
Currie
European
By ROBERT POWELL
MARTIN Currie European Investment Trust has done well over the last six months,
benefitting from strong dividend growth and a good performance by some of its
new investments.
Fully diluted net asset value per share rose 8.1% to 127.1p during the half
year to October 31, outperforming a 7.2% increase in the FT Actuaries Europe
(ex-UK) Index.
Dividend income rose by 50% #486,000 and the #30.5m trust benefited from the
selective purchase of new issues such as the Italian mobile phone company
Telecom Italia Mobil, the shoe and luxury goods manufacturer Gucci and the
German pharmaceutical company Merck. Edinburgh-based fund manager Martin Currie
said the outlook for 1996 in Continental Europe was promising, given the
prospects for low inflation and a further cut in interest rates.
``We are likely to see more new issues and further privatisations in the months
ahead which could provide some selective opportunities,'' it said.
Holdings in France and Germany were reduced from a combined total of 35% of the
portfolio to 29% as the German market appeared increasingly expensive and
long-awaited monetary reforms in France failed to come through.
The trust, meanwhile, boosted its position in Switzerland, which accounts for
12% of the portfolio, and Italy, which accounts for 7%. As usual, there was no
interim dividend.
