<HEADLINE>Superstars fail to sparkle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET McMASTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224935</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a typical Open opening day. A posse of unheralded, little-known
journeymen and youngsters cluttered the upper reaches of the leaderboard
yesterday after the first round of the Australian Open in Melbourne, while the
superstars failed to sparkle.
A nap hand of Aussies - Rob Whitlock, Lyndsay Stephen, David Bransdon, Peter
McWhinney, and Lucien Tinkler - shared the lead on 68, four under par, while
the group on 69 included former US PGA champion Wayne Grady and New Zealander
Michael Campbell.
Greg Norman, making the worst possible start, was three over par after eight
holes, but finished on level par after making three birdies. The other big
attraction, John Daly, shot 73.
There are plenty of trees at Kingston Heath and Daly was more constrained than
he ever was at St Andrews last July. Even using an iron off the tee, the
American could out-hit both his playing partners, but they outscored  him.
Campbell had five birdies in his 69 and Wayne Riley, who won this title in
1991, shot 71.
Daly had trouble reading the greens and Norman found them as fast as anything
he has ever putted on. Leading scores (Australian unless stated):
