<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tam's golden opportunity ends up in the air</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224936</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TAM Dalyell, the West Lothian Labour MP, is famous for being persistently
loquacious on the subject of the Lockerbie Pan-Am bombing. Tam has bombarded
Lord Rodger, the Lord Advocate, with letters on the issue.
Imagine, then, the horror of Lord Rodger to find himself plonked side by side
with Tam on the London Shuttle with the prospect of an hour-long grilling from
which there could be no escape. Alas for Tam, he was oblivious to the identity
of the gent occupying the neighbouring seat.
Mind you, who do you know who would definitely win a prize in a Spot the Lord
Advocate competition?
One bark for aye
THE important deliberations of Strathkelvin Council licencing board were
delayed this week when only four members turned up - one short of the required
quorum. The councillors were debating what to do next when who should be
spotted walking his dog in the adjacent park but one of the duly elected
members of the board.
A polisman in attendance was duly dispatched to ask the councillor if he would
make himself available for civic duties. He did so and the due processes of
municipal majesty went ahead thanks to five cooncillors and a dug.
What's in a name
WE have mentioned once or twice before Mr John Reid, principal of Bell College,
Hamilton. He is famous for his direct manner of speech (giving rise to his
nickname Rab C. - one of many affectionate cognomens) and for the impressive
rise to some #90,000 a year he managed to achieve in his annual salary as a
reward for taking the college (or University of Hamilton as it will surely soon
be known) ever upward further-education-wise.
We hear Mr Reid has yet another nickname - JC. Not because he is a godlike
figure. The initials stand for Johnny Cash, a reference to his salary.
A belly laugh
A SPHERICALLY challenged chum of the Diary (not unlike the Diary really) tells
us the Panorama interview with Lady Di struck a chord. He now knows that during
a recent period of low self-esteem he too was suffering from bulimia. Sad thing
was he got the bingeing bit just right but did not realise you were supposed to
throw up afterwards.
Sounds like a Derek Johnstone joke to us.
Fare enough
THE quantity of beggars in post-ceasefire Belfast may be small but there is no
doubting the quality. Engaged in conversation with a wee guy called Bobby in a
city centre bar we were first asked what team we supported - Kilmarnock seemed
to cause little reaction either way - then tapped for a couple of quid.
Declining to pay up but offering him a pint in lieu we were told: ``No, it's
not for drink, I want to get a taxi up the road.''
q PASSING Campbell College near Stormont our party was informed this was the
only public school in Belfast and catered for the cream of Ulster society -
so-called because they are all rich and thick.
Job creation
LOOKING through the situations vacant columns (as you do - you never know the
minute) we notice Glasgow City Council has vacancies for a ``creative services
officer (electrician)'' and a ``creative services technician (joiner)'' for its
museum and art galleries department.
We wish all applicants well and can imagine the celebrations of the successful
candidates in whatever pub. ``Are you still at the joinery?'' an acquaintance
might ask. ``No. I'm in creative services.''
``And what about big Willie the spark?'' ``He's doing awfy well. He's just been
appointed creative services officer.''
``Do you still do homers?'' ``No problem. And if you want a few pictures hung,
we'll throw that in for free.''
q In the same edition of the Herald jobs pages, a Glasgow company advertised
five vacancies for psychics, clairvoyants, and fortune tellers. A reader asks:
``Surely all these posts were filled before the advert appeared?''
q Finally, on the jobs front, we see an advert for ``experienced chick
sexers''. Before you get out your CV, we should point out it appeared in
Poultry World. Yes, those kind of chicks.
Gobstoppers
We at the Diary are second to none in our furtherance of the Scots tongue. Thus
we recommend, for those inevitable lulls in the pub conversation, a book of
Scottish proverbs published by Birlinn at #5.99.
It includes such handy phrases as:
q Ye was wheedle a laverock frae the lift. You would charm the birds from the
sky.
q What makes you sae rumgunshach and me sae curcuddoch? Why are you so rude and
unpleasant to me when I am so friendly and anxious to please you?
q She that fa's ower a strae's a tentless taupie. A person who falls at the
smallest of obstacles is a fool.
We should point that trying to read the whole book at one go can lead to
feeling ``forjidged, forefoughten, and forejeskit'' - An alliterative
expression denoting extreme fatigue.
And please remember: ``A bonny bride is soon buskit and a short horse is soon
whispit.'' Which, of course, needs no translation but we we will tell you
anyway - it means a slight task is soon finished.
</TEXT>
