<HEADLINE>Dodds aims to bury jinx tag and sink his former club</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Broadley</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF Billy Dodds helps Aberdeen to success in the Coca-Cola Cup final he might
not be seen around Pittodrie for a few days, because the little striker is
planning a massive party to make up for all the bad times which have blighted
his career.
Dodds saw his dream move as a teenager to Chelsea axed, then he was relegated
from Scotland's top division with both Dundee and St Johnstone.
He said: ``If we lift the cup you won't see me for a while. That would be the
highlight of my career and would compensate for all the hard times.
``When I signed for Aberdeen I never thought for a moment that we would be
embroiled in relegation. Even my mates were giving me stick that I was a jinx.
I simply kept my head down and stepped up my work-rate.
``Last season was a fluke. Basically, it is the same team who were fighting
relegation which has taken us to this final, as Paul Bernard is the only
newcomer.
``We could not afford to look back or we would have found ourselves in exactly
the same position once again. But manager Roy Aitken has drummed into us that
we are winners.
``This is a huge club desperate for success. If we play as we did in the
semi-final we must have a great chance. But it won't be easy against Dundee.
``Jim Duffy has them playing quality football and his team has a bit of
everything - experience, youth and flair. But we have a lot of talent and know
we are a good side now.
``It would make my day at Hampden and mean so much to win this trophy.''
Eoin Jess and keeper Theo Snelders stepped up their training yesterday and are
confident of being fit for Hampden.
q MOTHERWELL striker Tommy Coyne, who has been out of action for a month with a
knee injury, has seen his comeback delayed yet again.
Fir Park manager Alex McLeish said: ``Tommy went to a specialist and his
return, unfortunately, looks like being later rather than sooner. It's
disappointing because he is a very important player for us.
``But we will not rush him back. He'll receive the proper rest and will only
return when fully fit.''
McLeish was forced into playing himself at Kilmarnock last Saturday and he may
have to turn out again for the basement battle with Falkirk as his problems
mount.
Said the manager: ``Apart from our long-term victims, John Philliben, Eddie
May, Jamie Dolan and Rob McKinnon are struggling a little.
``I would say Rob has the best chance. He made his comeback last week after
being out for 10 weeks and he felt a bit of tiredness within his muscles.''
</TEXT>
