<HEADLINE>London Festival Orchestra, Glasgow Cathedral</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS was stop-over Glasgow for the London Festival Orchestra on their annual
round Britain Cathedral Concert Series tour. The format this time at each of
the five venues visited is to engage the local cathedral choir for a couple of
choral numbers and then flesh out the rest of the programme by selecting
assortments from the band's extensive repertoire.
So last night it was Glasgow Cathedral Choir's turn and their contributions
opened both halves of the concert. While the 16-strong group looked splendidly
bright, garbed in scarlet robes, their performances unfortunately sounded
muffled and colourless under the baton of their director John Turner. Not
entirely the choir's fault, perhaps, as building works in the cathedral
resulted in the audience seated facing down the nave towards the entrance with
the singers standing on the rear steps, backs tight up against the huge doors
and required to project over the orchestra.
Where in the Haydn works and even in forays Cantique de Jean Rancine the
ensemble playing tended towards the thick and woolly, textures became
immediately cleaner when Ross Pople, LFO director, took over to conduct the
purely instrumental pieces. Janacek's Suite for Strings was suitably astringent
in tone and Lucy Wakeford tripped delicately through the Debussy Dances for
Harp and Orchestra.
For the concluding work Ross Pople directed from the cello desk, joining an
account of Dvorak's Serenade for Strings that tipped the programme dangerously
close to an excess of saccherine.
q Sponsored by the After Eight Collection.
</TEXT>
