<DOCNO>GH951124-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flockhart fights back to oust seed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH champion Bruce Flockhart boosted his Olympic hopes when he put out the
3/4 seed, Chinese-born American Kevin Han, in the second round of the Scottish
Open at the Kelvin Hall yesterday.
The 23-year-old Stirling University student is the first Scot in 20 years to
reach the men's singles quarter-finals.
Ranked 26 places below his opponent in the world, Flockhart now has a prime
opportunity to prove himself, with the race to Atlanta fast gathering momentum.
He will meet fellow Brit Anders Nielsen at the next hurdle, another player
keenly contesting an Olympic berth.
Flockhart took time to find his feet against Han, struggling in the first game
to lose out 15-4 in a matter of minutes. But the twice National champion
rallied to win the next almost as comfortably, 15-5, and made the most of Han's
errors in the last to win 15-12.
Scottish champion Anne Gibson also battled through, defeating Poland's
Katarzyna Krasowka by an easy 11-2, 11-8.
``I play England's Tanya Groves next, and I just hope it's not third time lucky
for her, because we've met twice this season and I've won both times,'' said
Gibson.
Victory for 27-year-old Gibson could be enough to propel her above rival Julia
Mann in the world rankings, so fuelling her Olympic dreams.
GILLIAN DORRICOTT
</TEXT>
