<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Traders remain confident as the Footsie tumbles</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROFIT-taking and two Monopoly and Merger Commission referrals forced most
equities to finish lower after Wednesday's record close, but dealers said the
market's upward trend was still intact.
``But for the electricity referrals, it was a pretty steady day considering it
was (US) Thanksgiving,'' one trader said. ``It was always likely that we would
have a down day, especially with the US on holiday.''
US financial markets were closed yesterday in observance of the annual
Thanksgiving holiday. American markets will close early today.
The UK Government's decision to refer two electricity sector bids to the MMC
sent the FTSE-100 index of leading shares back down to the 3600 level. Key
support held, but the market closed down 29.9 points at 3602.5.
The referral to the MMC of PowerGen's bid for Midlands Electricity and National
Power's offer for Southern Electric unsettled the electricity sector, that had
grown used to the Government nodding through takeover bids.
Southern Electric shares finished the day at 913p, down 62p, while Midlands
Electricity dropped 59p to 918p.
National Power lost 16p to 478p while PowerGen finished down 21p at 540p.
Despite the referrals, dealers said bid activity was likely to continue,
resulting in further highs for UK shares.
``We haven't seen the last of the bids,'' one dealer said. ``Company balance
sheets are pretty strong and they have to do something with the cash.
``Companies can either give the cash back to shareholders or they can make
bids,'' he added. ``Our bet is the bids will continue well into 1996.''
In the bond market, gilts closed higher during light trading in a market with
few sellers. Traders expect bonds to remain quiet until Tuesday's budget speech.
December long-gilt futures reached a new contract high of 109-08 during the day
before closing 9/32 up at 109-04.
In the equities market, the water sector saw the first-ever takeover of a
privatised group by a foreign company when Northumbrian Water agreed to a #823m
bid from French group Lyonnaise des Eaux.
The Newcastle-based group's shares jumped 35p to 1169p in reaction to terms
worth 1179p a share in cash and special dividends.
Other water group shares went higher on rumours of further bid moves. Severn
Trent led the way at 665p, up 8p.
North West Water was up 4p to 609p after its interim results showed growing
profits.
Forte saw quieter trading than yesterday at 351p, up 4p, as dealers learned
that Japan's Suntory did not want to make a counter-bid to Granada's #3.3bn
offer. Granada gained 4p to 653p.
Paper and packaging group Ferry Pickering improved 24p to 192p on a #26m
takeover by Wace, which also expanded its greeting card business with a
separate acquisition in Dublin. Wace fell by 6p to 239p.
Polar raced up 52p to 430p after a merger deal to create a stronger electronic
components firm with Abacus, which improved by 1p to 279p.
Powell Duffryn was a big loser as it reversed 74!sp to 480!sp on losses,
including almost #30m of one-off charges, and after a cautious statement on
prospects for its fuel business in the key winter months.
Storehouse advanced by 10p to 332p after better-than-forecast interim profits
of #34.5m, up 42%.
Its Mothercare stores made up for poorer trading at the Bhs chain. Chief
executive Keith Edelman said that September and October had been bad months,
though the stores group had seen some improvement in November.
The insurance sector stood out while most other top stocks were hit by
profit-taking.
Legal &amp; General, which recently announced a #160m windfall for with-profits
policyholders, was up 11p to 706p. Commercial Union was another in demand with
a 8p gain to 643p.
Inchcape was a major loser at 238p, down 18p, on the belief that it will lose
its status as a FTSE member and be relegated from the list.
Publisher Dorling Kindersley added 24p to 528p after Microsoft sold its 17.9%
stake at 507p.
A profits warning at money broker Exco sent it 21p lower to 120p and a grim
trading update from property group Regent Corporation sent it diving 2!sp to 5p.
Cable &amp; Wireless gave up 13p to 453p after a run on the shares of its Hong Kong
Telecoms subsidiary in the wake of the C&amp;W boardroom upheavals.
Engineer Babcock International was cut down 13p to 148p after a downbeat
results statement and losses in its German business.
</TEXT>
