<HEADLINE>Third-quarter GDP figures show recovery has stalled</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAN-GERMAN gross domestic product growth was static in the third quarter of
this year from the second quarter, the Economics Ministry said yesterday in its
latest monthly report.
Economists said the news confirmed their belief that the recovery from
Germany's deepest post-war recession in 1993 had ground to a halt in the second
half of 1995.
The Ministry said: ``We expect that seasonally adjusted real GDP was near
enough unchanged in the third quarter from the second and that the year-on-year
change was clearly lower than that of the first half of the year.''
Pan-German year-on-year GDP growth was 2.6% in the first half of this year.
The Federal Statistics Office is due to release detailed data on third-quarter
GDP on December 7 but the Economics Ministry often releases its own estimate in
advance.
The Ministry said the situation on the labour market remained very
unsatisfactory. Unemployment has risen for the last three months in a row.
``In West Germany there is not enough economic activity to bring any relief to
the labour market.''
It said a clear improvement in the jobs situation was not yet in sight largely
as a result of the economic slowdown. Industrial orders and output fell in the
third quarter from the second.
``The development in this economic cycle is clearly much less favourable than
than in previous cycles,'' the report said.
The main reasons for the slowdown were a less buoyant world economy, the
strengthening of the mark against most currencies which has led to firms losing
share in world markets.
``These problems were exacerbated by high wage rises and rises in supplementary
wage costs,'' it said. - Reuter
</TEXT>
