<HEADLINE>Scots off to a bright start</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224944</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANY of the Scottish contingent yesterday set about restoring pride from poor
past performances in the PGA European Tour Qualifying School in Spain with
strong opening rounds over the more demanding San Roque course.
Longniddry's Raymond Russell and Scott Henderson of Kings Links both carded
two-under-par 70s across the 7044-yard course on the sun-drenched Costa del Sol
to settle in third place. Buchanan Castle's William Guy was on 73.
Former Walker Cup player Russell enjoyed calm morning conditions and carded
three birdies and a single bogey. The 23-year-old narrowly missed qualification
at his two previous attempts.
With temperatures as high as 30C, Russell rolled in an eight-foot putt to
birdie the 395-yard second and made pars until the 443-yard eleventh, where a
20-foot putt dropped. A later bogey was countered at the 207-yard sixteenth,
where his No.4-iron tee shot ended two feet from the hole.
Former Scottish assistants' champion Henderson crashed with a closing 80 at
Montpellier last season. The 26-year-old's opening effort improved on that
total by 10 in a round which included five birdies.
Guy's round comprised two bogeys and a birdie. Having failed last season at the
fourth play-off hole, the Glasgow golfer could contend again this week.
At Guadalmina, Walker Cup player Stephen Gallacher posted a one-over-par 72
while Downfield's Andrew Crerar was round in level par. Leading scores:
