<HEADLINE>MANUFACTURING Threat to 75 jobs at heater firm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224945</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEATOVENT Electric, an East Kilbride based company which manufactures heating
appliances, has been forced into receivership, placing 75 jobs at risk.
Coopers and Lybrand, which was yesterday appointed receiver, said it would try
to sell the company as a going concern.
Heatovent specialises in manufacturing storage heaters and has annual sales of
#4.5m, but the expenses involved in a move to new premises led to a cash
squeeze.
``The company moved to larger premises in East Kilbride in 1993,'' said Coopers
&amp; Lybrand corporate recovery partner Ian Rankin. ``The increase in overheads
unfortunately coincided with a downturn in the market leading to cash
difficulties.''
``With an order book of #700,000, we will continue trading with a view to
finding a buyer for the business as a going concern. Some interest has been
show, even at this early stage.'' he added.
</TEXT>
