<HEADLINE>BBC seal five-year deal with WPBSA Ramsay wins top sporting award</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224946</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALISON Ramsay, the former Great Britain internationalist and the most-capped
woman player in the world, last night joined the list of all-time Scottish
greats when she was presented with the MacRobert Thistle Award for her services
to hockey by Glasgow's Lord Provost Tommy Dingwall at the City Chambers.
Ramsay retired from the international scene in June after having played in a
record 257 internationals (150 for Scotland and 107 in the colours of Britain)
including the defeat of Korea for the bronze medal at the Barcelona Olympics.
Ramsay's interest, like the rest of British hockey, will be focused on the
Hartleyvale Stadium in Cape Town this afternoon when the current British side
will attempt to secure a place at the Atlanta Olympics.
Britain still require two points to be certain of advancing as one of the five
qualifiers but their task was simplified yesterday when China beat South Africa
1-0 and Canada surprisingly beat European champions Holland 1-0 from a goal by
Karen MacNeill three minutes from time. Results:
South Africa 1, China 2; Holland 0, Canada 1. Placings - 1, Germany, 8 points;
2, Korea, 7; 3, Argentina, 7; 4, GB, 6; 5, Holland 5; 6, China 5; 7, S Africa
3; 8, Canada 3.
q.GREAT Britain, fielding Scot Colin Hector, beat Argentina 4-2 at Reading last
night. Russell Garcia (2), Don Williams, and Rob Thomson were the home scorers.
q.THE men's indoor season gets under way at the Bell's Sport Centre in Perth
tomorrow.
</TEXT>
