<DOCNO>GH951124-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ING sees earnings advance by 15%</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224948</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Amsterdam, Thursday - DUTCH banking and insurance giant Internationale
Nederlanden Groep (ING) today announced its net profit rose 15% in the year's
first nine months while total income went up 7.1%.
The income rise was fuelled by steady growth in its insurance activities and an
improved result from financial transactions in its banking activities, ING said.
Net profit for 1995's first three quarters was 1880m guilders, up from 1640m
guilders for the same period last year.
ING's total income reached 29.13bn guilders, 7.1% higher than the 27.19bn
recorded at this stage of 1994.
Earnings per share rose to 6.87 guilders, from 6.24 guilders in the
year-earlier period.
ING said its pre-tax result from banking and insurance activities combined in
the first nine months rose 16.1% to 2760m guilders.
After deduction of dividend payments on own shares, ING was left with a pretax
result of 2720m guilders.
ING reiterated earlier forecasts that net profit per ordinary share for the
whole of 1995 will top 1994's level.
The group said the growth of income and operating expenditure in its banking
activities was influenced by the inclusion of Barings in the consolidated
accounts.
ING bought the failed British merchant bank after it collapsed early this year
amid massive losses blamed on rogue dealer Nick Leeson who arrived today in
Singapore to face trial for his deals.
Barings showed a modest positive result, according to ING, with Barings Asset
Management making a contribution to this.
On the Amsterdam Stock Exchange, ING put on one guilder to close at 100.90,
after its results gained a good reception from investors. - AP/Reuter
n Warsaw, Thursday - General Motors Corporation and its German division, Adam
Opel, are planning an investment worth up to $390m to build a production plant
in Poland.
Opel Chairman David Herman met Polish Industry and Trade Minister Klemens
Scierski to pave the way for opening detailed negotiations next month.
Mr Herman said the company was considering a greenfield production facility
with capacity of up to 100,000 passenger cars a year.The overall investment
could range from $280m to $390m, he said.
The location of the site will be established during negotiations and Opel
planned to make its final decision next year.
The announcement follows the November 14 decision by GM's Polish partner,
Warsaw's FSO car factory, to sell a controlling stake to the South Korean giant
Daewoo. The Koreans agreed to invest more than $1100m in the Polish carmaker. -
AP
</TEXT>
