<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack McLean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224949</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WEE boys born during the War were practically princes. Mind you wee girls were
equally royalty. Mums looked after their children and held them close in those
dark days when their men were off getting killed and maimed or, more often,
more stupid with the tedium of battle. Very proud of wee boys, mothers were
then. After all, mothers knew that their sons would grow up to defend them, the
poor bleeders. Fifty years on most mothers probably still do, but not if you
were to go by every bloody blatt in a quarter of a century.
Not one single daily rag exists without an egregious onslaught against the
gender with the sticky-out bit from women. Not ordinary women of course.
Ordinary women make splendid mums by and large, and decent enough wives, and
lovely girlfriends, and as for aunties and grandmas . . . But every blatt has a
special combination of special pleading and outright penis envy which must
surely embarrass media women.
Our own paper saw two serious onslaughts on males within the past five days and
very cliche-ridden they were at that. Truth to tell I mind the cliches rather
more than the insults, but it might be suggested that were male writers or
broadcasters to state that kind of near-racist contumely which it is thought
enlivens blatts and TV and radio programmes, they would be sacked.
I have had the insensitivity of men and the tenderness of women up to the point
at which one begins to question questions.
Sensitivity? The past 20 years has seen a grand array of sensitive women who
have challenged the male establishment. Mrs Marcos, Mrs Thatcher, Mrs Windsor,
and now, I suppose, Mrs West. No doubt there is some excuse for these sirens
which female commentators can put up and I shall be interested to discover such
ingenuities.
I feel, most men I know, feel, beleagured at every turn by the media, the
social agencies, the politicians, the bloody know-alls, and the professional
jeremiahs of the gender war. But the last straw came with one of my colleagues
this week. She complained about men of course, but the complaint was that we
always won quizzes in pubs.
This is a bit like saying that the reason why I win quizzes is because I know
more or, come to think of it, the reason why the other team won was because
they were better. What possible harm can pub quizzes be, or any other quizzes,
including the ones I have been happy to take part in of a Christmas dinner with
my family?
Our commentator the other week in the blatt suggested that men were incapable
of asking the serious questions about emotions and feelings and . . . I never
heard such drivel. The overwhelming majority of bleeding violets who make up
the poetic tradition since the Greeks for heaven's sake right through to the
Romantics, and the Georgians, and then the War poets, and then on to - until
the monstrous regiment of lady neurotics in the post-War years - have been men.
Just give me one - one female Love poet to touch Donne, or Spencer, or
Shakespeare, or Burns, or Yeats, or any bloody one at all. Now get out of my
way.
But why do the ladies get up so much of a head of steam in their condemnation
of men, what they get up to, the games they play, quizzes, rugby, and football,
and why do they become so upset when it turns out that with a few exceptions
men are the better musicians and writers and artists and politicians and
anything else and why do they crack up most of all when it is proved that any
woman can be as good as any man in any field. All they have to be is just as
good.
Why do I have to find myself pressing the button on Women's Hour because I
can't cope with any more serials about a mulatto girl in St Helena whose father
was the younger son of the wicked Duke of Buckingham? (Anybody who listens in
to Women's Hour has come to heart-sinking when the dread phrase ``And now time
for our serial'' slides across the airwaves.)
Why do I have to read the sort of bar-room punditry from birds in Jaeger suits
and find myself throwing away damn-near every newspaper and magazine which
comes my way?
When my mother had me during the War I was doubtless a young warrior to be. But
in those days, even a wee boy was loved for being a child who would become a
man: not a figure of ill-placed and resentful hostility, as it seems to be
today.
</TEXT>
