<HEADLINE>Backyard thinking can grow contrary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Julie Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224950</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT has not been a week to make light of things, but stuck in a groove in my
head has been the famous exit line of Voltaire's novel, Candide. ``True
enough,'' says Candide, who has finally learned he cannot change the course of
history, ``but we must go and work in the garden.''
A colloquial English translation misses the precision and philosophical charge
of the French: ``Il faut cultiver notre jardin.'' Our garden, our own backyard.
We must not neglect it, we must make it productive. Voltaire's hero has decided
a strategy of benign and constructive parochialism better serves the world than
high-minded interference in its broader business.
It's an attractive position, but one which looks risky when parochialism turns
malign and destructive. In the vicious parish-pump politics of the Balkans,
heads are knocked together by ``the international community'', mainly America,
whose high-minded president whistles in the dark of a confused agenda.
Will the patchwork peace work, or will the intervention of its brokers cause
more and wider blood-letting?
In the handsome English town of Gloucester, Fred and Rosemary West cultivated
their garden and turned it into a mass grave. What could be more parochial than
their own little world - the exclusive intimacy of their shared hobby? Who
could be more disastrously provincial than the neighbours, relatives, friends
and acquaintances who have crawled out of the woodwork to maximise the assets
of long-held misgivings and suspicions? But the surface brutality of the Wests'
life, the squalid sex, the beating of their children, was ``none of our
business''.
Among the least successful horticulturists in their own gardens are the media,
whose useful function of reporting the news has long since been overtaken by
the urge to interfere through explaining it, sometimes helpfully, sometimes
fancifully, but always officiously. And if we can't lay our hands on an
explanation, if we can't understand the neighbours' war in Bosnia, if we talk
to all the experts and still find nothing to explain the Wests, then an opinion
will do.
I, for example, have an opinion this week on the postal workers' unofficial
strike which began in Edinburgh and spread elsewhere, and my opinion couldn't
be more parochial, even if it's hard to cultivate your garden when you haven't
had any mail for four days. I try to see the broad picture of a workforce made
nervous by doubts about an uncertain future which we all share - as much in the
newspaper industry as anywhere - but it isn't easy to get past the view from my
overdraft.
Between them the Royal Mail and their workers have brought bitter new meaning
to the promise: ``The cheque's in the post.'' The bedrock of my monthly income,
the cheque for my freelance work for The Herald, has been lying all week in a
sorting office somewhere in Edinburgh.
I won't starve, of course; I have funds elsewhere and a pack of credit and
account cards, and if the worst comes to the worst I can always borrow pocket
money from my husband.
But there will be bank charges to pay on all the regular transactions the
cheque normally covers, and there will be many other people for whom the
disrupted mail service means real hardship.
The private customers, the business ones, all of us feeling aggrieved by the
poor return on the support we gave to postal workers when the Royal Mail was
under threat of privatisation; some of us now cursing their panicky
pariochialism and making plans for a future which will be less and less
dependant on a method of communication which looks more and more inefficient.
I'm not just talking about the indifference and incompetence of individual
postal workers, although we've got those, too, in Edinburgh. (Among the mixture
of personal, business and junk mail which arrives daily in our household there
are regularly misdelivered, not misaddressed, letters.) I'm talking about the
cumbersome business of physically transporting envelopes and their contents
between senders and receivers. It already seems quaint. Its days are surely
numbered.
The modest, one-woman business run from a back room in our home was very slow
to enter the age of electronic communications, but it now uses the Royal Mail
much less than it did. The hard copy which once went into the post, sometimes
into Express if deadlines pressed, now disappears down a telephone line with
the help of a modem. Documents and letters come and go by fax. The National
Magazine Company, occasional employers, electronically deposit their fees for
my work straight into my bank account.
I'm not sure why Caledonian Publishing, who are much more regular employers,
don't pay me electronically, too, but I'll be making inquiries; and if all
that's required is some information about my bank account then one more regular
delivery will be lost to the Royal Mail. Perhaps a little bit of tangible
satisfaction - the comforting crackle of a freshly-issued cheque - will also
disappear, but in my first job they used to hand out banknotes in little brown
envelopes. It's a long time since I had any sentimental feelings about this
insecure and often grubby method of payment. I'll adjust.
Lately, I've begun to feel we've been too sentimental about the Royal Mail and
the parochial nirvana which is the status of the sub-post office. There are two
sub post-offices within a few minutes walk from my house/place-of-work and at
least one of them is one too many.
Support your local post office? Why? It closes every lunchtime and takes half
the day off on Wednesdays and Saturday. It's an anachronism.
Support your local postal workers? They'll have to give me a better reason than
their vital contribution to the Christmas card industry. I can live without
second deliveries, and I'm sure I can learn to live without first.
</TEXT>
