<HEADLINE>How Scotland lays down the law over witnesses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARGARET VAUGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224952</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE threats of a new law to ban the media from paying witnesses, in the wake of
the Rosemary West trial, have all the feeble force of plastic sabres rattling.
For legal remedies already exist which could have been used to keep cash out of
the courtroom at Winchester, according to senior legal figures who believe the
Attorney General already has the power to deal with such cases. They cite the
1981 Contempt of Court Act and criminal law which can be used against those
suspected of interfering with witnesses.
The real question is not how to stop lucrative liaisons between witnesses with
a lurid tale to tell and those willing to pay for them in future. It is why it
was allowed to happen at all in the West case.
Yesterday Attorney General Sir Nicholas Lyell argued there was ``a strong
case'' for a change in the law and said he was ``seriously considering'' making
cheque-book journalism illegal in court cases.
The Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay, commissioned a report into the issue after
several witnesses admitted receiving up to #100,000 for their stories. And the
newspaper watchdog, the Press Complaints Commission, announced it will conduct
an inquiry because payments to witnesses is contrary to its voluntary code of
conduct.
At least seven witnesses at the West trial said they had taken payments ranging
from #750 to a reputed #100,000. It was revealed in court that witness Janet
Leach - who gave evidence about her conversations with Fred West while he was
held in prison - had a #12,000 agreement with a newspaper group for ``exclusive
rights'' to her story and a #100,000 agreement for a book.
Although Mrs Leach, a prison visitor, had at first lied about the payment in
court, she later admitted the offer, denying she had embellished her evidence
to make it more marketable.
There were claims that some witnesses were not called at all because of worries
that their evidence would be seen as tainted by the cash they had received.
Rosemary West's solicitor, Leo Goatley, said the defence team had ``very real
concern'' about the activities of certain members of the media. But aside from
the forlorn pleas from the defence lawyers and a rap on the knuckles for a
small local paper, the Attorney General did not tackle the antics of the
powerful national media giants who wafted tens of thousands of pounds under the
noses of witnesses.
Scotland's former Lord Justice General, Lord Emslie, Edinburgh University's
Professor of Scots Law, Robert Black, and the Crown Office all confirmed
yesterday that existing laws can be used against those who approach witnesses
in the run up to a trial.
Although England and Scotland have separate legal systems, the 1981 Contempt of
Court Act applies in both countries. And on both sides of the Border there is a
law to deal with interference with the course of justice.
Lord Emslie believes that approaches to witnesses before a trial are covered by
the common law: ``It's my impression that this is already covered by the law on
the perversion of the course of justice, or attempts to do so, or by acts
calculated to do so.
``It would cover the danger of witnesses being persuaded, or encouraged, to
polish their evidence to suit the fee they were to get. Presumably the fee is
calculated on the view that the witness is able to give a fairly dramatic
account of a particular event. If the witness felt like it, I suppose the
testimony could be made dramatic, whereas in the truth of the matter it might
not be.''
He did not believe the Contempt of Court Act, which says that any publication
which creates a substantial risk of serious prejudice to forthcoming legal
proceedings and is punishable by imprisonment of up to two years, could have
been applied in the West trial.
Professor Black, however, says that while the Contempt of Court Act is
basically about publishing things likely to influence a jury in a trial, it
could have been applied if the witnesses were influenced by payments:
``If it can be established, and there is some evidence that witnesses were
giving evidence in a dramatic way because of the arrangements with newspapers,
there is no reason why the Attorney General shouldn't have taken proceedings
against them. It is too late now. But where was he when the problem was
extant?''
If the behaviour of newspapers was likely to influence the testimony that the
witness gave, that could well amount to contempt of court.
Similarly, the Crown Office indicated that it would come down hard on anyone
who made approaches to witnesses in a trial: ``Anything which interferes with
the course of justice may amount to the crime of attempting to pervert the
course of justice, or in certain circumstances contempt of court,'' a spokesman
explained.
The West case, arguably more than any other, illustrates how the law on
contempt of court, and the attendant substantial risk of prejudicing a fair
trial, are viewed north and south of the Border.
In Scotland, the legal strait-jacket ensures that when someone is arrested on a
serious charge you will read only the bare bones until the case comes to court.
In England, as the West case shows, the media will provide readers, viewers,
and listeners with a wealth of details about the case, publishing pictures of
the accused, background information, even apparent motives. The lurid reports
of Frederick West's case, after his suicide, but before his wife was tried, is
only the latest in a dishonourable list stretching back beyond the Yorkshire
Ripper.
In Scotland, journalists trying something similar would be viewing the case
from a small spartan cell. Yet in England, the Attorney General, responsible
for initiating contempt of court proceedings has more often sat on his hands.
A spokesman at the Attorney General's office yesterday sighed in admiration
over the ``very robust'' response taken by Scottish courts to the risks of
prejudicing a trial (although he wasn't aware, until he made checks that the
same law is on both sides of the Border) but he said the view of legal experts
in England was that the contempt of court act did not cover cheque-book
journalism.
While the law on interfering with witnesses exists, it would have to be proved
that there was intent to subvert or pervert the course of justice.
``If the journalist simply enters into an arrangement for payment or pays on
account of the story later, he would not have any malicious intent as far as
proceedings are concerned, he is merely interested in securing his copy. ``I am
well aware that the Scots tradition is much more robust, and it's not unusual
to find fairly similar offences having a rather different outcome in Scotland
and in England.''
In Scotland, newspapers and broadcasting organisations know to their cost the
risk of falling foul of the law. There have been heavy fines for publishing
articles that their English counterparts wouldn't even bother checking with a
lawyer.
Martin Smith, a Glasgow solicitor who advises on media law, was in no doubt
about his response to any journalist who might think about approaching a
witness: ``You are not allowed to approach witnesses, simple as that. You are
not supposed to question witnesses prior to their giving evidence. In my view
that could constitute contempt.
``If the West trial had been held in Scotland, no paper would have signed up
any of the witnesses before they gave evidence. That is the law.''
But then, to borrow a phrase from a court regular, Ian Hislop, the editor of
Private Eye - the law in England, as it applies to contempt hearings, is a
``banana''.
The case of the Taylor sisters who were freed after being found guilty of the
murder of a love rival because of prejudicial reporting during their trial. It
is but one outrageous case in point. Another includes the aborted trial of
Geoffrey Knights, the boyfriend of EastEnders' actress Gillian
Taylforth, for assault.
Then there is the Press Complaints Commission which says ``paying witnesses or
potential witnesses in current criminal proceedings'' violates its code of
conduct. Apart from a sharp skelp over the legs for an intrusion of privacy
given to the News of the World editor, Piers Morgan, it has yet to instigate
action in cases where gross contempt of court has been shown.
The purchase of a prostitute on Sunset Boulevard, by the News of the World, who
paid #100,000 to Divine Brown to deliver a blow to Hugh Grant's image with her
story of their late-night liaison in a car, may be held out as justification
for the practice. The paper sold 150,000 extra copies the week it appeared.
The qualities may still balk at such naked cheque-book journalism, not least
because they cannot afford it, it is hard to deny that bad practice soon drives
out good, and the need to sensationalise to sell means that straightforward
reporting is lost. That is one argument. The real risk though is that by
refusing to stand up to the powerful media forces who flout the law the chance
of real people seeking real justice is lost - along with respect for the
independence of the law. But that may be another argument entirely.
</TEXT>
