<HEADLINE>Minister changes laissez-faire approach on power company takeovers Lang catches City on hop</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224953</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT of the Board of Trade Ian Lang took share markets rather by surprise
yesterday when he referred PowerGen's bid for Midlands Electricity together
with National Power's offer for Southern Electric to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
He has perhaps given the impression that as far as the privatised utilities are
concerned it is virtually a free for all and anything goes.
In fact, though, there is a difference in that in both these cases a power
generator will be taking over an electricity distributor. The generating
companies and the distributors are in the same industry and, therefore, more
open to criticism that they could operate against the public interest after a
merger.
ScottishPower's bid for Manweb was waived through. It could be argued that
ScottishPower was already vertically integrated and operates separately
geographically, while Manweb can still shop around. But it still looks
anomalous in the light of yesterday's decision.
So far as the Trade Minister is concerned he still takes a somewhat
laissez-faire approach, stating yesterday that he did not believe vertical
integration between electricity generators and distributors was objectionable.
In fact, he said he did not find it objectionable in any sector.
So possibly on this occasion he has been rather pressured to make what could be
considered an uncharacteristic decision. But he admitted these two bids did
raise competition concerns, hence the referral.
It is the first time any of the bids in the electricity sector have been sent
to the MMC following the wave of takeover activity that has swept the industry,
not least from outside the UK.
In fact, Mr Lang earlier this month overruled the advice of the new
director-general of fair trading, John Bridgeman, and cleared North West
Water's #1800m bid for Manchester-based electricity distributor, Norweb. Mr
Bridgeman had recommended referral to the MMC. But it seems the Minister has
now drawn the line. And not before time.
No spree
APART from a few short-lived pockets in the year, the domestic retail
environment has been tough and if anything has recently shown signs of becoming
even more competitive. Consumers remain reluctant to go on a collective
shopping spree. This presents retailers with a problem because many of them
have grown fat in the past on the back of buoyant consumer spending and higher
selling prices.
Such paths to increased profitability no longer exist and may indeed be lost
for ever. Consumer spending is not expected to recover strongly in the months
ahead, despite the fact that billions of pounds are to be released in the new
year from the expiration of Tax Exempt Special Savings Schemes (Tessas). Having
acquired a nose for value for money merchandise, consumers show little signs of
giving it up.
If sales growth is to be smaller than in the past, costs have to be cut if
profits are to increase. Given that shop workers are not among the most highly
paid members of the workforce there is little scope to cut labour costs. The
supply chain is where many organisations are looking to streamline their costs.
Storehouse has joined Marks &amp; Spencer and Burton in seeking to concentrate on a
smaller number of key suppliers which provide around three-quarters of their
merchandise. These tend to be the larger suppliers, many of whom work for a
number of the major retailers.
The aim is to make the supply chain more responsive to customer demand. It is
early days yet for Storehouse but already its ``Breakthrough'' supply
initiative is starting to bear fruit in terms of better stock control and lower
markdowns.
The electronic revolution has provided an opportunity for retailers and their
suppliers to restructure traditional relationships, to speed up product
development and store replenishment, and to transform the accuracy and
efficiency of buying and merchandising processes.
This in turn enables retailers to provide customers with new standards of value
in terms of design, price, quality, and availability.
PFI problems
CBI Scotland has joined the long list of organisations expressing their concern
at the lack of progress in the Government's Private Finance Initiative, (PFI).
The organisation's new director, Iain McMillan, has written to Scottish
Secretary Michael Forsyth, requesting action on the stalled PFI.
Members of CBI Scotland are still reporting considerable difficulties with the
PFI. Mr McMillan says that some major infrastructure projects have slowed
dramatically because of PFI considerations. He added that despite earlier
substantial progress on the M74 project, there is little sign of construction
activity between the completed northern and southern sections.
The PFI was meant to breathe new life into the moribund construction sector but
has failed to live up to earlier expectations, with many projects tied up in
red tape. Accountancy firms and construction groups have have said what they
think needs to be done to kickstart the initiative. Namely, for the Government
to pick out a number of flagship projects and effectively manage them.
While there are no shortage of firms willing and able to participate in the PFI
they need some organising. It is unrealistic and short-sighted to expect them
to plan and instigate major infrastructure projects which have strategic
economic importance
</TEXT>
