<HEADLINE>Reforming tax system Complex and confusing structure</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224954</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN liberal democracies most people balance any resentment about paying taxes
with the acceptance of their necessity to meet collective need, from defence to
welfare. All existing systems have however grown up over time and, in Britain
in particular, it seems hard to institute much root and branch reform. Every
tax has its defenders as well as its victims and any change which moves
attention away from the last, is as likely to re-focus it elsewhere: the
Revenue has to feed a persistent hunger and it can hardly be surprising that
its attention is concentrated in extracting more from all existing sources
rather than on making these more rational and efficient. Yet the present
structure of UK taxation is both complex and confusing. It is fortunate that
millions are not expected to make tax returns, for they have a nightmarish
aspect which forces many to employ others (expensively) in their compilation.
The onset of self-assessment is likely to make matters worse in this respect,
however; and the draconian impositions now at the disposal of the Inland
Revenue may yet breed a far more hostile response to the whole business.
The onset of the Budget is a good time to give such matters an airing. It would
make many lives, politicians', administrators' including tax officials'; but
also taxpayers', easier if the tax system were simplified. That is especially
true of income tax which may now produce much less than half the revenues but
still impacts most on everyone's consciousness. The way in which the tax and
benefits systems interact sometimes means, for example, that some individuals
in effect encounter tax rates of 80%, now widely recognised to be destructive.
A thorough reform would disentangle the two systems as they at present
interact, though it would be even more desirable to integrate them, a
dispensation which seems, so far, to have been found practically impossible,
although the Lib Dems still champion it in theory. We certainly ought to take
millions out of the tax net altogether, and keep them out. Most Budgets do take
large numbers out but the phenomenon known as fiscal drag inexorably brings
them back. Low inflation and modest earnings increases may keep them out now.
Several tax bands make for complexity. Labour's new 10% band is an error as is
the partial switch to 20% from 25% on which the Conservatives are engaged,
while retaining 40% as a top (to which Labour might add a new 50% rate). The
fewer the separate rates the better; and changes should have the effect of
taking taxpayers out of the net altogether rather than merely complicating the
arithmetic all have to endure when additional rates are introduced.
Somewhat similar logic should apply to tax concessions designed to add to the
attractions of various activities the state would wish to encourage, from
direct saving to home ownership. This is quite apart from the way in which the
tax system, in its corporate form, is supposed to encourage investment. The
outcome produces huge volumes of paper work; but can sometimes have other more
beneficial effects. The question is whether it is worth the candle. The
abolition of tax relief on insurance premiums did not for long damage the
British propensity to buy endowments. Mortgage tax relief has seriously
distorted the housing market, though its reconstruction in recent times has
suffered the most unfortunate timing. The benefits of house ownership should
not be skewed by considerations of tax: indeed the basic rate, whatever it was,
could be lowered if this practice could ever be abolished.
As for encouraging savings there are many devices apart from tax relief that
could be utilised. The difficulty has to be faced in all of these areas -
income tax is seen as almost as much a social agent of redistribution as much
as a source of revenue (hence our desire to keep some onerous taxes which raise
little revenue). The two aims can run in tandem but the main aim is to raise
money fairly, in order to spend it wisely. That must mean reform. Too many poor
people pay income tax (sometimes at astonishing rates) and everyone's liability
is complicated by a clutch of exceptions and special provisions.
</TEXT>
