<HEADLINE>Effects of postal dispute Serious setback for business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224955</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOST of us will suffer inconvenience if the postal dispute remains intractable
but for Scottish business the effects will be serious and long-lasting. For
this reason, if for no other, the heads of all those involved should be
collectively banged together. If that implies that both parties to the argument
appear culpable it is clear that this is the growing perception. The role of
the postal workers in the unofficial industrial action is the most obvious
element and it cannot be emphasised sufficiently how wrong they are. The law
affecting industry and the relations between management and workers is not the
happiest piece of legislation ever framed. Although nobody wishes to return to
the days of free-for-all strike action when workers walked from their jobs at
the slightest provocation, and sometimes with no provocation at all, the
current law is not equitable and badly needs to be reviewed.
Disputes become heated because of the difficulty of achieving legal industrial
action and penalties against even innocent unions are grossly punitive.
Nevertheless, it is the law and as such should be respected and followed until
it is changed, not least because of the legal and financial repercussions.
Unofficial action will not advance the cause of the postal workers one whit,
and this has been made abundantly clear to them by their union which is
justifiably worried about what will happen if it cannot demonstrate its
innocence in all that has taken place. The actions of Royal Mail management in
the dispute appear equally open to criticism. The Scottish Chambers of Commerce
said yesterday that what has happened is a sad reflection on modern management
and employee relationships; the comments of the Scottish Chambers go straight
to the heart of the problem. In preparation for privatisation the management of
the Royal Mail invested heavily in new technology with the aim of cost cutting.
This was combined with a management style which demonstrated implacable
determination to get its own way, with obvious effects on the level of stress
and uncertainty imposed on the people in the organisation. Royal Mail workers
are not noted for militancy but unofficial stoppages doubled in the past two
years, apparently as a direct result of the new style of management. Much of
what the Royal Mail leadership says can be excused, of course, on the grounds
of efficiency. It may be more efficient to move the bulk of postal deliveries
to the morning, and management may be utterly truthful when it says that there
is no intention to remove the noon post. But at what level will the noon post
run, and if it is reduced, what are the implications for this in terms of
employment, be it full or part-time?
It is becoming clear that over-powerful management in British industry is
beginning to result in diminishing returns. Management and workers in the Royal
Mail, faced with growing competition, must work together or they will not work
at all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Electrification of route</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224956</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTRAIL'S efforts to rent a few more nearly new diesel trains (apparently
surplus to South of England's needs) may offer a marginal improvement to the
woefully inadequate Sprinter railcars whose 50-minute Glasgow-Edinburgh
schedules are now seven minutes slower than achieved in 1975.
But why the silence and lack of push for early electrification of Scotland's
most intensively used Capital Cities route, which carries nearly eight million
passengers per annum?
Electrification and some modest upgrading of our country's finest engineered
route could achieve the crucial 30-35 minute station-to-station journey time
necessary if rail is to become more attractive relative to ongoing motorway
improvements, eg, nearly #300m for recent/proposed M77, M8, M74 extensions.
With a pathetic 23% of our rail network improved by electrification, Scotland
now ranks almost bottom of a 20-nation European league table - a curiosity
corner out of step with the worldwide railway renaissance taking place around
us.
ScotRail and Railtrack must forcefully remind this Government over the justice
and more enduring benefits of electrifying the Glasgow-Edinburgh line,
deserving of more than just another quick-fix with improved diesel trains.
K A Sutherland,
Research Officer,
Railway Development
Society (Scotland),
53 Cochrane Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour and Nolan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COUNCILLOR Margaret Murray is right when she says the Labour Party campaigned
vigorously to have the Parliamentary Register of Members' Interests improved.
She is wrong when she asserts that Labour is silent on having principles
applied to local government.
Last year the Prime Minister announced the setting up of the Nolan Inquiry into
standards in public life and its terms of reference. These terms of reference
included ``elected members and senior officers of local authorities'' and
``members and senior officers of all non-departmental public bodies'' (Hansard
October 25, column 758). The Parliamentary Labour Party, far from being silent,
supported the setting up of the Nolan Inquiry, supported in full its terms of
reference, supported the total application of its recommendations in respect of
Members of Parliament, and succeeded in persuading the Commons, despite the
Prime Minister's opposition, to adopt full disclosure on earnings from
consultancies. Councillor Murray should inform herself of the facts before
rushing into print.
Councillor Catherine
Craigie,
Labour Group Leader,
Cumbernauld &amp; Kilsyth   District Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000123</DOCID>
