<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foolhardy Scargill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224959</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO of your correspondents describe Arthur Scargill as courageous.
Many readers will say that a more appropriate description would be foolhardy.
Arthur Scargill succeeded Joe Gormley as general secretary of the NUM whose
wise leadership greatly strengthened the unions. I often wondered at Joe
Gormley refraining from publicly criticising his successor. He must have been
sorely tempted to do so.
What a contrast between his brilliant and constructive leadership and Arthur
Scargill's performance, so tragic for the coal-mining industry.
He should gracefully retire from the trade union and Labour Party scene - the
best thing he could do for the cause of socialism.
Bill Hattan,
Tanera,
Strachur.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lottery and the law</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR two articles give a good review of all the problems raised by the lottery
(November 14).
I was particularly struck by your statement that Camelot's director of
operations admitted that there was little that Camelot could do to enforce the
ban on sales to children under 16.
Surely the logic of this would then require that they cease operating the
lottery if they cannot keep it within the law, something which they openly
admit.
Prof John F Woodward,
Airliewood,
15a Drumbeg Loan,
Killearn.
</TEXT>
