<DOCNO>GH951124-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lesson learned</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224961</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN Royal Infirmary had to postpone a heart operation for a few days
because of an unexpected emergency demand for intensive care beds.
Was the use of the word ``cancelled'' in The Herald headline the usual attempt
to sustain the myth that the NHS is in crisis, or does the journalist not know
the correct meaning of the word?
I suggest that he/she be given the option of having his/her next pay cheque
postponed for a few days or having it cancelled. I am sure he will get the
message.
J A Duncan,
Woodbine Cottage,
Torrisdale,
Campbeltown.
</TEXT>
