<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Encore!</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224962</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE experienced a tremendous feeling of euphoria and have been the recipient
of many telephone calls offering congratulations on a wonderful achievement.
What did I do? Win the Nobel Prize, climb Mount Everest backwards, or discover
a cure for baldness?
No, I really surpassed myself. I had my letter published in The Herald.
I would like to assure fellow readers and potential letter writers that you do
not need to be a friend of the Editor in order to get your epistle published.
Robert Johnstone,
7 Bankview Drive,
Kirkintilloch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Double standard</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224963</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN William Russell's article on the four-letter word does he not contradict
himself? (November 15).
Saying it is for parents to tell children such language is not acceptable in
their home, then condoning the same language on television which is also in
their home, seems a double standard.
As my old English teacher used to point out swearing was not strong language
but proof that your command of the language was so bad you did not know the
correct words to use.
Tom Affleck,
3 Beechwood Crescent,
Lesmahagow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Waiting in the rain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224964</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GOOD example to illustrate Lawrence Kemp's point that rail fragmentation is
bad for the customer occurred recently at Larbert (November 17).
Glasgow to Inverness passengers were denied access to their onward train for 10
minutes after their connection had been terminated due to flooding.
Passengers waited on the platform in the pouring rain while permission was
sought from three control centres for the doors to be opened to let them on
board.
Apparently, Railtrack had omitted to tell InterCity East Coast that there were
problems on the tracks and ScotRail had not advised that passengers had been
detrained short of their normal transfer point of Stirling.
You also report that Railtrack will now depend on road cranes to cover
derailments in future. Do they not realise that many Scottish rail routes run
through very boggy terrain? How would they get a road crane to the middle of
Rannoch Moor?
R J Ardern,
26a Southside Road,
Inverness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rail link problem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224965</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE solution to the problems of traffic-island airport could be resolved quite
simply (November 14).
Are ScotRail/Railtrack so removed from the actual facts that they are unaware
of the present existence of a disused single track line? This line branches
from the main Glasgow to Paisley line at Gallowhill and extends to the grounds
of the old Babcock works.
The route passes under the main Paisley/Renfrew road and bridges over Wright
Street in Renfrew. It surely would not be beyond engineers' ingenuity to
develop a route to the airport.
Donald Fraser,
4 Wallace Road,
Renfrew.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Missing the train</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224966</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE railway people at Glasgow Central are clever.
The trains are going out on time - hooray! - by the platform clocks.
But they are ensuring that travellers miss trains - by keeping the platform
clocks 25 seconds fast and the concourse display six seconds slow. And, as the
concourse display shows only minutes, it can be up to 1!s minutes behind the
platforms.
Stuart Cresswell,
28 Monreith Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Right-wing views</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224967</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH political history is obviously not one of Ian Doyle's stronger points
(November 16). A little research on the topic would have helped him to discover
that by 1979 Brian Wilson had long outgrown ``shortpants''.
During that year he was old enough to enjoy his propensity for sharing
political platforms with right-wing Tories in his crusade against Scottish
devolution.
Indeed, if Ian Doyle were to dig a little deeper he would also learn that his
own recent statements on the subject of Labour's current plans for a devolved
assembly were but a mild whimper compared to some of the stuff which emanated
from Brian Wilson's lips back in 1979.
Time does change some things and Brian Wilson, MP, now claims to support the
creation of a devolved assembly. Unfortunately, however, his support for Tony
Blair would indicate that he has still not lost his old admiration for some
right-wing Tories.
J Finlayson,
26 King Street,
Newport-on-Tay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
