<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots who never returned</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224969</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK WEBSTER'S article, Scots who made America dream, triggered memories of a
period I spent in Canada in the early 1970s (November 18).
I worked in a psycho-geriatric hospital in a place called Terrace, 1000 miles
north of Vancouver. Residents, elderly men from all over the world, with a fair
proportion from Scotland, had few local visitors, and no family contact.
Often they'd left their homeland when young, travelled extensively, had not
retained familial links, and eventually due to poor mental functioning were no
longer able to do so. Few had local connections to the town of Terrace, and
little of their history was known.
One resident, Jimmy McDonald, originally from Glasgow, was oblivious to those
around him, but constantly muttered, ``Celtic two, Rangers nil''. This was
generally ignored by residents, but on July 12 when everyone was treated to a
drink, arguments would ensue.
On one occasion quick action by staff prevented Jimmy from being hit over the
head by a walking stick by an irate English inmate.
Another Scotsmen was convinced that tap water was poisoned, so he would open a
valve from waterpipes along the road and drink his supply before water entered
the hospital system.
A well-spoken gentleman, a Jack Mackay from Stornoway, during a period of
lucidity gave me relatives' address in that town, asking me to get in touch
with them. He'd left when he was 15 years' old and never returned.
My inquiries drew a blank, but unfortunately, or perhaps fortunately, Mr
Mackay's dementia deteriorated so he did not ask the outcome.
On visiting the remote small town of Hyder, on the Alaskan border, I came
across a cemetery where Scots names on gravestones were evident, but few
details given.
I'm sure that many at home in Scotland have wondered about the fate of those
who left never to return nor maintain contact.
Angela Gillies,
8 Cedar Road,
Cumbernauld.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Discourteous</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224970</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ with great sadness Victoria Freeman's report on facial disfigurement
(November 16). The sadness I felt was not for Susan Duncan - who has a facial
disfigurement as a result of having had a tumour removed from her face - but
for the writer of this article. Only once did she mention Susan's Christian
name and referred to her continually as Duncan. What happened to Miss Duncan,
Ms Duncan, or Susan?
This might be the norm when reporting on crimes but on such a delicate topic
this brave and courageous lady deserved a little more respect.
Naida Dodgson,
21 Wallace Avenue,
Bishopton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cairngorm funicular</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224971</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR article, EU deadline threat to ski railway plans (November 18), presents
the Cairngorm Chairlift Company's plans for a funicular railway up Cairn Gorm
as a `once only' chance to gain European funding for tourism development in the
Highlands and Islands.
This is misleading. What the developers are worried about is that they need so
much EU money to make this scheme viable that, unless they get in quickly,
Objective 1 tourism money will be used on other projects.
It would be much better if a number of smaller, more sustainable, projects
could be developed which spread both economic benefits and environmental
pressures more evenly throughout the Highlands and Islands. Everyone knows that
the Cairngorms are one of Scotland's most precious natural assets. Great care
and caution are needed in considering their future.
David Minns,
Head of Public Affairs,
Scotland,
The Royal Society For The  Protection Of Birds,
17 Regent Terrace,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>First step on road to Olympics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MIKE HAGGERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224972</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CURLING
SCOTLAND'S top curlers gather in Kilmarnock today for the first qualifying
steps towards the Winter Olympics, while Foresthills, in Aberfoyle, will host
one of the most important club level events on the calendar with the Calor Gas
Province championships being staged there.
Six Scottish teams, in both men's and women's divisions, will go on to the ice
at Kilmarnock along with representatives from both the English and Welsh
Curling Associations. By the end of the weekend's round-robin play, the eight
teams currently in the Olympic preparation squads will be whittled down to six.
The Scottish men's teams involved include those skipped by Gordon Muirhead,
current Scottish champion and world silver medallist; Hammy McMillan, reigning
European champion; and Tom Brewster, the current world junior champion. The top
women's skips include Kirsty Hay, Jackie Lockhart, and Claire Milne.
The 1998 Winter games in Nagano, Japan, is the first time that curling will be
a full Olympic sport and this momentous move has helped create the British
Curling Association to supervise British team selection.
Earlier this year, the selection procedures being proposed by the BCA were a
major topic of disquiet at the annual meeting of The Curlers Association, a
players' organisation that includes many of the top internationalists, but
since then, relative peace has broken out with both sides glad to agree that
all selection action will take place on the ice.
MIKE HAGGERTY
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Keep your finger on the pulses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>VICTORIA FREEDMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224973</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As the debate grows over mad cow disease and the dangers of chewing the fat,
Victoria Freedman weighs up the arguments for vegetarianism
Being vegetarian doesn't necessarily mean they will be eating healthily
THE recent investigation into the death of a farmer from an incurable brain
disorder has refuelled debate over whether Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the human
equivalent of BSE - bovine spongiform encephalo-pathy, also known as mad cow
disease - is proving to be a bigger threat than has been officially admitted.
It could be that the disease can be transmitted to humans handling cattle feed
containing infected sheep offal - or simply through eating the meat.
No more appealing is poultry where chickens or turkeys have been artificially
fattened, the birds unable to support their own weight.
Perhaps, the argument runs, we had better become vegetarians - but recently it
emerged that some vegetarian meals, including Linda McCartney's Beefless
Burgers, contain an excessive amount of fat, almost twice that stated on the
packet. And doesn't cheese have a higher fat content than meat?
The question is whether vegetarianism is as healthy as we have been led to
believe. If consumers are not concerned, they might certainly feel confused,
unsure of which diet to follow and which of the organisations representing meat
eaters and vegetarians is to be believed.
On BSE, Alistair Donaldson, general manager for Scotland of the Meat and
Livestock Commission, says: ``The position is clear cut. It's an animal health
problem. There is absolutely no scientific evidence of linkage between BSE and
CJD.''
That is so, there is no definitive evidence. Yet there is undeniably reason for
confusion since microbiologist Professor Richard Lacey believes it is more than
99% certain that mad cow disease has spread to humans. ``Whatever the
powers-that-be claim, CJD and BSE are one and the same,'' he says.
Retired neuropathologist Sir Bernard Tomlinson says he had changed his mind and
was now ``far from certain'' that the disease could not be transmitted.
The nutritional value of meat far outweighs any remote risk of CJD, but many
people give up meat for ethical rather than health reasons. Methods of rearing
pigs, and production practices in general, anger many vegetarians.
``The idea that sows and litters running outdoors are more welfare-friendly is
absurd,'' says Alistair Donaldson. ``There are weather problems, pests such as
foxes, and contamination by seagulls which are carriers of a whole heap of
diseases.''
He points out that the level of prosecutions for abuse against domestic pets
far exceeds that of farm animals and that production practices are
independently monitored.
Similarly, there is a range of legislation and policing regarding slaughtering.
The use of hormones has been banned since 1988 and the use of antibiotics, for
health reasons, is also governed by regulations.
Donaldson adds: ``As for the belief that animals are fed or bred unnaturally -
I think that relates to the concept of genetic engineering and I'm sure the
industry will look at ways to harness it to the advantage of production but not
the abuse of animals.
``We have to dispel the image of an industry that is mischievous and has ill
intent, run by monsters out to do nothing but make money. What is produced has
to be produced competitively, but farmers are certainly not making fat
profits.''
Around 97% of the population are meat eaters, he claims, and if beef
consumption has been reduced it is due to agricultural-support policies which
have affected supplies. ``If it's not there, you can't eat it.''
If it is there, John Carlisle will certainly eat it. ``I don't feel guilty that
animals are bred to be eaten. I look at sheep in fields when I'm driving but I
don't think of the lamb on my plate,'' says the 34-year-old father of two young
children.
``I wish humans didn't try to change nature for the sake of producing bigger
animals more quickly, but nothing would persuade me to give up meat. I believe
my body needs it. It gives me energy.''
Carlisle would accept any decision by his children to become vegetarian but
presently encourages them to eat as he does, and that includes meat surrounded
by fat.
``Unless I have evidence that it alone definitely produces heart disease then I
will continue to eat it,'' he says. ``I've always been very healthy and never
overweight.''
But then so has Joy Hamilton, aged 78, from Edinburgh who has been a vegetarian
for 40 years - a perfect advert for the claim that vegetarians suffer 30% less
heart disease and a 40% reduced risk of cancer.
As a child she disliked the idea of ``eating dead flesh'' and became a complete
vegetarian when pregnant.
Hamilton, who has never needed to take a vitamin pill in her life, says:  ``It
isn't difficult to stay healthy providing you're replacing the protein in meat
and balancing proteins in meals such as beans on toast.''
A typical meal for her might be home-made vegetable soup with lentils and bread
followed by fresh fruit. ``You do have to spend more time cooking to eat
healthily,'' she concedes.
Both her children were boarders at the school she attended, St Christopher's in
Letchworth, a progressive co-ed and completely vegetarian.
``Funnily enough they both eat meat now - my son even married a girl whose
father was a butcher - but my grandchildren are vegetarian,'' says Hamilton.
``It's the thing now for young people. What worries me is the young girls who
become vegetarian thinking it is slimming or because pop stars do it - but
they're living on junk food.''
Julie Tomlinson, of the South East Scotland Vegetarian Society, agrees that not
all vegetarians eat sensibly. ``People become vegetarian for different reasons.
Some, like my sister, gave up red meat because they were shocked by how much
food we imported from Third World countries to feed our animals - such as
peanuts from Ethiopia at the height of the famine there. Or they feel that land
should be put to other uses. Some become vegetarian for economic reasons. But
it doesn't necessarily mean they will be eating healthily.''
Indeed, according to a report by the Food Commission, an independent consumer
association, several manufacturers of ready-made vegetarian meals use a kind of
vegetable fat at least as dangerous as saturated fat.
``We also thought manufacturers were cashing in on the growing interest in
vegetarianism,'' says Sue Dibbs, commission co-director. ``We were quite
surprised by how expensive many of the ready-made meals were - especially when
we looked at the ingredients, which were not terribly expensive.''
Eman Nakshabendi, senior dietician at Glasgow's Royal Maternity Hospital,
believes that the advice given to pregnant women should apply to the whole
family.
They divide food into groups and believe the main part of the diet should come
from the bread, pasta and rice group, accompanied by fresh fruit and
vegetables, at least three times a day.
Food that should be eaten moderately includes meat, chicken, fish, eggs and
dairy products. Food to be limited are those with sugar and hidden fat - such
as pies, chocolate and processed items.
As it is harder to absorb iron from vegetables than from meat, pregnant women,
children and teenagers who are vegetarian are advised to increase the Vitamin C
content in their diet by eating more food and raw vegetables, and to drink a
pint of milk a day.
``It's not a question of good and bad food but good and bad habits,'' she says.
``For example we would advise people to grill their burgers instead of frying
them, to cut down on fat. We would never say you should or shouldn't eat meat,
both can be healthy, in the same way we wouldn't say don't eat chocolate. After
all, eating is also something that should be enjoyed.''
</TEXT>
