<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shares tumble after Trade Secretary  steps into #4700m electric+ ity takeovers Power bids referred to monopolies commission</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Chris Stone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224974</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ELECTRICITY share prices tumbled yesterday after President of the Board of
Trade Ian Lang announced he was referring PowerGen's #1900m bid for Midlands
Electricity and National Power's #2800m offer for Southern Electric to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Midlands Electricity fell 59p to 918p and Southern Electric by 62p to 913p. The
bids automatically lapse on referral.
Mr Lang said he had decided to refer the PowerGen and National Power bids to
the MMC because he considered that each raised competition concerns in the
generation and supply of electricity.
``In general, I do not believe that vertical integration is inherently
objectionable whether in the electricity industry or elsewhere,'' he added.
``However, in these two cases, the structural change proposed could have an
effect on the development of competition in the industry.''
Both bids had virtually been triggered by the Government's decision on the
advice of the Office of Fair Trading not to refer Scottish Power's hostile bid
for Manweb to the MMC. Mr Lang at the time said that the industry regulator
could make licence changes to satisfy concerns raised by vertical integration.
Undertakings signed by ScottishPower included agreeing not to sign contracts to
supply Manweb with electricity and to make clear to customers which company
they were dealing with, and also that Manweb sold its stake in National Grid
when it is floated.
At the time there had been strong speculation that the ScottishPower bid, the
first by a power generator for a distributor, was most likely to be put before
the MMC. Professor Stephen Littlechild, the industry regulator had wanted the
bid referred.
Yesterday's referral of the two bids - the MMC is required to report on its
findings by March 22 - was followed by a statement from National Power that it
was concerned whether as a result of the competition issues in relation to
generation and supply to which the Secretary of State's announcement referred,
its proposed sale of 4000 megawatts of power plants, which it was close to
securing, could be completed as planned.
The industry regulator had threatened both National Power and PowerGen with a
monopolies inquiry unless they disposed of a substantial amount of their
generating capacity.
The MMC investigation now means that the whole situation will be looked at
afresh. National Power had expected to complete the plant sale by March 31
having selected a buyer by the end of December as agreed with the regulator.
Representatives of electricity consumers have been demanding a monopoly enquiry
from the time the bids were made some two months ago though it was felt that
the Government was far less concerned, particularly given that ScottishPower
had been allowed to go ahead with its bid for Manweb, albeit after making the
aforementioned guarantees.
The Government all along has insisted that it was not against vertical
integration in principle and the two generating companies had been confident,
at least in the earlier stages, that the bids would be waved through.
While there are differences between the ScottishPower Manweb situation -
vertical integration was already in play in Scotland - and other issues could
be decided by agreement with the authorities, as proved to be the case, it is
difficult to see why Mr Lang has decided to act tough now.
Unless he feels that geographically and in other respects, it would not be
enough to just seek assurances. Either that or he is proving that the
electricity industry is not a free for all despite what has gone on before.
</TEXT>
