<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lyonnaise in offer for Northumbrian</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224975</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LYONNAISE des Eaux duly launched its expected bid for Northumbrian Water
yesterday and the agreed deal values the group at #823m.
Shareholders will receive 1179p cash per share, including a special 14p net
dividend. They will also be paid the interim dividend of 11p already declared.
There is a loan note alernative.
Northumbrian said the price was ``four to five times ahead of any other in the
sector and at a 40% premium to the rest of the sector, we believe we achieved a
significantly better price for shareholders by accepting Lyonnaise's offer''.
The French water group said it would be creating a strong North-east
England-based group which should create ``significant employment and investment
opportunities in the region''. It promised that there would be no compulsory
redundancies.
Northumbrian claims to be one of the best water groups in Britain. It says it
has the lowest levels of leakage and has made the greatest efficiency gains
during the last 18 months.
The group is also well known for owning the Kielder Reservoir, which is the
largest man-made lake in Europe. Lyonnaise already owns the adjacent company,
North East Water, which has 1,400,000 customers, and aims to make savings by
combining the two operations.
``Northumbrian and our local water company, North East Water, already work
together in a number of areas and we strongly believe that merging our UK water
interests with Northumbrian will strengthen both businesses,'' said Jerome
Monod, chairman of Lyonnaise.
The French utility has been interested in Northumbrian for some time and was
finally given the go-ahead to bid by the Government earlier this month, so long
as prices were cut by 15% over the next six years.
``We believe that the terms agreed for the acquisition of Northumbrian by
Lyonnaise fully reflect the value and unique qualities of our company,'' said
chairman Sir Frederick Holliday.
Northumbrian deals with all the sewerage waste from the Scottish Border to
Teesside, serving 2,600,000 customers. It also provides drinking water to
1,200,000 customers.
Lyonnaise also owns the smaller Essex and Suffolk water companies and these
will be joined together in the new company called Northumbrian Water Group.
``We will retain the Northumbrian Water name and the new group will build on
the considerable strengths of the two companies to provide levels of customer
service which are unmatched in the rest of the country,'' said a Lyonnaise
spokesman.
n NORTH West Water, the British water company in the process of buying
neighbouring electricity distributor Norweb, on Thursday announced a 22% rise
in pre-tax profits in the first half to September 30.
NWW posted profits of #167m compared with #136.8m in the first half last year.
It raised its interim dividend 11% to 9.27p per share, having already announced
and paid a special 3.8p per share special dividend funded by efficiency gains.
Chairman Brian Staples warned that NWW intended to sue The Times newspaper over
a report alleging the company had supplied water contaminated with sewage to
700,000 cutomers, unless the paper retracts the story and apologises.
NWW, which will change its name to United Utilities from January 1, said the
period ahead will be demanding as it tries to deliver and even exceed the
benefits it said would derive from the Norweb acquisition.
``Our early examination of the business has confirmed the robustness of our
assumptions and nothing has fallen short of our expectations,'' Mr Staples said.
Following controversy over supply restrictions during last summer's drought,
NWW said these were no longer ``palatable'' to customers and it pledged to
greatly reduce the likelihood of water cuts.
</TEXT>
