<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Watt becomes 3i's Scottish director</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG Economics Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224976</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE director of investment capital group 3i's Glasgow office since 1990, Willie
Watt, is to become director in charge of the entire Scottish operation on
December 1.
This newly-created role gives Mr Watt, 36, overall charge of the three Scottish
offices in Glasgow, Edinburgh, and Aberdeen, a seat on the group's six-strong
British management board and UK-wide responsibility for independent,
family-managed businesses in 3i's portfolio. He will continue to be based in
Glasgow.
Mr Watt says his new role will enable 3i in Scotland to act as a unified
business - reflecting the trend among advisers and competitors - while
maintaining local decision making and service across the three regional
offices. ``All three offices will remain fully resourced to handle the whole
spectrum of investments from start-ups to large MBOs,'' he said.
Two areas where the more unified approach will be quickly felt are emerging
technologies, capable of rapid growth, where a Scotland-wide expertise will be
established, and the Government's private finance initiative, where 3i is keen
to help plug the shortage of equity but the average deal size is likely to be
significant.
Mr Watt, who joined 3i from Aberdeen University in 1984, says 3i Scotland is
anxious to segment its own marketplace before competitors do the job for it.
Thirty years ago, its predecessor ICFC had 100% of its market. Now that market
share - investments in 286 Scottish companies valued at #242m - is between 50%
and 60%.
</TEXT>
