<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glenmorangie toasts 32% increase in profits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224977</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLENMORANGIE malt distiller Macdonald Martin is seeing the first fruits of its
reorganisation programme, which has helped boost first half operating profits
by 32% to #4.12m.
This was achieved on turnover up 10% at #18.1m, with the impetus coming from
rising volumes as price increases prove difficult to achieve.
Malt accounted for just over 40% of turnover with Glenmorangie volumes up 4%
and undisclosed profitability 10% greater.
The US, German, Italian, and Dutch markets were outperformers while Japan was
dull. French markets continue to be uncertain.
At home, Glenmorangie - volume up 3% - remains market leader in both Scotland
and the UK with a 14% share, although it is being pressed hard by the United
Distillers Classic Six selection.
The blends saw good performances from the Martins 20-Year-Old in Portugal and
from Bailie Nicol Jarvie, which is at the top of the premium blends and priced
about #1 higher than Highland's Famous Grouse.
The standard blends had a tough time due to the continuing polarisation of the
market between the own labels and the premium end. In export markets, there was
a downturn in volume due to the hiatus caused by a change in distributor in the
United States.
However, this is not a particularly significant part of the overall business in
terms of profitability.
Sales of new fillings amounted to perhaps #1.5m but profitability is coming
under pressure because of rising malted barley costs. But the likely price
recovery looks fairly minimal at just 1p on a 150p listed price per litre.
Macdonald Martin is spending heavily on product promotion which is taking some
of the cream from profits in the short term. It is also looking ever harder
into Asia where Highland Queen is a market leader in the Indian bottled
scotches although that led to a #125,000 half time loss as the market is
developed. And there are expectations that a deal should be completed soon in
China.
Nearer home, the #11m investment in the recently acquired Broxburn plant will
add 50 people to the current 200 strong payroll. The development will bring
about substantial savings with some #500,000 annually from bringing all group
stocks into the one complex while offering superior bottling facilities once
the capital programme is completed.
The sale of the Commercial Street premises in Leith to Forth Ports brought in
#1.9m of which there was a net #499,000 gain after allowing for repairs to
Broxburn.
That surplus helped boost pre-tax profits by 52% to #4.02m with last year's
figure being depressed by #440,000 of exceptional reorganisation charges.
Chairman Geoffrey Maddrell is expecting real profit growth in the second half,
albeit at a slower rate than in the first six months.
Analysts are pencilling in a full year total raised from #5.71m to about #6.6m.
That points to the A shares at 645p trading at around 19 times likely earnings.
The interim dividend has been raised 10% to 275p with 12p probable for the year
for a 2.3% yield.
</TEXT>
