<DOCNO>GH951124-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Norman MacCaig 85th Birthday Celebration, Assembly Rooms, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lesley Duncan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224978</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was billed as a party for the doyen of Scottish poets. And Norman MacCaig
was there - a tall rather frail figure now, but still with that imperious head.
What a gift of nature not only to be, but so completely look, the poet! A
sell-out audience of more than 500 greeted him like a pop star in the foyer.
He stayed the silent centre of attention. Others read from his works. They gave
a fair taste of his laconic style and deadly wit, from No Choice (``I think
about you/in as many ways as rain comes'') to his skewering of the Street
Preacher (``He howls outside my window. He howls about God'').
But the evening turned out to be rather a giant cabaret by fellow Scottish
poets. The night-club ambience was helped by the audience's sitting at tables
rather than in pious ranks. And if the corner bar kept up a ground base of
clinking through the proceedings, it was perhaps more disconcerting than
disrespectful to the man who penned the Ballade of Good Whisky.
Joy Hendry of Chapman and Dolina Maclennan commred. Their shepherd's crook to
haul off longwinded contributors was not needed. Douglas Dunn acted as
warmer-up with a poem about school dinners. Brian McCabe pursued darker themes
in his funny food poems.
Sorley MacLean, looking rather fierce, rendered two poems uncompromisingly in
Gaelic. Liz Lochhead was pawky about pawkies and much else. Adam McNaughtan
sang his comic reprise of Hamlet. In an equally sonorous voice, Hamish
Henderson provoked the audience's deepest response with his Free Mandela
rallying cry to a Spanish Civil War tune.
The Boys of the Lough and piper Allan MacDonald made music classily.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coulthard offers advice on how to go faster still Formula 1appealsto McRae</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224979</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN though it was the morning after the night before, world rally champion
Colin McRae had dried out enough brain cells to think reasonably and look to
the future by appealing for his sport to be given the recognition it deserves
and also suggesting Formula One might be his next challenge.
It is thought moves in that direction might already have been made on behalf of
the 27-year-old Scot, and if he should feel now that having become the first
Briton and the youngest ever winner of the world rally championship he needs a
greater adrenalin rush he won't have far to look for assistance. One of his
neighbours in Monaco is fellow-Scot David Coulthard, and he said yesterday he
would be more than happy to offer any assistance and advice.
Coulthard, who has just finished his first full F1 season and has left Williams
for McLaren, believes McRae could make the transition if he so desires. ``I
would welcome Colin into F1 and although you can't really compare our cars with
rally cars, success depends a great deal on confidence and experience and Colin
has both qualities,'' Coulthard said.
``His achievement in becoming world champion is absolutely brilliant. It is
excellent and you have to say he is up there with Michael Schumacher. Michael
currently is the guy who does it best in F1, but Colin is the best in rallying.
``As far as I am concerned a world champion is a world champion and I'm sure we
will be meeting when Colin gets back here to Monaco. He lives just across the
harbour, which makes us virtually neighbours, so no doubt we'll be going down
to the pub for a celebration, even if it is an English pub.''
McRae made it clear yesterday, the day after his Network Q RAC Rally triumph,
that he would relish the opportunity to drive a F1 car, and pointed out: ``I
like fast cars and the F1 car is probably the fastest you can get. I would love
to try one.''
Coulthard, who had a traumatic season, was enjoying his last few days ``just
chilling out'' before beginning testing work with McLaren-Mercedes next week
and he added that it should not be too difficult for McRae to secure a test
drive. ``If there was any way I could help him I would and I have to say it is
probably easier for a driver of a two-seater car to switch to a single than the
other way around,'' said Coulthard, who finished third in the F1 drivers'
championship behind Schumacher and Damon Hill.
``If someone can drive a car which always seems to be out of control he would
be able to handle one which, while quicker, is much more controlled,''
Coulthard added. ``I drove an Escort Cosworth rally car recently, but it felt
unnatural the way it slithered around corners.
``My environment is much more controlled, but also much faster. Everything
happens quicker in F1 but you always feel you have more control of the car even
if it can get up to a speed of around 210mph at a circuit like Hockenheim.''
McRae insists no formal moves have been made regarding a switch of cars and
circuits, but the challenge has great appeal. ``I wouldn't mind giving it a
try,'' he said, ``but it may never happen.''
McRae, who divides his time between homes in Monaco, Switzerland, and Lanark,
then asked that rallying be given the coverage he believes it merits,
stressing: ``Rallying is on a par with F1, but we don't get the same coverage
as grands prix although we are getting closer and closer.
``However, I hope my victory will raise the status of rallying because a sport
tends to be given more attention in a country which has the world champion.''
His #3000 prize for defending his RAC crown - less #1075 in fines for speeding
on the ``recce'' of the course - is loose change compared with the several
million pounds Schumacher picked up in bonuses for winning the F1 title.
McRae's salary is unlikely ever to match that of the German's reported
#15m-a-year deal with Ferrari. However, McRae's own contract negotiations are
sure to be strengthened by his lofty new status.
McRae-mania was quickly apparent at Chester on Wednesday when several thousand
people - the rally was watched by more than two million - packed the racecourse
to hail the hero after his victory over Carlos Sainz, his team-mate and rival.
There was friction between the two Subaru drivers after the Scot was ordered to
let the Spaniard win on the last day of the Catalonian rally - the team wanted
both their drivers to go into the RAC level on points to secure the
manufacturers' prize - but yesterday McRae said the bad feeling had subsided.
He could afford to be magnanimous, but McRae's willingness to forget was a
further measure of his maturity as a sportsman, who seems destined to collect
more championships if he decides to remain in rallying.
``Colin has proved that not only does he have the talent, but also that he can
control it,'' said his co-driver, Derek Ringer. ``At times on the rally he
raised his level to a point which defied definition. He has been so committed
yet so relaxed. He found his own pace.''
Where that pace, the astounding speed at which he can drive a car around dirt
and tarmac, will take him now remains to be seen. He says he can win the rally
title again, but F1 is the ultimate in speed and another Scot in that business
would do the image of this nation no harm at all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Babcock boosts profits with sale to Mitsui</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224980</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACTFILE
Interims  1995       1994
Pre-tax profit #19.2m      #2.8m
Turnover #393.7m     #348.9m
EPS  10.77p       0.85p
Dividend 1.25p       nil
BABCOCK International, which is on its way to becoming the new owner of Rosyth
naval dockyard, has boosted its profits at the half-way stage with the sale of
its energy division to Mitsui of Japan.
Pre-tax profits for the six months to September 30 rocketed seven-fold to
#19.2m as a result of the sale.
This gave the group sufficient confidence to pay an interim dividend of 1.25p,
its first half-year payout since 1992.
However, the #26m net gain from the sale of a 75% stake in Babcock Energy to
Mitsui was partially offset by a #9m charge for cutting back loss-making
operations in Germany.
The group's manufacture of cement handling equipment in Germany has been hit by
the strong mark and about 200 local employees are being laid off.
Stripping out exceptional items, operational profits fell to #2.2m from #2.8m,
leading Babcock shares to fall 12p to 149p.
Nevertheless, chairman John Parker was confident that Babcock had turned the
corner and had set itself on course for a more profitable future.
``Following the sale of Energy, group management is now in a position to
concentrate fully on the strategic development of other core businesses and we
now have significant financial resources to fund our plans,'' he said.
Much of Babcock's #33m of cash balances are likely to be invested in purchasing
the dockyard at Rosyth, which is expected to fetch #20m to #25m.
Babcock already manages the Rosyth yard, which is currently engaged in the
refit of two nuclear submarines and could be in line for further submarine
contracts in view of safety problems at its rival Devonport near Plymouth.
Babcock has been negotiating to buy the Rosyth dockyard for a year, but these
talks have been held up by the problems at Devonport, which is also up for
privatisation. Nevertheless, Babcock hopes to complete the purchase by March.
The company is also part of the Rosyth 2000 consortium, which has been declared
preferred bidder for privatisation of adjacent port facilities at Rosyth which
have just been vacated by the Royal Navy.
Babcock has a 25% stake in Rosyth 2000, alongside Forth Ports, ScottishPower,
and the Bank of Scotland.
Negotiations for the purchase of the 355-acre site, which is due to be
converted into a commercial port and industrial site, should also be completed
in March. The price tag is thought to be around #20m.
Further down the line, Babcock also has its eyes on the future privatisation of
Portsmouth dockyard.
Following the sale of its energy division, which includes factories making
power station equipment at Dumbarton and Renfrew, Babcock is concentrating on
the management of facilities such as Rosyth and the manufacture of equipment
for handling bulk materials ranging from timber to grain and cement, and the
repair and maintenance of railway rolling stock.
It has formed a joint venture with Siemens called Railcare, which last June
bought the Springburn railway workshops in Glasgow and a similar facility at
Wolverton near Milton Keynes.
Despite limp reaction to the company's interim results, Broker Tilney is
maintaining its forecast for full-year pre-tax profits of around #19.5m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Former minister for sport Gamble on the rising stars</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224981</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE highly successful Lottery has passed its first anniversary. It brings two
thoughts immediately to mind. First, that a personal win is long overdue;
second, to distribute the Lottery money in our own way, to our own good causes.
As far as sport is concerned, the arrangements were set by Parliament. Scotland
receives around nine per cent of the Lottery money allocated to sport. This is
distributed by a special committee of the Scottish Sports Council.
They have done their job wisely, and spread the money both geographically and
to where the need is most urgent.
With the exception of the Millennium Fund, Parliament made it very clear that
the distributing committees, whether they be sport, the arts, charities, or the
heritage, should be absolutely clear of any ministerial or Governmental
influence. The Government also made it clear Lottery money should be over and
above the normal funding by departments.
So far so good. But I think we should have a rethink and a change of emphasis.
There must be a greater flexibility in the award system. The Sports Council has
a guideline - not a requirement - that grants should be matched by a 50% input
by the applicant. That is a reasonable approach, but it is restrictive in that
the Sports Council can only fund capital projects, and not support a body
through revenue funding. Applications can only be for buildings and facilities
and not for running costs.
This is open to argument and as time passes, I am sure there will be a change.
The sooner the better. This is essential if we are to help individuals as so
clearly set out by Craig Reedie a few weeks ago. The Sports Aid Foundation, the
Sports Council, the Foundation for Sport, and the Arts, help where they can,
but it is at the level just below the top - the emerging stars, without
sponsorship, who need assistance in many sports. From here will come our
successes, if not at the Olympics at the next Commonwealth Games.
It is also essential if some of our capital projects are to be serviced. A
swimming pool is an obvious candidate. Running costs are high and even with
local authority assistance, support would be required from the Lottery.
I believe too, and I certainly was not allowed to suggest it to the Sports
Council or the Millennium Commission, that in the sporting field there are two
projects above all else that the Scottish public want to see.
A completed Hampden Park with the new stand, medical centre, library and other
facilities, and the final touches to Murrayfield.
Yes, we want the forests, canals, museums and sports grounds already approved,
but I think the Scottish people want us to have the two finest national
stadiums in the United Kingdom.
Together they could cost another #20m, but they would be an important factor in
any application for a major world event to go alongside the excellent
facilities of Edinburgh and Glasgow.
It may mean holding back on some small projects now, but in the long run, it
could be best for Scotland.
The Lottery has succeeded beyond our dreams. Now let us have a pause for
thought leading to greater flexibility, and the achievement of even greater
successes in the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MOTOR SPORT DIARY</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>motor sport diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975224982</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN a quiet week for local sporting events, details have been issued of the
Scottish Motor Racing Club's 1996 season. It includes all the race meetings at
Knockhill except for the British Touring Car Championship weekend and a BRSCC
event in June, and also takes in two meetings at Croft near Darlington.
The season opens at Knockhill on April 7, continues with Croft on the 20th,
then returns to Knockhill on April 28 and May 26. The second Croft visit is on
June 8, and the later Knockhill meetings are on June 30, August 11, September
1, September 22, and October 6.
Road saloons, road sports cars and Formula Ford will all have their own
championships. There have been almost 100 enquiries about the new Escort and
Fiesta XR Saloon Cup, which is a very heartening response. Historic Ecosse
drivers will have their 1996 outings - probably five at Knockhill and one at
Croft - formalised as a championship. Being there and finishing each race are
the most important things, because ten points are offered for starting and ten
more for finishing, compared with three, two and one for the first three
drivers in each class.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Scottish car that went a fair distance before it stopped</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224983</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Arrol-Johnston is still an evocative name. ROSS FINLAY recalls its birth and
trip into motoring history
LAST month's feature on George Johnston's 1895 Panhard concentrated on him as a
pioneer private motorist. But he was also the founder of Arrol-Johnston, which
outlasted all the other original Scottish car manufacturers.
Johnston experimented for several years before actually going into production.
Two of his associates were so put out by the slow progress that in 1899 they
went off and founded Albion. He formed the Mo-Car Syndicate, and it was Sir
William Arrol's presence as one of its members which gave the car itself the
Arrol-Johnston name.
Arrol was one of the most highly regarded personalities in late Victorian
Scotland. A blacksmith turned brilliant civil engineer, he gained both a
knighthood and immense public esteem by building the Forth Bridge.
He was on the board of several engineering ventures, and was, for instance, a
founder director of Babcock and Wilcox in Renfrew. But the Arrol family recall
today that he took no direct part in the running of Johnston's company.
Arrol-Johnston's factory at Yate Street in the east end of Glasgow was
operational by 1901. Johnston favoured already obsolete styling with the driver
sitting high up in the centre of the car, passengers fore and aft.
The Yate Street works, a stock of part-completed cars and detailed company
records were all destroyed by a fire which broke out on the evening of May 8,
1901. The Coats family of Paisley, investors in the syndicate, offered the
disused Underwood Mill in the town as a replacement. Production restarted there
in 1902.
The late George Oliver, historian of the Scottish motor industry, had the
opportunity to drive an Arrol-Johnston of the original design. He was impressed
by the smooth operation of the very complex but effective horizontally-opposed
engine and also by the car's unexpectedly quiet running.
Sir William Lithgow owns an early Paisley-built Arrol-Johnston. He says it is
``not easy to drive, but very robust and can scamper along at 20mph. I was
advised that great difficulty was experienced in getting these engines to run
properly.
``I suspect that the biggest problem has been in understanding the
characteristics of the low-tension magneto, and timing the break to match the
voltage peak. The engine is started with a recoil system similar to a Flymo,
tricky if you have never tried to start a three-and-a-half litre Flymo.''
In 1905 William Beardmore of Parkhead Forge bought out the loss-making Mo-Car
Syndicate's original members and installed John Napier as managing director.
Johnston himself left.
Arrol-Johnston made a splash when one of its cars, modernised by Napier, won
the inaugural Tourist Trophy race on the Isle of Man. Napier himself drove the
winning car, beating no less a make than Rolls-Royce into second place.
The company continued losing money, though, a situation which changed very much
for the better in 1909 when T C Pullinger, with experience at Darracq, Sunbeam
and Humber, arrived as yet another new broom. He moved production to a new
factory at Heathhall on the outskirts of Dumfries, which is why this week's
Classic Car  (left) is a Doonhamer.
Post-war, business prospects for the smaller firms within the UK industry, as
mass production arrived, were bleak. In 1927 Arrol-Johnston merged with Asters
of Wembley. There are still some Arrol-Asters about, including one in the
Museum of Transport in Glasgow, sharing exhibition space with examples of
Beardmore and Galloway, other makes once part of the Arrol-Johnston group.
As the Depression loomed, publicity in connection with the company's rebuild of
Sir Malcolm Campbell's Bluebird made little impression. The liquidators arrived
in 1929, and the original indigenous Scottish motor industry was about to put
up the shutters.
</TEXT>
