<DOCNO>GH951124-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CLASSIC CAR raring to go</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN March 1965 the famous Sword Collection was auctioned off at East Balgray
Farm near Torranyard in Ayrshire. One anonymous member of the Royal Scottish
Automobile Club bid successfully for the 1922 15.9hp Arrol-Johnston registered
DL 2560 - and promptly presented it to the club.
The Arrol-Johnston remains in the RSAC's ownership today, and is seen every
summer at vintage runs and parades all over the south of Scotland. This is its
home territory, because it was built at Arrol-Johnston's Heathhall factory on
the outskirts of Dumfries, now occupied by Gates Rubber.
Just as signficantly, it was bodied by the coachbuilders A C Penman, also of
Heathhall, and it is the successor company, Penman Engineering, which restored
the car, just before the Dumfries Octocentenary celebrations in 1986.
Managing director Edwin Hunter takes his turn at the wheel, but Ian Gray, a
supervisor at Penman Engineering, is its most regular driver, notching up 1500
miles in an average summer, when the car may take part in events at places like
Dumfries, Kirkcudbright, Selkirk and Biggar.
Many people do a double take at the drophead body, because it does indeed have
only one door - on the front passenger's side - and the spare wheel is mounted
where the driver's door would normally be.
Gear lever and handbrake are to the driver's right, because there is no need
for an uncluttered door opening. Another notable feature is the three-piece
windscreen of unusual style for its time.
Ian Gray reckons the top speed with the 2613cc engine to be about 38mph, but
Arrol-Johnston built very torquey power units and believed in big flywheels. He
can leave Heathhall for Biggar, and stay in top gear all the way up the climb
past the Devil's Beef Tub on the A701.
Two features which take some getting used to are the central throttle pedal and
the rear-wheels-only brakes. Like many vintage car drivers, Ian Gray wishes
modern motorists, seeing the Arrol-Johnston, would make more allowances for it.
Once off the road for the winter, DL 2560 will stay under wraps at Penmans
until March. Then Ian Gray will simply put petrol in the Autovac, clean the
plugs and check the battery, and this sturdy vintage machine, in its 75th
season, will be raring to go.
</TEXT>
