<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Converter test ... of character</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Many a driver could
faint or scream when the whole expensive, catalytic truth comes out with the
new emission regulations, warns Ross Finlay
COME January, many people presenting their cars for an MOT test may either
faint or run screaming from the test centre on hearing the result. New emission
regulations come into force then, and it is dead certain that hundreds of cars
all over the UK will fail each year, because their catalytic converters are out
of action.
The point about these devices is that they either work or do not work. There is
no intermediate just-about-good-enough stage.
And the really bad news is that, if a car fails the test and cannot be issued
with a pass certificate until a new catalytic converter is fitted, then,
depending on the model of car and the size of the replacement converter, the
owner will be looking at a bill for a new unit of anything between #300 and
#800, and even higher in some cases.
Jim Corbett of Citroen Glasgow is one of the service managers who has been
looking closely at the implications of the Vehicle Inspectorate's new test
schedules. They include measuring four types of exhaust gases - carbon
monoxide, carbon dioxide, unburned hydrocarbons, and oxygen.
He has also been studying the results of a series of informal roadside tests
carried out in the south of England. As many as 15% of the vehicles examined
could not meet the 1996 requirements, many because their converters were
useless.
From workshop experience, he knows that there are two main reasons why a
converter fails. One is that an owner has put in a quantity of leaded petrol.
Admittedly, some converters will continue to work after a small amount of
leaded fuel has found its way into a tank otherwise filled with unleaded, but
the general rule is that lead wrecks converters.
It does happen that someone runs out of fuel in a converter-equipped car,
manages to get hold of a gallon can of fuel which turns out to be leaded, and
runs the car, perhaps just for a mile or so to a filling station, on a
part-tank of undiluted leaded petrol. In fact, running the tank dry will
probably ``kill'' the converter anyway.
Although some people still fail to realise this, a catalytic converter is not a
filter which can be cleaned out if the wrong materials clog it up. It is a
sophisticated device in which a chemical reaction, between the exhaust gases
and some very expensive metal plates through which they are led, ``cleans up''
the exhaust.
The fact that the metals involved are such things as platinum and rhodium is
what makes a converter cost so much. They do not, to mix a metaphor, grow on
trees.
As Jim Corbett has seen on several occasions, the other reason for the failure
of a catalytic converter is that it suffers physical damage and cannot be
repaired. We tend to think that converters are safely tucked away, but they are
in fact quite vulnerable.
A rough stretch of road which wrecks a car's exhaust may also terminally damage
the converter. And the consequence of some apparently unconnected incident - a
small front-end collision, perhaps - may be that the service manager says:
``Repairing the body damage will cost #100. And, by the way, there'll be
another #600 to replace the converter which got dislodged by the impact.''
When all this becomes generally known, owners will no doubt try to have their
cars put through the test in the best possible conditions. For instance,
somebody whose car blows a bit of smoke when warm may try to put it forward for
the test cold. The Vehicle Inspectorate will not allow that.
Test centres must ensure that the car is well warmed-up following a standard
routine. A hand-held computer gives a digital print-out showing not only the
emission levels of the gases concerned, but also the exact engine oil
temperature reading, to show that the test was carried out correctly. Centres
already have charts giving the temperature requirements for each make and model
of car likely to be presented.
The #28.38 test fee currently charged is a fairly silly non-round amount of
money. But the much bigger amounts some people will have to stump up afterwards
will not seem so funny.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No money-spinner for the trade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jim Corbett</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS well as wondering what MOT customers will make of the 1996 tests, Jim
Corbett is mulling over the implications for the garage trade of the new
requirements. Its reaction is anything but enthusiastic.
Several test centres have recently given up, and it is quite possible that more
will follow suit. The problem is that the expense of installing the exhaust
test equipment, then paying for the operator's time - and operators will
obviously take longer to complete the more complicated 1996 tests - is crazy
when set against the revenue that comes in.
The test fee recently went up from #26.10 to #27.38. Trade representatives had
lobbied for #30.95 as a more sensible figure, but were given a dusty reception
by officials.
Even people who think the motor trade is composed entirely of millionaires may
realise that the extra #1.28 per test will not go very far, even allowing for
the fact that the equipment is probably written down in the books over a
ten-year period.
A typical deal may see the garage paying something like #4500 for its new test
equipment. It would take 3515 tests at the extra #1.28 each to cover that
figure. And that is before any calculations about how much, at a typical hourly
labour rate, the operator's extra time will cost - a cost which cannot be
passed on to the customer.
Partly because of discounting in their retail sales, many dealerships are
trying to maximise profits from their service departments. But it is impossible
to improve the working of an operation which more or less by definition must
run at a loss, certainly in its early stages, and cannot either increase its
charges or reduce the time taken over its work.
In addition, there are concerns in the trade that the 1996 regulations may be
only a first step. If new standards are brought in, say in another two years,
bang goes the advantage of writing down the cost of the equipment over ten. The
test equipment manufacturers may well say that the 1996 equipment cannot be
modified, and that garages will have to invest in an all-new set-up once again.
In the end, it may be that only main dealers for individual makes of car will
continue as test centres. They can hardly refuse to provide that service for
their franchised make. But few of them will regard it as much more than an
unavoidable and barely profitable duty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
