<DOCNO>GH951124-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Much room from little loom grows</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975224987</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OF all the vehicle manufacturing companies in the world, Toyota is one of the
keenest at letting people know the statistics of its business. They make
intriguing, and at times highly entertaining, reading.
The first Toyotas were built exactly 60 years ago, when a tiny automobile
department was set up in the founding family's loom factory. In the table of
production numbers, against the year 1935 there appear the figures: total
vehicles 20, passenger cars 0. All the first-year Toyotas were trucks.
Contrast these with the corresponding statistics for the most recent full year
of production, 1994. They read: total vehicles 3,508,456, passenger cars
2,769,359. At first the temptation is to think that these numbers represent the
total Toyota production since the company was started, but they are single-year
figures, and from the Japanese factories alone.
They take no account of the manufacturing and assembly plants in the United
Kingdom, North and South America, Africa, Australia and New Zealand, and
elsewhere in Asia.
Toyota is so big in the Japanese economy, and so concentrated in its production
facilities, that its head office and 12 individual manufacturing plants are
located in a metropolitan area called Toyota City. Cars, truck and bus chassis,
engines, electronic and other components are all built within a small radius,
with two shipping complexes nearby.
Selling is a huge international operation, and often started on a small scale
in an area where Toyota now dominates certain sectors of the local market. For
example, the company took its first tentative steps in Africa in 1957, when it
set up a small import business in Ethiopia, of all unlikely locations. Now it
sells throughout the continent, and the Landcruiser is the          most
prominent 4x4 in several countries.
Like most Japanese companies, Toyota uses different model names in different
markets. Some of them are hardly to British tastes. Showrooms in Japan, for
example, display vehicles like the Caldina, Estima, Emina, Cynos, Chaser,
Sprinter, Carib, and Deliboy.
We chuckle at the quaint Nipponese names. But if you recall what has happened
to the home-owned British motor industry, who should be doing the laughing? One
notable thing about one of the world's biggest motor manufacturing companies is
that members of the founding family still help to direct its affairs. Their
name is actually Toyoda.
A mysterious Japanese enterprise involved in a lagging-behind London property
development recently pretended to have an entirely imaginary spokesman called
Mr Toyota. That may have gulled the London property writers, but it would not
have fooled the motoring staff, who know the two names are, confusingly, not
the same.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
