<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>North Sea order for Brown</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BROWN Brothers, the Edinburgh-based engineering firm, has won a multi-million
pound order for equipment to transfer oil and gas from undersea wells on to a
floating storage vessel moored in the North Sea.
The 100-tonne swivel stack will be mounted on the converted tanker Dagmar
Maersk. This will be linked by pipelines to undersea oil and gas wells in
Conoco's MacCulloch field when it comes on stream in December 1996.
The seven-metre high swivel stack will control the flow of oil and gas pumped
aboard the vessel, however much it may pitch and roll in heavy seas.
The exact value of the contract was not disclosed.
Brown Brothers, which specialises in the manufacture of motion control
equipment for merchant vessels, warships, and offshore platforms, is a
subsidiary of the Vickers engineering group.
</TEXT>
