<DOCNO>GH951124-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Profits on tap for water shareholders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER the bonanza that shareholders of the English electricity companies have
enjoyed it could now be the turn of shareholders in the privatised water
companies.
Lucky holders of shares in Northumbrian Water are to receive #11.79p for each
share following the #823m takeover bid for the company from Lyonnaise des Eaux.
This means that since the start of the year they have seen a 73% profit on
their investment.
A typical holder of 200 Northumbrian shares since privatisation in 1989 has
seen a total profit of #1878 plus dividends of about #280 on his original #480
investment. Had the same amount been invested in an average quoted company the
gain would have been just #206 plus dividends of roughly #100.
The Northumbrian return is on a par with the profits seen by shareholders in
the English electricity companies (recs) following the bidding frenzy in the
industry which has left just four out of the 12 as independent companies.
Shares of two companies, Norweb and Seeboard, have about doubled this year and
the smallest gain in the sector still came to 59%. Even companies like South
Wales which have not received a bid have seen huge rises on their shares.
Now to cap it all shareholders are going to receive a further bonanza from the
listing on the stock market of shares in National Grid. As the company was
formerly owned by the recs, part of its value is being passed on to them
directly. Each rec shareholder will receive on average of about eight Grid
shares for every 10 rec held. This is equivalent to a windfall of some 180p for
each share they own.
The electricity bonanza reflects the perceived value in terms of profits and
cash flow of the recs to other companies and the Government's decision, taken
against the advice of the electricity industry regulator, to allow a
free-for-all to develop. The value of the companies stems basically from the
cheap price at which they were privatised and the subsequent relatively light
regulation of the industry.
Increased efficiency through manpower cuts have enabled the companies to reduce
the price of electricity in real terms but more of the benefits have gone to
shareholders, who in addition to huge capital gains have received large rises
in dividends each year since privatisation.
To take the example of Manweb which received a #1100m bid from ScottishPower. A
holding of 200 shares bought on privatisation cost #480. At the bid value, it
is now worth #2040, giving a profit of #1560. It will also have brought in
dividend income totalling #210, spread over five years.
While these figures are on a par with the Northumbrian Water case, shareholders
in the other water companies have not done nearly so well. On average the
shares have risen by 15% this year, slightly less than the market as a whole.
Since privatisation a holder of 200 Anglian Water shares for example has seen a
gain of #680, though dividend income has been similar at #260.
Scots have missed the utilities bonanza because water was not privatised and
ScottishPower and Scottish Hydro-Electric were not sold off as cheaply. They
were privatised after the English electricity and water companies, when the
Government had learned more about valuing them. They are also different in
being integrated power companies, generating and distributing electricity, and
of less interest to bidders.
Since privatisation, shareholders of ScottishPower and Hydro have seen gains of
57% and 48% respectively which is insignificant when compared with the fourfold
rise in an investment in the average rec.
More predators are likely to be looking at water companies now that the
Government has allowed the Lyonnaise bid through, albeit with some pretty
stringent conditions, notably that prices to consumers have to be reduced by
15% by 2001. But they will not generate same excitement as the electricity
companies.
There appears to be limited interest from within the UK, not least because of
the heavier regulatory hand when compared with the recs. North West Water is
spreading its wings by bidding for the rec which operates in its geographical
area, Norweb, and Welsh Water is contemplating doing the same for South Wales
Electricity. There may be attempts by two adjacent water companies to merge,
though this will be resisted by the regulator.
The water companies face a new round of heavy capital expenditure to achieve
higher standards of supply and waste treatment. In contrast, the recs have few
spending obligations and generate large amounts of cash.
The attraction for overseas companies is that Britain will allow them to buy
actual assets, the water plants, sewage works and distribution networks. Water
suppliers around the world generally do not own their plant. Instead it is held
by local or central government, which may well hire a private sector company to
operate the system and collect the revenue.
While margins for Lyonnaise's domestic operations in its home market may be 2%
or 3% they may range up to 25% in Britain because it will own the assets. As a
result the industry will be of particular interest to overseas utilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pope lays it on the line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN COONEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224990</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS week a Scottish visitor to Ireland remarked that the anti-divorce
campaigners were so well organised that he reckoned that they would pull off a
surprise publicity coup ahead of polling in today's referendum.
This pre-vote coup was accomplished in spectacular style yesterday with the
intervention of Pope John Paul II when the 75-year-old Pontiff urged the Irish
people to pray more intensely to preserve ``the unbreakable bond of marriage''.
The Pope's appeal to Irish electors to block the introduction of divorce
publicly signals the Vatican's blessing of the strenuous efforts taken by the
Roman Catholic hierarchy.
This papal intervention came after several Government ministers and the leader
of the SDLP in Northern Ireland, John Hume, had appealed to voters to take
account of the sensitivities of Protestants in Ulster, especially the possible
negative effect on the peace process if the divorce referendum is perceived to
have lost out to ``Rome Rule''.
While the anti-divorce campaigners rejoiced that the Pope's message would
copper-fasten victory for them today, Rome's intervention was seen as
interference by the six political parties in the Dail which have been taken
aback by the volatility of public opinion.
A lead of over 20 points in opinion polls in favour of law reform measure at
the start of the referendum campaign has been cut to a mere three points, with
the swing still heading for a No vote.
The nightmare for the Government is of a repeat of 1986 when a similar attempt
to introduce divorce swung from a 2-1 margin in favour at the outset to a 2-1
defeat on polling day.
This time the political establishment and the media have responded more
vigorously to the barrage of propaganda and scare tactics of the anti-divorce
lobbies. Today's referendum result could be the closest since Eamon de Valera
drafted the Constitution in 1937 with its prohibition against divorce.
The proposed amendment to the Constitution would allow divorce in cases where
couples have been separated for at least four of the previous five years. A
couple would have to prove reconciliation efforts had failed completely. The
courts would be empowered to make orders about property rights and the welfare
of children.
Although 18 separate pieces of legislation had been put in place since 1986 to
deal with such contentious money and property issues for an estimated separated
80,000 couples, the anti-campaigners have rallied support by claiming that the
first family would lose its constitutional rights, that marriage would no
longer be a permanent contract, and that the introduction of no-fault divorce
would accelerate marriage breakdown as in Britain and the United States.
These social arguments have been skilfully presented by a small group of
dedicated activists that include Des Hanafin, a reformed alcoholic; Joe
McCarroll, a teacher whose own marriage has broken down; a retired High Court
judge, Rory O'Hanlon, who is a member of the ultra-right Catholic body Opus
Dei; and a constitutional lawyer, William Binchy, the brother of novelist Maeve
Binchy.
A second group of even more zealous Catholic fundamentalists want to roll-back
recent liberal social changes in Ireland and have smeared the two Jewish
members of the Dail. An instance of scare tactics was a poster stating ``Hallo,
divorce, Good-bye, daddy.''
The evidence shows that many women have been influenced by this propaganda that
reduces them to chattels of errant husbands. Opinion within the main Opposition
party, Fianna Fail, has swung solidly against divorce, recreating a de facto
alliance of the Catholic bishops and Fianna Fail that was so decisive in 1986.
In an end-of-campaign appeal, Prime Minister John Bruton tried to counteract
the impact of the Pope. Today the Irish people have ``the opportunity to vote
for a more pluralist and tolerant country,'' he said, urging respect of
minority rights.
The Pope's remarks merely add a new chapter to the intimate relations which
have characterised Vatican policy towards Ireland since its independence in
1922.
During the 1932 Eucharistic Congress the voice of Pope Pius XI was heard for
the first time in a radio broadcast by the vast crowd of pilgrims attending
Mass in Dublin's Phoenix Park. ``The silence of the people as the Holy Father
spoke became almost painfully intense. There was a catch in each one's throat,
and every eye was moist. Over the whole multitude surged a tide of pride, and
gratitude, and exaltation,'' according to the Congress chronicle.
Five years later, as the archives now reveal, Joseph Walshe, the secretary of
the Department of External Relations, was sent by de Valera to secure advance
approval by Pope Pius XI for the draft Constitution - ahead of its publication
in parliament and presentation to the electorate.
While Pope Pius XI withheld his full approval, he and subsequent Popes have
lauded the Irish Constitution as reflecting Catholic values, particularly in
regard to the family. So much so that when Dr Garret FitzGerald tried to
persuade Pope Paul VI in the 1970s to approve the removal of sectarian features
from the De Valera Constitution, he was strongly rebuked by the elderly Pontiff.
``Ireland semper fidelis - Ireland always faithful'' were the last words
uttered by Pope John Paul II after his historic visit in 1979 when 2.7 million
people flocked to hear him.
In 1987 and in 1992 when the Irish bishops made their ad limina visit to Rome
to account for their stewardship, Pope John Paul made it clear he wanted them
to hold the line against divorce, abortion, and a secular Ireland.
The firmness of the Pope's intervention shows no weakening of his policy
towards Ireland, despite the dismay felt in Rome at the recent spate of sexual
scandals involving senior clergy.
The odds are that the measure may narrowly be accepted - but don't be surprised
by a No vote.
The outcome will be closely watched for evidence of the extent of the influence
of the traditional alliance of Pope and bishops in a referendum which has at
its core the question of whether the Constitution should reflect Roman Catholic
or pluralist values.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
