<HEADLINE>Generations gone to pot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEEDEE CUDDIHY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224991</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRIED &amp; TASTED
DEEDEE CUDDIHY puts instant meals to the test
LAST month, the managers of a pub near Glasgow University de-cided to hand out
free Student Survival Kits in a bid to get even more useful customers through
the doors. The kits included a condom (yawn), toothbrush and toothpaste and
some pot noodle, the instant dried snack food that you pour boiling water over
and eat straight from the container.
It wasn't the original Pot Noodle - launched by Golden Wonder in 1979 and now
selling in Britain at the rate of 110 million units per annum - but one of an
increasing number of pot noodle imitators which the public, nevertheless,
insist on calling pot noodle (in the same way that vacuum cleaners are referred
to as Hoovers).
The point is, do students really survive on this stuff? Some of us who
experienced the 1979 prototype will find it hard to believe that anyone could
eat a whole container of pot noodle, even under duress.
But perhaps the product has changed over the past 16 years? We bought five
varieties of eat-from-the-pot snack meal and with the help of lecturer Pauline
Devlin, tested them on six, second year students from Cale-donian University's
Department of Consumer and Manage-ment Studies.
Sinead, Louise, Eleanor, Claire, Natasha and Leigh tried out Pot Rice chicken
curry, Pots of the World Texan hot chilli and beef and tomato Pot Noodle (all
by Golden Wonder) as well as Pasta Regale tagliatelle parmagani and Nissin beef
Cup Noodles. All the products were priced at around 75p per pot in supermarkets.
Pot Rice - Sinead thought the flavour was good, Grace said she liked it, the
other four were put off by the smell, flavour and texture which they pronounced
artificial and over-processed.
Texan hot chilli - Louise and Eleanor liked this better than the Pot Rice,
Grace and Natasha both said it was too spicy, Leigh and Sinead didn't like,
respectively, the texture and the taste.
Beef and tomato Pot Noodle - the variety which drew the least violent reactions
from our testers, with most agreeing it wasn't bad and Eleanor going so far as
to say she might buy it.
Pasta Regale - Sinead and Louise were very impressed with this nicely
presented, vegetarian product, declaring it good enough to put on a plate.
Eleanor also liked it, Grace pronounced it ``boggin''', Natasha said it was
disgusting, Leigh was put off by the smell and appearance.
Nissan Cup Noodles with beef - although Sinead remarked on the rather bland
flavour of this product, all the testers were impressed by its real food
flavour and appearance.
At the end of our testing session, five of the tasters said they might try one
or more varieties of pot noodle again - especially if they were drunk. Natasha,
however, declared that she had been put off for life.
</TEXT>
