<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Queensland still in charge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224992</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAST bowler Michael Kasprowicz took a career-best seven for 64 to put
Queensland in command against the Sri Lankan tourists on the second day of a
four-day match on Thursday.
Kasprowicz's superb spell helped dismiss Sri Lanka for a paltry 178 in reply to
Queensland's first innings 305. At the close, Queensland were 13 for no wicket,
and with a lead of 140, were well-placed for victory with two days to spare.
Only Sri Lankan captain Arjuna Ranatunga offered any resistance to the
Queensland attack, top scoring with 77 before he was caught by former
Australian captain Allan Border off Kasprowicz.
q FOUR West Indies players whose behaviour was considered ``unsatisfactory''
during the team's tour of England this year have appeared before a disciplinary
hearing. West Indies Cricket Board of Control (WICBC) have still to name
officially the players involved, but the Caribbean News Agency (CANA) said it
was known Brian Lara, Carl Hooper, Curtly Ambrose, and Kenny Benjamin met the
disciplinary committee on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
