<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Radford delivers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PHIL PENFOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224993</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is a note of apology in Michael Radford's voice. ``I'm afraid that I'm
rather rootless,'' he says, ``and that's a direct result of being a child of
the remnants of the Empire. My father was in the services, and was posted just
about all over the place. I always say that White Mischief is one of my least
personal films - all about the ruling classes in Kenya in the early forties -
but then I think about it and realise that it is probably more reflective and
personal to the way I was brought up than anything else.
``If I had to have a home anywhere, I guess it would be in Scotland, where I
spent a lot of my professional growing-up, and a lot of childhood holidays. And
I still love the place. But as for settling down anywhere, I find that
terrifically difficult.''
Radford, at 45, is one of the younger British film directors who has made his
mark with a series of movies that, while perhaps they did not perform to major
box office bucks at the time of release, are now considered either landmarks of
film - or cult classics. ``White Mischief is shown by request on cable stations
in the US about once every month,'' he says.
Radford, born in New Delhi to an English father and an Austrian mother (``which
complicates things still further,'' he laughs), worked as an actor and a
teacher before becoming one of the first students at the newly opened National
Film School. He graduated with another distinctive film-maker, Bill Forsyth. He
started off making documentaries, and then his film of Jessie Kesson's novel,
The White Bird Passes, received Scotland's best dramatic picture award in the
early eighties. Then came Another Time, Another Place, an adaptation of another
Kesson novel, which won prizes at festivals all around the world.
It was Radford who directed Richard Burton in his last film, 1984, (possibly
one of that much-maligned actor's better pieces of work on film) and then came
White Mischief.
``The critics jumped on it. Trampled it,'' says Michael. ``And naturally, I got
very disheartened by that. Who wouldn't? So, licking my wounds, I went off to
France and started writing screenplays and making commercials to keep body and
soul together.''
Meanwhile, the Italian actor and humourist Massimo Troisi had seen Michael's
work, and made contact. The two men became friends and vowed they would make a
film together. It all came to be in the movie released this month in the UK, Il
Postino (The Postman).
The film has already been a phenomenal success in the US. ``As I speak, I think
it's the biggest-grossing foreign language film of all time,'' says Radford
with a broad smile.
``How it's captured the hearts and minds of so many people I really don't know,
though I'd like to think it was because it tells a story, that it offers people
a chance to think about what they're seeing, and it reflects a very human
drama.''
And drama in real-life, too. Tragically, Troisi died the day after shooting
finished. ``His ill-health was no secret at all,'' says Michael sadly. ``He'd
had heart problems since his late teens, and had to take things easy. He knew
he had a problem. And ironically he had been offered a heart transplant just as
we went into production, but declined it. Massimo said he believed in Il
Postino so much that he'd put it off, that the film was more important, and
that, as far as making it went, it was now or never.
``We had to bear all this in mind, and not over-tax him. It meant that he could
do about two hours actual work a day. And shoot around the `problem' by using a
stunt double who was so like Massimo that it was uncanny. I defy anyone to spot
the joins - where it's Massimo and when it's the double.
``Basically, Il Postino has some of its roots in truth. There was a poet called
Pablo Neruda, he came from Chile, and he wrote some amazingly effective work.
He was exiled from his home country for some time.
``So we decided that we would place him on an Italian island, and have him
befriend this rather gauche postman. The film is about how the younger man
falls in love with the most beautiful girl on the island, and how he achieves
his ambitions with the help of the poet.''
Il Postino has a celebrity following in the US. ``So much so,'' says Michael,
``that we've issued a CD of Neruda's work, with people like Madonna, Julia
Roberts, Ralph Fiennes and Ethan Hawke reading it. Julia turned up at the
studio with this dog-eared copy of his collected works that she said she'd read
over and over again since her teens. And Madonna has everything he's ever
written. She just begged to be allowed to read something - and when she did, it
was just amazing. Very emotional. Perfect.''
Il Postino has now given Radford the opening einto big-time Hollywood. ``And
one of the reasons for that is that Jack Nicholson got up at some function or
other and said that the film was one of the most moving things he'd ever seen.
When Jack says that, people in LA listen. And listen hard.
``So I'm going to relish the moment, and take a little time to discover what I
want to do. Not too much time, because things move on very quickly in
Hollywood. You can be very hot one day - and luke-warm the next.
``One project I've got to consider is maybe a remake of Anna Karenina, with
Michele Pfeiffer in the title role."
He adds: ``Postino tells all of us that to have a mentor is a wonderful thing,
someone who can open that door of appreciation for you, and then guide you
through it. I think that it's a movie for intelligent people, people who want
to laugh and cry and be touched emotionally.
``Who was my own mentor? My history teacher at school, who just made me see
that books were the key to appreciating so many great things.
``I don't see why a film can't be both popular and intelligent, and that's
certainly the sort of film I want to make. You know when you're going to make a
stinker, because you're seduced by the size of the cheque.''
He chucked in acting himself, he says, ``because when the biggest role I had
was as the Dormouse in Toad of Toad Hall, with one line to say, I realised that
I wasn't getting anywhere fast.''
Does he see himself making films again in the UK? ``Well, yes because you can
never rule anything out. But I would, I confess, find it difficult to make a
movie in Yorkshire or Glasgow or wherever because my own personal mood isn't
right. I use my own personal instincts and let them guide me. You just can't do
anything else, can you?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
