<HEADLINE>Rangers still on Europe's rocky road to nowhere</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224994</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS are considering the possibility of preventing a few of their players
from appearing before the SFA disciplinary committee to answer allegations that
they behaved badly on the field of play recently.
Justice and the interests of the game might be better served if the Ibrox club
kept all of their players indoors on Champions' League nights and made them
study the art of movement.
Rarely can a group of players be so determined to put so much into a match yet
appear static. While Steaua Bucharest strolled, sprinted, and drifted often
unnoticed into spaces in support of their man in possession, Rangers worked
extremely hard to get nowhere.
Hardly any Rangers player on the pitch in Wednesday night's match made
intelligent runs in support of attacks and indeed it was partly because of this
failure that Paul Gascoigne set off on the remarkable run which created his
team's goal in the 1-1 draw.
Gascoigne took a pass from Brian Laudrup and when he had no-one available in a
position potentially dangerous to Steaua, he went on alone and scored a
wonderful goal. It was fortunate for Rangers that it was Gascoigne who was in
possession because no-one else, apart from Luadrup, could have engineered a
breakthrough from within his own half of the pitch.
The Romanians, by comparison, were casually fluent without ever producing
football which took the breath away, but when they moved forward, support
travelled swiftly as it should do. Sometimes the player with the ball had two
or three options while the Ibrox side's play suffered from a woeful lack of
vision within.
Steaua's coach Dumitru Dumitriu was not lying when he said too many Rangers
players seem always to be waiting for Laudrup and Gascoigne to do something
instead of doing it for themselves. The problem is, of course, that too many of
the players who are likely to win an eighth successive domestic championship
are incapable of seeking out space or making the telling run.
There is a profound lack of awareness about this Rangers team and they cannot
become European graduates until they can think on their feet like their foreign
opponents. Rangers actually had more possession than Steaua, but endeavour
without direction equals sweat, and that alone will not do, even at Ibrox where
they have been vulnerable.
This season alone Hibernian, Raith Rovers, Aberdeen, and Celtic as well, of
course, as Borussia Dortmund, Juventus, and Steaua Bucharest have taken points
from Ibrox. That should alarm the management, and if his players won't, Walter
Smith will have to apply some thought to the deficiencies highlighted in five
Champions' League matches which have yielded only two points and four goals.
Rangers have conceded 12 goals, although eight were scored by one team,
Juventus, which also suggests the defence is not nearly as strong as its early
season promise. Indeed, more than #25m has been spent building a team for
Europe, and clearly Rangers are still not good enough.
Players like Gary Bollan and Alex Cleland were bought in as fillers, squad men,
and surely it was never the intention to rely on them on the big occasions,
although injuries to others reduced Smith's options considerably to the point
where he has had to turn again to John Brown, who thought his playing days were
over.
Neil Murray falls into the back-up category also, but more should be provided
by others like Gordan Petric, who was at fault when Rangers conceded the
equaliser to Steaua. Petric appears intent on proving he is indeed a player who
will cost a team                     perhaps half a dozen goals in critical
games. He has not looked comfortable in the rarified atmosphere of Champions'
League football, even though he is a foreigner.
Also, Alan McLaren, despite all the praise delivered at his feet, has not done
enough to convince sceptics, and neither David Robertson nor Stephen Wright
possess the necessary com-posure and touch to play the modern wing-back roles
to the full. Rangers are trying to pass the ball from the back, but when they
move forward and pass wide, hoping for the ball to be taken deep before being
delivered into the box, they run the risk of losing possession with players out
of position.
Up front, Smith bought in Oleg Salenko with the intention of creating a
dangerous new strike force, but the Russian and Ally McCoist are not gelling
well. The latter is a penalty-box player, and he needs service - only one real
chance was created for him against Steaua - otherwise he loses any
effectiveness. Smith must sign another striker soon and it must be one who is
capable of enhancing the system being played in the absence of Mark Hateley,
whose presence made a long-ball game productive.
A lot more spending will have to be done if Rangers are to add to the qualities
of Andy Goram and Richard Gough, and also Laudrup and Gascoigne, provided these
two give their best for the cause.
It is astonishing to think Smith has a team which could set a new mark in
Scottish football history in terms of league champion-ships yet they are
impotent abroad. Of course, if the chairman, David Murray, is happy setting
home records, he won't have to find more money. But if he seeks greater
exposure for his team, it will cost him again.
</TEXT>
