<HEADLINE>Rouyan can show class</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224995</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROUYAN, who carries something of a ``handle with care'' tag after a series of
annoying leg problems, can show himself very much at the top of his game by
winning the Jacky Upton Handicap Chase today at Newbury.
The nine-year-old was restricted to two runs in handicap chases last term but,
a smart hurdler who won Sandown's Tote Jackpot Handicap                  Hurdle
for Ron Simpson in January 1991, he has proved equally able over fences.
Although once-raced in novice chase company in each of his first two campaigns
in the care of Jenny Pitman, Rouyan showed useful form in five races the season
before last.
And last term, with two wins as many starts, he confirmed himself a progressive
chaser and - just as, if not more important - one still on the right side of
the handicapper.
Eskimo Nel is an improved filly of late and can make light of a 5lb penalty in
the Brimpton Handicap Hurdle.
Brian Harding might have missed out on the ride aboard One Man in the Hennessy
Gold Cup, but he still has plenty to thank Gordon Richards for and can partner
the Greystoke trainer's Better Times Ahead to victory in the Helshaw Grange
Handicap Chase at Bangor.
</TEXT>
