<HEADLINE>Make or break for Stirling at Bridgehaugh Joiner return boosts Melrose's title hopes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224996</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRAIG Joiner has lost time to catch up when he returns to senior club rugby
after injury by playing for Melrose in the top-of-the-table contest with
Stirling County at Bridgehaugh tomorrow. A stress fracture in a foot has kept
the 21-year-old international wing out for more than two months.
He had played only two premier league matches in early September before he was
forced to rest his injured foot, and he returns with only a couple of
championship fixtures left in the Melrose calendar, though none can be more
important than the Bridgehaugh game between the past and current title-holders.
Melrose would be almost guaranteed the SRU Tennents Premiership trophy if they
were to win, whereas Stirling need to complete the double over the Borderers if
they are to retain any prospect of keeping the championship: County won the
clubs' previous encounter, albeit by only 27-26, last month at the Greenyards.
apart from the background to that match, it will be an especially demanding
return for Joiner. His direct opponent will be none other than his
international colleague, Kenny Logan.
Whether or not Melrose go on to win the title, Joiner's target will be to
regain a place in the South XV for the district championship next month as a
stepping stone to returning to  the national team. The Melrose wing has played
in 12 of Scotland's past 14 internationals, missing only the defeat by South
Africa a year ago and, of course, that 15-all draw with Western Samoa last
Saturday.
Rowen Shepherd, Millan Browne, and Derek Lunn, like Joiner, resume for Melrose.
While Joiner is on the way back, two other capped players, Derek Stark and
Derek Turnbull, have been sidelined by injury. Stark has had a wrist operation
after injury while playing for Boroughmuir against Watsonians on Sunday, though
he is hopeful of returning to rugby before the end of the year, and Turnbull
will be out for much longer after a double leg fracture during Hawick's victory
over Edinburgh Academicals the same day.
Ally McLean takes over from Stark on the right wing for Boroughmuir against
Heriot's at Meggetland tomorrow. Stuart Reid also resumes, after his
international debut last Saturday, but Boroughmuir have lost their New Zealand
lock, Darren George, because of injury.
John Graham, who has recovered from an ankle injury, makes a timely return to
the Hawick back row to replace Turnbull for the visit to Netherdale.
q THE Melrose committee were due to meet last night to decide what action to
take over the eye injury sustained by prop Mark Ross during their premiership
clash with Edinburgh Accies. The player was apparently punched and later
underwent surgery to his left eye, which may be permanently damaged.
Academicals issued a statement yesterday in which they said that no formal
complaint had been received from Melrose and that they did not intend to take
any action against any of their players.
q AFTER sharing the two-match series with Ulster last weekend, Glasgow open
their defence of Scottish rugby's under-18 district championship with a visit
to Langholm to play against the South tomorrow (kick-off 2.0).
Ulster beat the Glasgow boys 25-16 at Ardrossan last Friday, but the home team
had an 18-16 win in the rematch at Stranraer on Sunday morning. Glasgow's XV.
S Hutchinson (Cambuslang); A Pollock (Glasgow Southern), S Kidd (Kilmarnock), S
McAllister (Stirling County), R Pittam (Marr); S Weston (Hillhead/Jordanhill),
F Kennedy (Stirling County); L Haycock (Mid-Argyll), A Smith, T McCulloch (both
Stirling County), S Bryce (Dalziel), J Toner (Allan Glen's), A Lees (Ayr,
captain), B Allan (Hamilton Academicals), D Wilson (GHK). Replacments - C Smith
(Ayr), J Millan (GHK), M Dick (Cambuslang), G Sykes (Ayr), J Maclay (GHK), J
Mundell (Cartha Queen's Park), J Crump (Dumfries).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
