<DOCNO>GH951124-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tough test for `A' team</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DEREK DOUGLAS Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224997</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND `A' have fixed up a prestigious fixture against the South African
provincial side, Northern Transvaal, to be played in Pretoria the day before
the Calcutta Cup game at Murrayfield.
The clash with the Blue Bulls on Friday, March 1, is likely to take place in
the Loftus Versfeld Test arena where Scotland played most of their matches
during the World Cup.
The Scottish shadow side now has a solid-looking programme, the defeat by
Western Samoa earlier this month being the first of six outings this season.
They will next be in action against Italy on January 6, a game which takes on
extra significance in view of the disappointing performance by the senior side
against the Samoans last weekend and with the Five Nations' Championship opener
taking place against Ireland a fortnight later.
With the exception of England, games have been arranged at `A' level against
the Five Nations' rivals, and the Northern Transvaal expedition fills in what
would otherwise have been a blank weekend.
Northern Transvaal will provide stern opposition for the Scots. They had five
players in the South African World Cup squad, with scrum half Joost van der
Westhuizen and flanker Ruben Kruger both playing in the RWC final against New
Zealand.
Yesterday, Scotland `A' manager Dougie Morgan said that the original plan had
been for the side to play Northern Transvaal last season but the fixture had
fallen through and Ivory Coast had stepped into the breach as part of their
World Cup warm-up programme.
q DAMIAN Cronin underwent keyhole surgery to a cartilage in his right knee in
Glasgow's Western Infirmary yesterday. The international second row, who has
had operations on the ligaments in both knees in the past, complained about
knee pain during Scotland's 15-all draw with Western Samoa last Saturday.
Cronin, who plays his rugby at No.8 in France, is expected to be released
today, and return to France.
q GARY Armstrong and Doddie Weir met Newcastle rugby director Rob Andrew again
this week for further talks. The Scottish pair have now been issued with draft
contracts and they are being examined by lawyers. All being well, Armstrong and
Weir could make their Newcastle debuts in January.
q EDINBURGH Academicals' spokesman Magnus Moodie said yesterday that the club
had now received the letter from the SRU concerning the ``tantamount to
cheating'' remarks by coach David Sole following the premiership game with
Melrose a fortnight ago. ``Accies have now replied to the union and await their
further comment. I'm not able to divulge the contents of our response,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
