<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saltire Quartet, Queens Hall, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975224998</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH the art of the string quartet is traditionally linked with a mature
and reflective audience, the new young quartet-in-residence at the Queens Hall
believes in extending boundaries.
Thanks to its association with 14 local schools, there were as many children as
adults present on Wednesday for an evening of Haydn, Beethoven, and Ronald
Center.
No music, it's true, is more mature than Haydn's G-major quartet, Op 77, No 1,
a product of the composer's fragile old age. But no music is more vivacious, as
the spruce and springy performance demonstrated.
Only the slow movement, which needed richer harmonic resonance, fell seriously
short of expectations, but no doubt that will be rectified soon, if the
treatment of the slow movement of Beethoven's F minor quartet, Op 95, later in
the programme is anything to go by.
Here the players, catching the elusive tempo to admiration, conveyed the
music's slow-footed sense of mystery, without losing the terseness that is the
special feature of the work as a whole.
Nor was Ronald Center's first quartet, sandwiched between the Haydn and
Beethoven, allowed to dally. Indeed, this grumpy, impatient music, written in
Aberdonian isolation in the 1940s and neglected ever since, seemed to call for
just the abrasive, rhythmically edgy performance it received.
Whether these young players will win the composer the support he never received
in his lifetime remains to be seen, but their forthcoming recording of this
work - a kind of cross between Bartok and early Britten - will surely help.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951124-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951124-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951124</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tail with a happy ending</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975224999</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE have had enough of the sordid sadism and brutality of the West trial and the
complications of the feminists welcoming the ultimate sex symbol to the
sisterhood; the British public needs a reassuring tale with a happy ending.
`Loyal, devoted mistress saves unjustly maligned family pet from death row' is
the perfect animal antidote. Dempsey lives and the law is an ass.
For more than three years Dempsey, a seven-year-old pit bull terrier bitch, has
been under a destruction order for being unmuzzled in a public place in
contravention of the 1991 Dangerous Dogs Act.
It took the High Court to quash the destruction order and allow Dempsey to be
reunited with her owner, Dianne Fanneran, a 47-year-old optician's receptionist
from west London, who displayed distictly terrier-like tenaciousness in her
long fight to save her pet. Dempsey's reprieve appears to have been on a
technicality because it was not Mrs Fanneran herself who removed the muzzle to
allow the dog, who was choking, to be sick.
Other unmuzzled pit bulls have been sentenced to death because there was no
legal alternative. A similar act ``of common sense and compassion'' by a
Maryhill man only hours after the Act came into operation resulted in his dog
being put to death and the owner being fined #250 and having a criminal record,
despite having complied fully with all the other requirements of the Act,
recalls John Robins of Animal Concern. ``If he had not removed the muzzle, the
dog would have choked to death and he would have been prosecuted for cruelty.''
Since the Dangerous Dogs Act came into effect, lobbyists have campaigned
against automatic death sentences for dogs whose owners contravene the law.
Even a sheriff refused to make a destruction order until an Appeal Court
ruling. The Dangerous Dogs Act Reform Group, chaired by past president of the
British Veterinary Association, Paul De Vile, includes the Scottish Society for
the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, the RSPCA, the Canine Defence League and
the League against Cruel Sports. They all support requirements to have ``pit
bull type'' dogs registered, implanted with a microchip detailing their owner,
tatooed and insured for third party liability and muzzled in public.
However, they say dogs with no history of injuring anyone are being put down
unjustly. They would prefer the future of the dog to be decided on an
individual basis by the sheriff or magistrate, and add they are not against
vicious dogs being put to death.
Most of the organisations support a national dog registration scheme which
would require all dogs to be registered and implanted with a microchip - the
canine equivalent of a car registration enabling the owner to be traced.
The legislation has already had an effect on the numbers of pit bull terriers
in the UK.
``The macho image of a powerful head-banging dog on one end of a lead and an
idiot on the other has lost its appeal. You don't see groups of yobs with a
clutch of pit bulls hanging round street corners the way you did in the early
70s,'' says James Barrington, director of the League Against Cruel Sports. In
the 70s, it campaigned against the breed, created entirely for fighting
purposes, being allowed into the UK. Now, because they have to be neutered, the
breed is beginning to die out.
IT was estimated there were 10,000 pit bull terriers in 1991. The Central Index
of Exempted Dogs, run by an animal shelter in Hertfordshire on behalf of the
Home Office, has registered 8600. Since then, 1850 have died or been put down.
Predictions that thousands of owners would have their pets destroyed before the
Act came into force to claim a #50 bounty from the Home Office were unrealised.
Unexpectedly, but alarmingly, in the last couple of years increasing numbers of
owners have had their animals put down because they have suddenly turned from
biddable pet to unpredictable, biting animal, reports Jim Grant, who runs the
register with his wife, Isabel. ``It seems to happen about the age of four. We
don't know why, but there is a theory the brain may begin to press on an
indentation in the skull of these dogs. Too many people have now told me their
dog `turned' within seconds for there not to be some pattern.''
There is also a lobby for a requirement for other breeds to be muzzled. Top of
the list in Scotland are rottweilers, not mentioned in the Act, despite the
death of 11-year-old Kellie Lynch, savaged by two rottweilers while walking
them near Dunoon.
Now the legislation is to be reviewed by an all-party committee of MPs after
claims it has cost taxpayers #40m as dogs have been held in kennels while their
owners appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
