<TEXT>
IT is now almost eight years since Dundee player-manager Jim Duffy was advised
by specialists that he should stop playing football. Yet, on Sunday, the
indomitable defender seems sure to lead his team on to Hampden and into his
first major final as a player.
At 36 years of age, Duffy genuinely believes that now is the time when he can
pick up his first medal, even though his damaged knee has become a standing
joke among the medical profession in Scotland.
Yesterday, as he began the serious preparations for the Coca-Cola Cup final
against Aberdeen on Sunday, Duffy grinned: ``The doctors, the surgeons, the
specialists, they all just laugh at me now. ``If I tell any one of them after a
game that I can't straighten my knee they just shake their heads, laugh, and
walk away.
``I suppose that's because they know that I won't do what they tell me to do,
which is stop playing football.
``They did tell me before, back in 1987, and I did listen and I took their
advice and I continued to do that for two-and-a-half years. I stopped playing
for that length of time and I hated it. I wanted to keep on playing and that's
what I have done ever since.
``Yes, I still feel pain after matches, but the pain is no worse now than it
was eight years ago.
``People say that I'm not as good a player now but, then, even without the
injury I'm not likely to be as good at 36 as I was at 28.
``I don't let it worry me, but I don't make a big deal out of it because there
are a lot of people worse off than I am. After all, all I've got is a sore
knee.''
Now, before the final, Duffy must decide whether or not he picks himself for
what is the biggest match of his career. He is in charge. But he will listen to
others and not make any sentimental decision about his own big day.
Yesterday he pointed out: ``This is a major match for this club, for this team,
and for these players. It is not about me. It is about all of us and I have to
make the right decision for Dundee Football Club.
``There will be no sentiment involved. If I think I am the right player for
this game, then I'll play. If I don't think that, then I will still be there on
the bench, still at Hampden, and still involved because I'm the manager.''
There is a strong belief within Duffy, which appears to have spread to his
squad, that Dundee can follow Raith Rovers' example of last season and produce
a shock result, though Duffy does not talk too much about the Ibrox final when
Celtic lost out.
He says simply: ``That was Raith's day. It was their big occasion and it has no
bearing on this weekend. We have to do it for ourselves.
``If anything the Raith result might work against us, because Aberdeen will be
more on their guard. They won't want to suffer as Celtic did.''
Even allowing for the possibility of caution from the Dons, Duffy reckons, like
so many at Pittodrie, that this will be an open final, a flowing final and
perhaps even a high scoring one. He admits: ``We have midfield players who want
to get forward just as they do. Goals can arrive from different areas. I think
we are better when we're up against a team with the same outlook as ourselves.
This will suit us.
``You know, I don't believe any of our youngsters will freeze on the day
despite their relative inexperience. The older players will worry more than the
young lads.
``Look, when you're a kid and you climb a tree, you get up there to the top and
you don't think anything about it. When you're a little bit older and you do
the same you start to think about what would happen if you fell.
``I would never say before a game like this that we might lose, but I have a
real belief that we can win this one.''
Duffy will decide tomorrow morning whether he will play himself or not.
So far, he has given his players his thoughts about the game and how the team
will be asked to play but the personnel remains secret.
My own belief is that Duffy will be in the team giving on-field guidance to the
young men around him, coaxing and ajoling then towards possible glory.
It's a role made for this man who has simply refused to quit the game he loves.
