<HEADLINE>Storehouse profits soar 42% despite tough trading</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975225001</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN spite of difficult trading conditions, Storehouse, the BhS and Mothercare
retail group, managed to raise its interim profits by 42% to #34.5m before tax.
The results were ahead of City expectations and the shares gained 10p to 332p
after an earlier jump to a high for the year of 337p.
A strong performance at Mothercare, with underlying sales growth of 2%, was
largely responsible for the improved performance although margins also improved
at BhS and costs were held.
The disposal of the discount chain One Up should help margins in the second
half. The disposal led to an extraordinary profit of #1.2m.
The interim dividend is raised by 11% to 3.0p, as part of a rebalancing
exercise between the two halves of the year. For the first time there is a
scrip dividend alternative.
The Mothercare operation has tightened up considerably since last year when
problems of overstocking led to hefty markdowns which in turn had an impact on
margins.
Mothercare's profits rose by over 120% to #9.3m. However, there is thought to
be scope to further improve the returns from the Mothercare business. This
should be aided by the steady roll-out of a new, more child-friendly format
into all the stores over the next two years.
New store openings in the period under review included one on Sauchiehall
Street in Glasgow. Sales fell by 3% on a like-for-like basis at BhS with the
unusually warm October not helping demand for women's wear. The weak housing
market affected lighting sales and children's wear and restaurant sales were
also lower.
On the plus side, lingerie and footwear did well. However, its trading profit
rose by more than 10% to #20.8m helped by lower markdowns.
The store portfolio is gradually being upgraded with refurbishments and new
store openings. During the year, the St Enoch Square BhS was upgraded and a new
store is due to open in Livingston next August.
Overseas, the franchise operations of the two stores are growing strongly. New
sites in Russia, the Philippines and Israel are under negotiation.
Despite the busy corporate development programme with capital expenditure of
#71.7m in the first half, almost matching the total for last year, the group's
financial position remains strong.
At the half year end, there was a net cash position of #56.7m producing
interest income of #3.3m. Although this will drop in the second half it will
still remain positive.
</TEXT>
