<HEADLINE>Swing is coming to town</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975225002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Luka Bloom is a musical whirlpool
at the heart of a Celtic trio.
DAVID BELCHER profiles an
Irishman abroad as he takes
part in his first UK tour
LUKA Bloom answers the phone in his dressing-room back-stage in a theatre in
Torquay with a jovial cry: ``Chinese laundry!'' Bloom: who he? On one level,
he's the late-blossoming younger brother of a long-established performer,
Christy Moore.
A better summary would be provided by the not-too-fanciful observation that
everyone who experienced Luka Bloom's Glasgow Royal Concert Hall show back in
January must have left feeling spiritually cleansed, hot under the collar, and
with their head in a spin. One man, one voice, one guitar: it added up to a
whirlpool of sound and emotion.
That night made a mighty impression on its star, too. ``It was a complete
shock, the reception I got. I've played to big audiences who knew me in Europe
and America, but not Britain.''
When Luka Bloom returns to Scotland next week, accompanied by Celtic
compatriots Sharon Shannon and Eleanor Shanley, he'll still be in the
best-kept-secret category, having just been dropped by his label, Warner
Brothers, after three albums. Over the years, incidentally, the same company
has done exactly the same thing to Emmylou Harris, Ry Cooder, Van Morrison and
Joni Mitchell. Is there a pattern here? Some comment about record company
notions of quality and quantity?
Mind you, it must be stated that none of Luka's trio of albums - Luka Bloom,
The Acoustic Motorbike, and Turf - came close to reflecting the power of his
live shows.
``That's a valid criticism, but one that I don't try to refute because I've
never set out to make records that reflect my gigs.
``I see myself as primarily a live artist who records, not a recording artist
who plays live occasionally.
``I hate live albums...... all whistling and clapping. Maybe I should record a
live half-hour movie with good quality sound. In a favourite club, the Paradiso
in Amsterdam, maybe.''
Luka Bloom has been playing since the Paradiso was in its fragrant heyday in
the seventies. Nevertheless, this UK tour is his first, following single shows
in London, Edinburgh, and Glasgow. He has globetrotted, though, having
initially forsaken his native Kildare for Berlin and more recently California.
The UK's different, you see. In days gone by, it's been less than welcoming. If
you're Irish, come into this immigration strip-search room......
``I was at Harwich, a teenager en route home for Christmas in the year of the
Guildford pub bombings. I was kept for hours, being searched, questioned. The
abuse I got, the downright venom.
``At the time I didn't feel in any danger. I just kept thinking: `This'll be
over soon.' But then as the case of the Guildford Four emerged, I got to
thinking: `That could have been me who got picked on.'
``It affected my desire, or lack of it, to work in Britain. Maybe it's ironic
that now during the Anglo-Irish peace process, here's me making my effort to
get over my own prejudices, my historical baggage.''
Wowing the UK, the Bloom-Shanley-Shannon touring party has been uniting on four
or five songs at the end of every concert.
``There's an Irish feel, but it's not what you'd expect. It's not the standard
jig-and-reel groove.''
But what else would you expect from a fellow who invested LL Cool J's raunchy
rap tune, I Need Love, with a winsome Celtic undertow?
Turn up to press your suit with, and plight your troth to Luka Bloom next week.
n.The Celtic Swing Tour: Aberdeen Music Hall, Tuesday, and Glasgow Royal
Concert Hall, Wednesday.
</TEXT>
