<HEADLINE>HSBC Tessa Plus has modest exposure to the Footsie index</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975225003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOLDERS of Tessas due to mature shortly will soon be bombarded with offers to
switch their funds to other banks and building societies as the accumulated
capital sum of up to #9000 (not the interest) can be transferred to a new Tessa
without penalty.
One of the more intriguing is the HSBC Tessa Plus which gives a modest exposure
to the performance of the FTSE-100 index over its five-year period.
It works by paying a basic 5% fixed over five years with a bonus at the end of
up to 30% if the index rises by at least this proportion. The total return is
potentially 155%, turning #9000 into almost #14,000.
This is equivalent to a return of 9.16% compound and an average yearly return
of 11%, which compares with the best yield of 7.5% currently available on an
ordinary Tessa, though there may be some special offers come the new year.
At its present rate, the stock market will be well into new territory in
January and it is possible that it will not be 30% higher still in five years,
though this is rather unlikely.
If it is not, then the return will be lower than could be obtained from a
conventional Tessa, where the risk is confined to interest rates dropping back
and cutting the return, though there are some fixed-rate Tessas available,
albeit at a lower starting rate.
The alternative for those wanting a protected exposure to the stock market is
guaranteed bonds. They offer a return linked to the smoothed performance of an
index usually the FTSE-100. Some offer not just a capital guarantee but a
minimum return as well as the link to the index.
A variation on this is the index-tracking PEP offered by Legal &amp; General which
for an insurance premium of 4% and an elevated annual charge of 2% gives a
no-loss guarantee after five years.
While the HSBC product is innovative, many investors will not be keen on
muddling fixed interest investment with exposure to the stock market.
</TEXT>
