<HEADLINE>Mail disorder causes a brief problem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975225004</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE postal strike yesterday landed football with a major problem ahead of
Sunday's Coca-Cola Cup final.
The Scottish League last night told supporters heading for Hampden on Sunday -
do not come if you don`t have a ticket in your possession.
Strathclyde Police have stressed that they do not want ticketless fans around
Hampden on Sunday when there will be no tickets on sale. The league, along with
Aberdeen and Dundee, were receiving calls yesterday by anxious fans checking if
their tickets were in the post.
Although Aberdeen have sold 18,000 and Dundee 16,000, it is thought that little
more than 100 supporters are affected, but last night there was no way of
knowing for definite.
However, it was not thought there was any danger of wide open spaces at Hampden.
However, there is the possibility that supporters' clubs who had uplifted
tickets personally may have sent them out to members by post.
League official Jim Kilpatrick said: ``We know some tickets are still in the
post and the message is that if they do not arrive in time, don't come to the
game.
``When the tickets eventually arrive return them to either ourselves or the
clubs when a full refund will be given.
``We regret that this has happened, and we hope that as the final is being
shown live on television, all fans will enjoy watching it.''
</TEXT>
