<HEADLINE>The torment goes on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975225005</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHE'S been gone for almost five years now, her face faded to a police-issue
snapshot, her bright 15-year-old personality reduced to a line in a computer
catalogue of thousands of lost souls.
But for Vicki Hamilton's father, Michael, the pain of her disappearance in
February 1991 is as present as it has ever been and has only been heightened by
fears about Frederick West's Scottish connections.
``He's got relatives up here. No-one ever found out if he was up here in 1991,
in Coatbridge. There's always that aspect of it. I read in the papers today
that they reckon there are 30 bodies under a car park but they don't reckon
they're going to dig it up. If there are 30 bodies lying down there, if Vicki
is one of them, I don't want her lying below a car park.''
The West case is just the latest in a series of ``what ifs'' which have
tormented the Hamilton family. Less than three weeks ago, one of the Falkirk
teenager's relatives overhead a conversation in a local bar which suggested her
body had been found beneath a wall.
Each time they call the authorities, deal with the new uncertainty, and carry
on waiting. ``It's the waiting, just waiting,'' says Hamilton. ``How do you get
through it? You don't really ever get through it. I just stick in at my work
and try to take my mind off it, but at the same time, it's always there. When
I'm on my own it's really bad.''
He had always been optimistic about seeing her again, but at the very back of
his mind he thinks she may be dead. He says he hasn't been contacted by the
police for 10 months and media interest in his missing daughter has tailed off.
``I think everbody just forgot about it,'' he says. ``I know there are a lot of
other girls out there who have gone.''
Officially, there are around 30,000 people reported missing every year, but
unofficial estimates suggest there may be a further 150,000 unreported
`disappeared' on the streets of British towns and cities at any one time. Some
will have been abducted, some will have gone of their own free will, others
will have been escaping abuse, still others launching themselves into what they
imagine will be an adventure.
Tracing them all is a lottery and a nightmarish one at that. The Police
National Missing Persons Bureau at New Scotland Yard was set up last year, but
it deals exclusively with ``vulnerable'' cases who have been missing for more
than 28 days; those under 18, over 65, or the mentally disordered. At the
moment they have 977 cases on their books, 443 under 18.
The bureau's work consists of trying to match information on their files with
the records of bodies which have been found, accidents, and those found
wandering the streets. Details of possible matches are sent out to local police
forces for further investigation.
Strathclyde Police have a total of 105 missing persons cases on their books,
dating back 25 to 30 years. Just yesterday they issued an appeal for a
13-year-old from Alexandria, missing from her home since November 16. Force
spokesman D..S. Ian Graham says they respond to every missing persons report,
using commonsense to judge how potentially serious the situation is.
``There is no specific time delay. If a woman says her husband went to the pub,
said he'd be back at 11pm and it's now 12, we might say OK, let's maybe leave
it. If he's not back at 2am come back to us. If it had been a 13-year-old girl
who had gone to the corner shop and had not come back we would be very
concerned about that, we'd be out searching the streets.''
The official channels, however, still leave thousands of families with
questions unanswered and nowhere to turn. It was to respond to their needs that
the National Missing Persons Bureau charity was created in 1992 by a retired
policeman.
THE charity has 14,000 people on its register and uses a variety of methods to
try and bring people back in contact with one another. It has a strict credo of
respecting everybody's right to disappear and will only put missing people back
in touch with their families if they want to do so.
NMPB spokeswoman Sophie Woodford says their key role is supporting those who
have been left behind.
``The families that are left behind go through something that is fairly
impossible to imagine. It's waiting for news, no idea what the news will be.
Completely left in limbo. One day they can be feeling quite positive and the
next they're really down. It's like a rollercoaster of emotions because they
just don't know what the outcome is going to be. If someone you love is ill you
can visit them in hospital, if someone has died you can grieve for them, if
someone is missing the family feels completely lost.''
But it is the faceless, unreported missing that most concern Scottish
journalist and author Andrew O'Hagan. People like many of Fred and Rosemary
West's victims who have cut the links, left home and have no-one looking for
them.
O'Hagan, who wrote the critically acclaimed book, Missing, said the number of
``unmissed'' is thought to reach 150,000 at any given time.
``There are a lot of young people within these parameters whose circumstances
bear enormous similarities to those of the girls who went missing in the West
case,'' he says. ``A lot of them will be similar to these new nine names. Quite
a number of these people will be Scottish.''
The Salvation Army, which runs a family tracing service, blames the increase in
the number of missing people on the fragmentation of society. O'Hagan says we
need to take a closer look at ourselves before we will find a solution to the
problem.
``It raises questions about community and society, and these are the questions
that need to be addressed. We need to be thinking about individuals. I think
there is a general failure of empathy. We don't quite notice people. The way it
happened in the West case, these girls, more than half of them had never been
reported as missing.
``The first reponsibility is for people themselves to take note of how people
live their lives and how they move. I think this is all part of a quite
obnoxious individualsim we have had over the past 16 years. We think only of
our own front doors.''
During his research for the book, O'Hagan spent time with the families of those
who had gone missing and found it a humbling experience.
``It is difficult to think of a situation that is worse. It's the agony of not
knowing, they never move on, there's just this great central agony.''
For Michael Hamilton, it is of little comfort that other families are enduring
the same agony. It is not an experience he would wish on anybody.
``They must be going through hell,'' he says. ``Where is she? What's she doing?
All the questions you ask.''
</TEXT>
