n.CUSTOMERS whose credit card payments are stuck in the post because of the
strike are being promised a sympathetic ear by the banks. Which is more than
they're likely to get from Royal Mail.
Asked if they would pay compensation to anyone incurring interest charges for
failing to deliver cheques on time, a spokesman told Check-Out: ``They'll have
to pursue the postal workers union, not us.''
The Royal Bank of Scotland is among those who will take the exceptional
circumstances into account. People awaiting statements are advised to phone
their credit card company or use ATMs to find out what they owe. Giro payments
can then be made at banks or transfers authorised by phone.
Meantime, Edinburgh Scouts are launching a city-wide Christmas delivery service
on Monday for just 15p a card. They expect their postbag to top half a million.
For details of collection points phone 0131 229 3756.
n.DO your bit for the environment by opting for a real Christmas tree next
month: it's estimated that the millions grown in Britain rid the atmosphere of
50,000 tons of harmful carbon dioxide each year.
Making artificial trees depletes energy resources and they produce toxic gasses
when burnt on rubbish tips.
According to producers, while the hot, dry summer has taken its toll, top
quality six to seven foot Scots pines are available for between #10 and #15.
Recommended suppliers in Scotland include Buccleuch Estates in Dumfriesshire
(01848 6283 and 01387 380202); Forest Enterprise, Peebles (01721 720448); Alan
MacVicar, Melrose (01896 822141); RTS, Crieff (01764 652858) and Christie
Elite, Forres (0800 626 070).
For a leaflet about watering and other advice for keeping trees in tip-top
condition until Twelfth Night, send an sae to British Christmas Tree Growers
Assocation, 12 Lauriston Road, London SW19 4TQ.
n.IF critics who blame Princess Diana's problems on emotional stress and
bulimia nervosa are right, she might benefit from extra Vitamin B12.
The Princess's eating disorders are likely to have depleted her reserves of
this vital, but little understood, vitamin which, American researchers now
claim, can cure depression and insomnia. B12 deficiency can also be
misdiagnosed as psychiatric disorders, they say.
As the richest sources of B12 are liver, kidneys and shellfish, vegans and
vegetarians are particularly vulnerable and should take health store
supplements.
