<HEADLINE>Trust badly hit by Mexico crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Powell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975225007</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By ROBERT POWELL
MURRAY Johnstone's Emerging Economies Trust was hard hit by the effect of the
Mexican financial crisis in its first year.
But the #45.5m trust, launched in September 1994, was lucky not to be fully
invested when the Mexican crisis struck three months later and this helped
limit the damage.
The trust has a quarter of its assets invested in Latin America.
Net asset value fell 12.4% to 83.63p during the 57 weeks to October 31, whereas
the trust's benchmark, the International Finance Corporation Investible Index,
fell 21.2% in sterling terms over the same period.
The trust dipped into revenue of #1.7m to pay out a final dividend of 1.0p per
share.
Murray Johnstone, which manages the trust from Glasgow, said the immediate
prospects for recovery in emerging markets were not bright since the recent
pick-up in the United States and Japan had diverted capital away from them.
It noted that the trust's board had approved #5m of long-term borrowing.
Meanwhile, broker Exco yesterday warned that taxable profits in 1995 would be
significantly lower than City expectations.
When it published its interims in the summer, the company said that the second
half of the year was traditionally quieter.
The group said it believed turnover would be down by 13% in the 12-month
period, a similar drop to the first six months.
A major cost-cutting and restructuring programme is already in place which
should reduce operating costs by #15m annually. An unchanged total dividend
payout of 9p per share is expected.
</TEXT>
