<HEADLINE>Fiction becoming fact in the great railways fiasco</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975225008</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WENT to Wembley yesterday - not, disappointingly, to see a ball being kicked,
but to visit the massive Railtex exhibition at the adjacent conference centre.
This is where the railway manufacturing industries show their wares.
There are a lot of them, with tens of thousands of jobs at stake. Britain is
still up there with the world leaders in terms of the equipment which goes into
trains. But, as in so many other areas of serious manufacturing before it, the
pace of decline is now precipitous.
This is not because nobody wants what our companies make. On the contrary, the
export market is booming. But an industry of this kind also needs a home market
and that is what is now in a state of extended hiatus. Last year alone, 5000
jobs were lost in railway manufacturing.
Indeed, probably the greatest irony within the whole rail privatisation fiasco
lies in the fact that it is the existing private sector which is bleeding
hardest and fastest, because so little investment is now going into the
railways.
And the passenger is beginning to notice in a big way. Within the past week, we
have had the public shouting match between Railtrack and ScotRail; the latter
blaming the former for delays on the Glasgow-Edinburgh route through lack of
maintenance and investment.
Up north, passengers between Inverness and Kyle were collected by bus - not, as
would be understandable, because of workings on the line, but because there
were no trains available in working order!
This all fits in rather grimly with the revelation earlier this week that
Railtrack has salted #1.14billion in a single year as a nest-featherer for
privatisation. This is money paid to them by the train operators and which
should be going into investment and maintenance.
It takes a very expert reading of the accounts to appreciate that this is not
in fact happening. But it is a case in which the people at the sharp end -
standing on station platforms around the country - could certainly have tipped
off the accountants about the consequences, if not the mechanisms being used.
The question of who would invest in the railways has all along been at the
heart of the case against privatisation. Last week it was brought into sharp
relief by the comments of James Sherwood, president of Sea Containers, who
envisages only a ``deteriorating railway'' and does not want to be part of it.
He has pulled his company out of bidding for franchises.
Meanwhile both Railtrack and the unregulated rolling-stock leasing companies
are guaranteed their revenue streams without having to make any commitment to
investment programmes. It is a formula which threatens precisely the
deterioration which Sherwood predicts.
Taken in conjunction with the other eccentricities of rail privatisation, the
investment factor justifies Labour's determination to halt - and if necessary
to reverse - the process of fragmentation and privatisation.
Last night the whole process descended even deeper into farce, with my
revelation that the managing director of Resurgence Railways - who have been
selected to run the railway of Brunel, the historic Great Western - was
previously the managing director of a double-glazing firm, which went into
liquidation earlier this year!
This tends to confirm that the Tories are now in such a state of desperation
and ideological over-commitment to rail privatisation that they are prepared to
give the franchises away, almost literally to anyone who will take them.
I remember, during the Committee stages of the Railway Bill, inventing a
fictional private train operator called ``Spivrail''. The Tories went
apoplectic about this slight upon the glories of private enterprise. Gradually,
my fiction is looking increasingly like fact.
Nobody should be in any doubt about Labour's commitment to a publicly owned and
accountable national rail network. However, the obvious first step towards
achieving this end is to miminise the extent of privatisation before a General
Election.
This is where the role of investors is crucial and I will continue to spell out
to them the risks inherent in touching the Tory scheme with a barge-pole. We
have overwhelming public opinion on our side, while comparisons with previous
sell-offs are irrelevant, since this is the only one which would continue to be
dependent upon taxpayers' subsidy for its profitability.
There is then no paradox in stating that Labour is eager and enthusiastic about
the prospect of harnessing private investment for the railway industry. There
are many ways of doing this without breaking up the national network.
If we can add to it through partnership schemes, then well and good.
But as for handing over railway operations to Spivrail or its close cousins, or
leaving Railtrack to cream off vast profits from taxpayers' money while the
network is starved of investment? Forget it. And the more strongly electoral
opinion expresses itself against this nonsense, the better the chance of
defeating it.
