<HEADLINE>Taxing times for those who cross the line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975225009</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IMAGINE a one-off tax bill from the Revenue for #1638m. That's almost enough to
knock a penny off the standard rate for every income tax payer in the land. It
represents eight per cent of the entire Exchequer take from UK corporation tax
in 1994/95, according to the last Red Book forecast.
We are not talking here about the wild dream of some would-be Chancellor. That
demand was paid by one as-yet-unidentified company, in the 1994/95 tax year, as
a result of Revenue non-compliance investigations which, in total, pulled in an
additional #4047m taxes. With characteristic understatement, our man in the
bowler hat called that one payment ``unusually large''.
The Revenue tucked the news away in one paragraph of its last annual report.
There has been plenty of speculation about who the hapless victim may have
been. Pharmaceuticals firm Glaxo, since merged with Wellcome, has denied it was
the one to cough up. It was suspected bacause it is engaged in a major legal
tussle with the tax inspectors on an issue which, almost certainly, lies at the
root of that mega back-dated tax bill.
They call it transfer pricing. It's all about precisely where, in the complex
chain from production through to final sales, multinationals account for
profits and pay tax on them. When you are operating across national boundaries,
it makes sense to maximise profits in low tax regimes and minimise them in
higher tax regimes.
So, for example, a multinational subsidiary making or assembling goods in one
country, where corporate taxes are relatively high, will sell the products on
to a sales and distribution subsidiary in a country where corporate taxes are
lower, at little more than cost of production. The distribution company racks
up the real profits, and pays the lower rate of tax on them.
UK ministers like to boast that, at 33%, our standard corporation tax rate is
among the lowest in the developed world. Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
made the point again on Monday, at the Scottish Financial Enterprise annual
dinner, whilst urging the Scottish business community to oppose any
constitutional change which brings with it what he has dubbed Labour's
additional tartan tax.
However, even within the European Union with its pretence of a single market
and a level playing field, there are member countries which dramatically
undercut that UK rate, in special circumstances. It's well known Ireland offers
inward investors a 10% corporation tax rate until 2010. It's much less well
known Holland, in its bid to become the main distribution hub for Europe,
offers an effective rate of 3.5% for multinationals siting warehousing and
sales operations around ports like Rotterdam.
As a result, American companies assembling personal computers in Scotland for
sale throughout Europe have a financial incentive to set up their main European
sales and marketing arm in Holland.
Needless to say, UK Inland Revenue inspectors are suspicious of such
multinational transfer pricing arrangements, which minimise both margins and
the resultant tax take here. If they can pick legal holes in these
arrangements, they pounce and slap on an additional tax demand, back-dated over
six years. That, almost certainly, is the fate which befell the nameless
company which coughed up #1638m.
According to a recent survey of 210 multinationals by accountants Ernst &amp;
Young, 49% were being investigated by the Revenue on their transfer pricing
arrangements. An astonishing 83% had been involved in a transfer pricing
dispute with the British tax authorities at some time in the past.
When I raised the issue with Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch he neatly
side-stepped it, saying: ``Where the profit element is accounted for is not
necessarily the main benefit from inward investment. The main benefit is that
we are providing employment and therefore bringing wealth creation to this
country.
``The spin-off effect of all the supply potential and the ability of the people
working for that company to spend are just as important as corporation tax at
the other end.''
That is one view. But, when the front-end cost to the Government, in grants and
other assistance, of luring inward investors here can be as much as #25,000 a
job, the back-end loss of corporation tax revenue on the scale indicated by
that single billion-and-a-half pay-back raises large, but almost entirely
unventilated, questions.
That one company paid the equivalent of more than three times the maximum
annual take from what Mr Forsyth has dubbed the Scottish parliament's tartan
tax. Under the Convention plans, the Edinburgh assembly will have no power to
tax business. Despite that, Mr Forsyth insists the tartan tax will scare inward
investors away from Scotland.
I would have thought the Inland Revenue's determination to get tough on
multinational transfer pricing - a determination likely to be underpinned by
clearer rules in the forthcoming Finance Bill - poses a more direct threat to
inward investors contemplating opening manufacturing plants in Britain than any
tartan tax. It will, after all, hit hard their own pockets.
Other countries, like the US, Australia and Germany, are tightening up on how
multinationals account for profits. With the Inland Revenue here determined to
do the same, it is critical fresh pressure is put on Brussels to outlaw
sweetheart tax deals of the sort developed in Dublin and The Hague. Only then
can we develop a more level fiscal playing field in the EU, as far as
multinationals are concerned.
The danger is that ministers, more concerned with the jobs inward investors
bring than any contribution they make to national tax revenues, will sanction
private understandings with key inward investors as to where their profits will
be declared and taxed. If the Revenue is to get tough, it should get tough with
everyone.
